<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Carver 2ndLd-Writethru a0854 08-02 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Carver, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0854,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author, Poet Raymond Carver Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to move up time element and UPDATE with
quotes. Picks up 3rd graf pvs. CORRECTS by deleting erroneous
mention of ``We Are Not In This Together'' in 7th graf pvs ``His
other...' Trims to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORT ANGELES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author and poet Raymond Carver,
acclaimed for his short stories about the difficulties of love and
financial problems in the lives of ordinary people, died at his
home here Tuesday of cancer at age 50.
   ``He died very nobly,'' said his brother-in-law Douglas Unger, a
creative writing professor at Syracuse University. ``He didn't let
on how bad his condition was.''
   Unger called Carver ``the greatest short story writer in North
America. He was the great innovator of the short story.''
   His most recent short story collection, titled ``Where I'm
Calling From,'' was published earlier this year by Atlantic Monthly
Press, and about the same time, he was named to the American
Academy and Institute of Arts and Letters in a ceremony in New York.
   His first collection of stories, ``Will You Please Be Quiet,
Please?,'' was published in 1976 and was nominated in 1977 for a
National Book Award. Critics praised the power and economy of the
writing.
   In January 1983, Carver became the one of the first recipients
of the Mildred and Harold Strauss Livings Award, a renewable,
tax-free stipend given by the American Academy amd Institute of
Arts and Letters that provides $35,000 a year for five years.
   Carver's other awards include a Wallace Stegner fellowship in
1972, a National Endowment for the Arts fellowship in 1971, a
Guggenheim Foundation fellowship in 1979 and a 1987 Governor's
Writers Award from Washington Gov. Booth Gardner. His works won O.
Henry awards in 1974, 1975 and 1980.
   His other published books include ``What We Talk About When We
Talk About Love'' (1981), ``Cathedral'' (1983) and ``Fires''
(1983). A book of his poetry, ``Ultramarine,'' was published in
1986.
   Carver was born in Clatskanie, Ore., and grew up in Yakima,
Wash, where his father was a saw-filer in a lumber mill and his
mother occasionally worked as a waitress or retail clerk.
   Carver studed writing through a correspondence course while
still in high school. After graduating from high school in 1956 he
worked for six months at a sawmill in Chester, Calif., and in 1957
married Maryann Burk. They later divorced.
   Carver moved in 1958 to California and took an introductionary
fiction-writing course from the late author John Gardner. He
transferred to Humboldt State, and his work began to be published
during his undergraduate years.
   He graduated from Humboldt in 1963 and attended the University
of Iowa from 1963 to 1964.
   Later in the 1960s he worked for three years as a night janitor
at a Sacramento hospital and wrote during the day.
   Carver once said he did not believe fiction had to bring about
personal, moral or social change.
   ``It just has to be there for the fierce pleasure we take in
doing it, and the different kind of pleasure that's taken in
reading something that's durable and made to last, as well as
beautiful in and of itself,'' he said. ``Something that throws off
these sparks _ a persistent and steady glow, however dim.''
   Carver taught writing at various schools and was a professor of
English at Syracuse University in Syracuse, N.Y., for three years
until 1983, and his wife, the poet and short story writer Tess
Gallagher, continued to teach there.
   Carver and Ms. Gallagher made their home in this small city on
the northern Olympic Penninsula from December through August each
year.
   Survivors in addition to Ms. Gallagher were his mother, Ella
Carver; a son, Vance Carver of Germany; a daughter, Christine
Carver of Bellingham; three grandchildren; and a brother, James
Carver.
   A graveside service is scheduled here for Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
