<1ST_LINE>u p AM-MichiganPrimary 2ndLd-Writethru a0403 08-02 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Michigan Primary, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0403,0368</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Gambling ban approved, later figures</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit voters turned thumbs-down on
casino gambling Tuesday, while Republicans statewide chose former
congressma Jim Dunn to challenge Democratic Sen. Donald Riegle.
   Dunn and Robert Huber, both millionaires, spent about $200,000
each trying to attract support for an underdog race against Riegle,
a popular liberal who had no primary opposition in his bid for a
third term
   With 31 percent of the precincts reporting, Dunn had 80,577
votes or 62 percent to Huber's 48,744 votes or 38 percent.
   The referendum on casino gambling was put on the ballot by
opponents of the plan championed by Mayor Coleman Young. He
believes casinos can bring desperately needed money into the city
and help lower its 9.6 percent unemployment rate.
   With 21 percent of precincts reporting, a measure to ban
gambling was winning by 14,050 votes or 64 percent to 7,793 votes
or 36 percent.
   Detroit also had a lively congressional primary. Four-term Rep.
George Crockett was challenged by City Council member Barbara-Rose
Collins and two lesser-known Democratic hopefuls. He was the only
U.S. House incumbent with primary opposition.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Young's opponents included many of the ministers and church
members who in the past have formed the core of his constituency.
   A Saturday rally turned into a public shouting match between
pro-casino and anti-casino forces, and all over the city preachers
used their pulpits to make one last anti-casino pitch on Sunday.
   Casinos have already been rejected twice by voters, and it would
require action by the Legislature to legalize gambling anywhere in
Michigan.
   Huber, who was in Congress for the 1973-74 term, and Jim Dunn,
who served in the 1981-82 term, both criticized Riegle as too
liberal for the state.
   Dunn devoted most of his energy to mending fences with the party
leaders he publicly criticized during his unsuccessful 1984 Senate
primary race.
   Huber, the more conservative of the two, emphasized his
opposition to abortion as he spent the bulk of his time trying to
endear himself to the partisans brought into the party by Pat
Robertson's presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
