<1ST_LINE>r i PM-WestBank-Chronology     08-02 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-West Bank-Chronology,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Dates in History of West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key events in the history of the West
Bank of the Jordan River, occupied by Israel since 1967:
   1918 _ British Gen. Edmund Allenby defeats Turkish forces in a
battle south of the West Bank city of Nablus.
   1923 _ The League of Nations gives Britain the mandate over
Palestine, an area that includes the East Bank of the Jordan River.
Palestinian leaders protest the decision and demand independence.
Later that year, Britain effectively partitions Palestine, handing
over the East Bank to Emir Abdullah.
   1946 _ The East Bank becomes the Hashemite Kingdom of
Transjordan.
   1947 _ The United Nations votes to end the British mandate and
partitions Palestine. Immediately after the decision, fighting
erupts between Palestinians and Jews. Jewish fighters establish
themselves in most areas accorded them in the partition plan.
   1948 _ After Israel declares independence in May, Arab armies
cross the border and attack Israeli forces. The Arab Legion wins
control over most lands accorded to the Palestinians in the U.N.
partition plan.
   1950 _ Jordan annexes the West Bank.
   1967 _ The Israeli army captures Arab east Jerusalem and the
West Bank from Jordan. Israel initiates an open-bridge policy
allowing West Bank Palestinians to maintain close ties with Jordan.
   1974 _ Arab leaders attending a summit in Rabat determine that
the Palestine Liberation Organization is the sole legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people, formally divesting Jordan
of this role.
   1987 _ In December, Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
launch a popular uprising against the Israeli occupation and demand
an independent state.
   1988 _ Arab leaders reaffirm the Rabat agreement. On July 31,
King Hussein announces that Jordan will cut legal and
administrative ties with the West Bank. As a first step, he cancels
a $1.3 billion development plan for the West Bank and dissolves the
lower house of Parliament, consisting of 50 percent of legislators
from the occupied lands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
