<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Bombings     08-02 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Bombings,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than a Dozen Bombings This Year Blamed on IRA</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are the major attacks this year in
Northern Ireland, England and Europe blamed on guerrillas of the
Irish Republican Army:
   Jan. 26 _ A policeman killed in Belfast by an armor-piercing
grenade that struck his armored patrol vehicle.
   Feb. 29 _ Two Ulster Defense Regiment privates killed by a
remote-controlled bomb as they locked steel anti-terrorist doors on
Royal Avenue in Belfast's main shopping area.
   March 19 _ Two British soldiers dragged from their car by
mourners at an IRA funeral, then beaten unconscious with crowbars
and shot to death.
   May 1 _ Three British airmen based in West Germany killed and
three wounded in two attacks in the Netherlands _ a car bombing at
Nieuw Bergen and a machine-gun attack on a car near Roermond.
   May 5 _ A bomb attached to a British serviceman's car in
Bielefeld, West Germany, failed to explode.
   May 21 _ A British soldier and his dog killed by a bomb blast
while searching for explosives near the Irish border.
   May 29 _ A mortar attack on a military base at Cookstown in
County Tyrone injured 14 soldiers and civilians, none seriously.
   June 15 _ A booby-trap bomb blasts a military vehicle in
Lisburn, 7 miles southwest of Belfast, killing six British soldiers
who had just competed in a charity race with about 4,000 other
people.
   June 23 _ A British army helicopter made an emergency landing in
South Armagh near the Irish border after what the IRA said was its
first attack using anti-aircraft guns.
   June 28 _ A bomb exploded in a school bus carrying 12 girls near
Enniskillen, seriously injuring one girl and the driver who was a
part-time member of the Ulster Defense Regiment.
   July 7 _ Two civilians killed and 10 wounded at a swimming pool
in west Belfast by a bomb the IRA said was triggered accidentally.
   July 13 _ Guerrillas cut through a fence at a British army base
at Duisberg, West Germany, to plant two bombs that slightly injured
nine soldiers.
   July 23 _ A car bomb on the main Dublin-Belfast highway killed
contractor Robin Hanna, his wife Maureen and 6-year-old son David
as they were returning from a vacation in the United States. The
IRA said the bomb was meant for a Northern Ireland High Court judge.
   Aug. 1 _ One soldier killed and nine wounded by a bomb at the
Inglis Barracks in north London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
