<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PoliticalNoise Bjt   08-02 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Noise, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Proxmire Protests Political Noise Pollution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noise. Screeching, yelling, bellowing,
desk-pounding noise.
   Noise, Sen. William Proxmire says, is invading political
discourse.
   Its inspiration: Well, perhaps it may be the influence of a
quarter-century of ear-blasting rock music upon the nation's young.
   ``Has the age of rock and roll so corrupted our generation with
noise that only the loudest shouters can win?'' Proxmire asked the
Senate on Monday.
   Or perhaps, the Wisconsin Democrat said, one can blame
television talk shows which elevate rudeness to a fine art and
operate under the rule of ``never start talking unless you are
butting in on another speaker.''
   ``If two speakers interrupt a third speaker simultaneously, and
all three keep taking, then you have the supreme thrill,'' Proxmire
said. ``Wth three people taking at once, it's impossible to hear a
coherent word, let alone a coherent sentence.''
   ``More and more people are catching on to this rock-and-roll
oratory,'' Proxmire told the Senate. ``They are finding it's a real
winner. Content is nothing. It doesn't matter whether the speaker
is logical or ridiculous.
   ``What matters is the loudness _ the decibels,'' Proxmire said,
his own voice rising to a shout.
   ``Does the speaker really get your attention?'' he bellowed to
the several senators on the floor at the time, and the galleries,
mostly filled with tourists from around the nation.
   ``Does he slam his fist on the table?'' the senator exclaimed,
slamming his own fist on his Senate desk.
   ``Does he stamp and shout?'' asked the senator, doing both at
the same time.
   ``Does his voice range from a roar to a screech and back to a
roar?'' he asked, roaring with the best of them.
   ``Does he flail the air with his fists?,'' he shouted, flailing
at the empty air next as if it were a punching bag.
   ``Does he slap his hands together and keep shouting?''
   He waved his arms above his head, slapped his hands together and
shouted: ``If he does all of these things, the press will call him
charismatic and more and more people will come to see him and hear
his noise.''
   These roaring thoughts on political noise and loudness were
ignited, Proxmire said, by a recent column on the subject by
Russell Baker of The New York Times, who said: ``Anybody who acts
as though noise were an argument instead of an assault is too far
behind the times to be rescued.''
   There are shouters in the Senate also.
   But Proxmire said the place is more often bound by ``slow and
sleepy'' oratorical tradition, conducted according to a gentlemanly
code in which speakers speak of each other as ``the distinguished''
and ``the honorable.''
   The future, however, may belong to ``the red hot shouters,''
Proxmire lamented.
   ``Whenever hot emotion and cold reasoning clash, hot emotion
wins every time.''
   ``I can just imagine this place 20 or 30 years from now _ let's
say in 2010,'' Proxmire said.
   ``The Senate chaplain will deliver a rock-and-roll, crowd
pleasing, shouting, morning prayer.
   ``The majority and minority leaders _ lacking the quiet dignity
of our present leaders _ will set the pace with a drum beat of
table pounding, shrill, rousing rhetoric.
   ``Result: This body will move from an ignored TV channel to big
time on TV ... the bawling, baying, bellowing, clamor and commotion
of the United States Senate will be on the air.''
   Having shouted his hope that the decibel level of political and
congressional oratory will be reduced, Proxmire lowered his voice
and ended his speech _ quietly.
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., sought recognition and made clear
Proxmire's point had struck home.
   ``After the distinguished senator from Wisconsin's oration,'' he
said, ``I may deliver my speech in just a little above a whisper.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
