<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     08-02 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third World Debt Crisis Strikes Blow at U.S. Agriculture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debt crisis that has engulfed many
developing countries is striking a blow at U.S. agriculture,
shrinking the available supply of credit to purchase American
commodities.
   ``High interest rates, declining commodity prices and currency
devaluations in the 1980s have thrust much of the burden of the
world's economic problems on heavily indebted developing
countries,'' says an issue paper produced recently by USDA's
Economic Research Service.
   Between 1975 and 1987, the total debt of all non-industrial
countries rose from $234 billion to about $1.2 trillion, according
to the authors, Mathew Shane and David Stallings. It noted a jump
in debt service payments in the early 1980s from about 12 percent
of total exports to 25 percent.
   Latin American debt service payments have climbed from 20
percent to 40 percent, the paper said.
   To compound matters, commercial banks have withdrawn credit and
the indebted nations have forced a reduction in imports while
attempting to spur exports.
   These moves to limit imports represent a serious problem for
U.S. farmers, because the developing world represents the fastest
growing market for agricultural exports.
   Imports of American farm products leveled off six years ago and
there has been little change since, a marked contrast to the 1970s
when the developing world's share of U.S. exports ballooned from 25
percent to more than 40 percent.
   The United States has battled to maintain market share with
federal programs to stimulate exports. The issue paper describes as
especially effective programs that guarantee credit to overseas
customers. It also points to food aid programs as particularly
helpful.
   ``Nearly 50 percent of all U.S. agricultural exports to the
problem borrowers were shipped under federal export programs in
1983 and remained above 40 percent through 1986,'' the paper said.
Among countries that represent major markets for the United States,
about 30 percent of all U.S. farm goods imported received
government support.
   The figure for Latin America is 40 percent, according to the
paper, while less than 15 percent of those to Hong Kong, South
Korea and Taiwan have been financed through such programs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department may reinstate
Mexico's eligibility to send beef, mutton, pork and goat products
to the United States.
   Mexico was dropped from eligibility in February 1984 because it
failed to meet provisions of the Federal Meat Inspection Act. In
specific, USDA said it lacked satisfactory testing for chemical
residues contained in the meat and species verification programs.
   ``A review team from USDA's Food Safety and Inspection Service
has visited Mexico's residue-testing laboratory and several of its
meat plants and FSIS is assured that Mexico's inspection program
now meets U.S. standards,'' said Lester M. Crawford, FSIS
administrator.
   The United States probably will receive no more than 2.5 million
pounds of meat a year from Mexico, or about 0.03 percent of
domestic production.
   As a result, reinstating Mexico as a supplier will have no
effect on either the American industry or consumer prices, USDA
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plants that have been modified genetically and
their possible effects on agriculture, health and the environment
are the focus of a federal conference set for Sept. 7-9 in
Annapolis, Md.
   Development and use of genetically modified plants for food and
other commercial purposes will be a major part of the conference,
sponsored jointly by the Environmental Protection Agency and the
Departments of Agriculture and Health and Human Services.
   The sponsors have invited government officials and academic
experts as well as representatives from industry and consumer
groups and environmentalists. There will be presentations by
authorities in the development of so-called transgenic plants.
   The Agriculture Department said in a statement that a small
amount of data already is available from field tests of the ability
of transgenic plants to resist pests and tolerate pesticides. The
plants also are being studied by researchers seeking ways to
upgrade nutritional characteristics, USDA said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirSafety     08-02 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Safety,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Statistics Show 1988 Improvement in Aircraft Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A frequent critic of federal air traffic
control efforts says a new government report showing a reduction in
near accidents is good news, but he says the system remains under
severe pressure.
   ``We're all happy to see it, but by no means are we ready to
celebrate,'' Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., chairman of the
Senate's transportation appropriations subcommittee, said Monday
after the Federal Aviation Administration released its figures.
   The FAA said there were 518 operational errors by air traffic
controllers during the first six months of this year, an 18 percent
drop from the 635 recorded in the first half of 1987.
   The 366 aerial near-collisions reported by pilots from January
through June this year was a 27 percent decline from the 500
reported during the same period in 1987.
   In addition, there were 60 reports of aircraft or ground
vehicles entering active runways without permission during the
first three months of 1988, 27 percent fewer than the 82 tallied in
the first quarter of 1987.
   ``These numbers, combined with the generally downward movement
in aircraft accident rates in the first half of 1988, indicate a
continued pattern of improvement in aviation safety,'' FAA
Administrator Allan McArtor said in a statement.
   But Lautenberg said the figures showed ``encouraging numbers,
not satisfactory numbers.''
   He said a military plane he was in last Friday flying to
Teterboro Airport in New Jersey had to veer off course to avoid
colliding with another aircraft that his pilot later told him had
been only 200 feet away.
   ``The system is under strain,'' he said.
   The frequency of operational errors, in which the required
spacing between aircraft in flight is violated, has been declining
since the middle of last year.
   But the number of aerial near-collisions has begun declining for
the first time in about five years, FAA spokesman John Leyden said.
The agency defines a near-collision as an incident in which two
aircraft come within 500 feet of each other in flight, or when
flight crews believe a hazard of a collision existed.
   Public concern about safety in the skies peaked last year.
Complaints from passengers surged, airliners crashed at the Detroit
and Denver airports and a helicopter carrying President Reagan
averted a collision with a small plane near his California ranch.
   The government, often under prodding from Congress, has taken
steps such as hiring additional air traffic controllers, changing
flight procedures around the country's largest airports and
requiring expanded use of devices that report an aircraft's
altitude.
   ``I think we can take some credit for this record of
improvement,'' McArtor said.
   Of the aerial near-collisions, 165 of the incidents involved at
least one airliner or smaller passenger plane, down from the 223
reported in the first half of 1987.
   The FAA does not yet have statistics available for the second
quarter of 1988 for incidents in which vehicles enter runways
without permission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Truckers'Licenses     08-02 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Truckers' Licenses,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trucking Industry Chief Wants Tighter Bars to Multiple Licenses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Associations in 2nd graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government should fingerprint truck and
bus operators or use even more sophisticated identification methods
to prevent the drivers from getting licenses from more than one
state, a trucking industry leader says.
   The president of the American Trucking Associations, Thomas J.
Donohue, criticized the Federal Highway Administration on Monday
for enacting regulations that require only that drivers' Social
Security numbers and physical descriptions be recorded.
   He said he was asking Congress to pass legislation that would
require the government to compile stricter identification
information, such as fingerprints or retinal images. Under that
technique, distinctive images are made electronically of a person's
eyes.
   ``It is irresponsible to do anything less than demand new
technology to solve our problem,'' Donohue said at a news
conference.
   Some truck and bus drivers avoid losing their licenses after
various safety convictions, such as for drug and alcohol abuse, by
obtaining licenses from several states. If they lose one, they
still have others.
   The Federal Highway Administration estimates there are 3 million
to 5 million truck and bus drivers in the country.
   A 1986 law now being phased in requires that truck and bus
drivers obtain special commercial licenses. It also makes it
illegal for a truck or bus driver to have a license from more than
one state. Donohue estimated that there are 900,000 bus and truck
operators with more than one license.
   Donohue said the Federal Highway Administration rules, issued
July 15, have ``a major flaw'' because it is easy to obtain several
licenses illegally.
   ``We all know you can go into any state in the union this
afternoon and get as many Social Security numbers as you want,'' he
said.
   Donohue, whose organization is the largest of the trucking
industry's trade groups, said fingerprinting or retinal imaging
would cost about $10 million to institute. The cost could be borne
by fees paid for truck and bus driver's licenses, he said.
   ``An investment of $10 million or $15 million in a system that
would keep the few really bad drivers off the road would seem to us
to be a reasonable thing to do,'' Donohue said.
   A Federal Highway Administration official said the agency
believes its current identification system is effective, and that
more advanced techniques may be in place by the 1990s.
   Richard Landis, associate administrator for motor carriers, said
the agency will be studying sophisticated identification methods
over the next two years and could propose new rules by 1990.
   Donohue said he is asking lawmakers to incorporate his proposal
into truck safety legislation the House Public Works Committee will
consider this month. Under his plan, states would have to select a
sophisticated identification technique by December 1989 and begin
using the process by October 1993.
   Donohue said his proposal was supported by 13 other highway user
and safety groups, including the National Safety Council. In
addition, Chairman Jim Burnett of the National Transportation
Safety Board, the federal agency that investigates accidents, has
expressed support for the idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Ozone     08-02 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ozone,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Fears Companies May Prolong CFC Production Due to Windfall
Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The possibility of reaping $7 billion in
windfall profits may lead chemical companies to prolong production
of compounds that destroy the Earth's protective ozone shield, the
Environmental Protection Agency fears.
   To encourage those producers to find substitutes for
ozone-destroying chlorofluorocarbon chemicals, the agency wants to
charge fees equal to the windfall earnings the manufacturers could
get as prices go up in the face of shortages of CFC compounds.
   An international treaty calls for a 50 percent reduction in CFC
production by 1998, and under EPA's expectations, the CFC shortages
will enable producers to raise prices with no increase in
production costs. The agency estimated the possible windfall at
$1.8 billion to $7.2 billion. The quicker substitutes are adopted,
the less the windfall.
   The agency gave notice Monday it was considering other
approaches: Auctions of the right to produce and direct regulation
of certain manufacturing processes that might require other
chemicals to be used instead.
   An official of the Office of Management and Budget said OMB
favored auctions and would press its view.
   ``We think the market ought to be allowed to do its work rather
than a bunch of bureaucrats like me,'' said Robert K. Dawson,
associate director of OMB. ``What is the evidence that we as a
federal government can allocate production equitably across firms?''
   The notices accompanied the agency's final promulgation of
quotas for CFC producers under the 1987 Montreal treaty requiring
the cuts in CFC production.
   EPA expects enough countries to ratify the Montreal treaty for
it to take effect next Jan. 1. Eleven nations accounting for
two-thirds of world production must ratify; six including the
United States have done so.
   The non-toxic, non-flammable and long-lived CFC compounds are
used as refrigeration fluids, solvents and blowing agents to make
plastic foams.
   CFCs eventually reach the ozone layer 15 miles to 25 miles high
that blocks the cancer-causing ultraviolet rays of the sun. There
the CFCs destroy ozone.
   Scientists blame CFCs for a roughly 2.5 percent decline in the
ozone layer since about 1960. EPA says each percent means 43,000
more cases of skin cancer in the United States, currently about
500,000 a year, and the regulations should prevent 3.7 million
early U.S. deaths among people living now and to be born before
2075.
   The five U.S. companies producing CFC compounds are limited to
their 1986 production during the 12 months starting next July 1,
assuming the treaty takes effect Jan. 1. They will have to make a
20 percent cut in 1993, and an additional 30 percent cut in 1998.
   Eileen Claussen, acting deputy assistant EPA administrator for
air pollution, said EPA was not sure it had authority for either an
auction or a fee. The agency concedes a fee might be considered a
tax that Congress would have to enact.
   ``If (an auction) was judged to be illegal, we would have
nothing. We wouldn't be in compliance with the Montreal protocol,''
she said.
   Also, she said, ``There is a concern about hoarding,'' with big
companies like automakers able to outbid the thousands of small
companies that use CFCs.
   Dawson said OMB believed EPA had authority to conduct an
auction. Neither agency disputes that in theory, an auction should
capture all the windfall for the government because producers will
bid for production rights up to the point where production doesn't
meet their profit goals.
   John Hoffman, project officer for the new regulations, said
``our concern is the incentive producers might have for keeping an
existing product in production,'' delaying the switch to harmless
alternatives.
   ``While higher prices for CFCs and halons will stimulate some
firms and industries to shift to alternate materials, institute or
increase recycling, or produce other products, if substitutes are
not readily available, many firms will have little choice but to
continue to use these chemicals while paying a higher price,''
EPA's notice said.
   The five U.S. manufacturers of CFCs are: Du Pont Co.;
Allied-Signal Corp.; Pennwalt Corp.; Kaiser Chemicals Co.; and
Racon Inc.
   Ten other companies import the compounds.
   The Du Pont Co. does not believe there will be a windfall
because substitute compounds are being developed quickly, said Joe
Steed, environmental manager for CFCs.
   ``If we can fund development at the rate we think we need, we'll
be doing well,'' Steed said. Du Pont says it will end all CFC
production about the year 2000.
   David Doniger, senior attorney with the Natural Resources
Defense Council, an environmental group, said he would challenge
the regulations in court.
   Halting ozone depletion ``requires a virtually complete ban on
CFCs and other ozone-depleting chemicals. Even then, recovery of
the ozone layer will take at least a century,'' Doniger said.
</TEXT>
