<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YonkersDeseg 2ndLd-Writethru a0749 08-02 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0749,0868</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yonkers City Council Defeats Housing Desegration Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 5-6 bgng ``This is...' with 9 grafs to UPDATE with
comments during and after meeting. Picks up 7th graf pvs ``Monday
night's...' Subs last 7 grafs with two grafs to tighten, conform
and CORRECT that Yonkers was bailed out sted bankrupt in 1984.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council members voted Monday night to
defy a federal judge who is threatening to bankrupt the city and
send them to jail unless they endorse a housing desegregation plan.
   The 4-3 vote came at a raucous special meeting in which speakers
were interrupted, cheered and booed. The majority voted not to
endorse a court-ordered plan providing for financial and zoning
incentives to attract developers to build 800 units of affordable
housing throughout the city.
   U.S. District Court Judge Leonard Sand has said that if the
council failed to pass the resolution by Monday, he would would
fine Yonkers $100 for the first day, and would double the fine for
each day thereafter. After 22 days, the fines would wipe out the
city's annual operating budget of $337 million.
   In addition, Sand has threatened to fine each council member
$500 a day. If they remained in contempt after 10 days, they would
be jailed, Sand said.
   After the vote, Mayor Nicholas Wasiscko said he might call
another special council meeting later this week, and hoped
meanwhile that the judge would see ``some good faith'' in the
closeness of the vote and would delay the fines.
   ``The rule of law has got to be respected,'' said Wasiscko, 29,
who won election as an opponent of desegregation but has since come
to support the court-ordered plan.
   ``Mob rule, whether it is on a street corner or in a city
council chamber, should never be the rule of the day,'' he said.
   One person was arrested for disorderly conduct outside the
meeting, where about 300 people congregated on the street, which
was closed off.
   During the meeting, Vice Mayor Henry Spallone, the most
vociferous opponent of the desegregation plan, rallied the crowd of
about 150 by blasting the federal government and the way it runs
public housing.
   ``The people of Yonkers are not guilty of anything. The people
guilty here (are) the federal government, the state, the MHA
(Municipal Housing Authority) and their lies,'' Spallone said.
   Spallone also charged that Sand felt himself to be above the
law. The vice mayor also claimed that any vote was illegal because
he was coerced into voting before a public hearing was held.
   Another member who voted against the plan, Council Minority
Leader Nicholas Longo, said there should have been a public meeting
before Monday night's vote.
   Noting that Sand lives in an exclusive suburb, Longo said,
``This is a typical case of the hypocrisy of the rich and elitist
looking down upon those who must work for everything they have.''
   Monday night's meeting was the latest installment in an
acrimonious dispute that began in 1980 when the Justice Department
charged that Yonkers had intentionally segregated its housing and
schools for 40 years.
   Yonkers, with 195,000 residents, is the state's fourth-largest
city. By virtue of its location, it also is a town with a split
personality.
   The east side is predominately white, middle to upper class, the
home of Sarah Lawrence College; it borders the wealthy towns of
Scarsdale and Bronxville. The west side is older, more industrial,
and mostly black and Hispanic; it adjoins New York City's poorest
borough, the Bronx.
   In 1985, Sand found Yonkers guilty in a landmark decision that
linked school segregation to housing segregation for the first time.
   The city's Board of Education launched its integration plan in
1986. That same year, Sand ordered the city to construct 200 units
of low-income housing on the east side and 800 more units of
housing throughout the city _ 160 low-income homes and the rest for
moderate incomes.
   When they campaigned last fall, six of the seven council members
pledged to fight the Sand plan. But in January, under threat of
fines, the council agreed to a consent decree that would allow
construction to go forward.
   The public recoiled. Residents mobbed council meetings,
screaming for hours on end. Council members received bullets in the
mail. Picket lines formed in front of the judge's homes in
Manhattan and Pound Ridge.
   The council flip-flopped, and sought to appeal the plan. The
U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear the appeal, but the council
persisted in its opposition.
   The threat of fines has special resonance in Yonkers, which
required a state bailout to avoid bankruptcy in 1984 and has
struggled to regain its financial footing. The city has seen three
years of budget surpluses as well as a growing tax base.
   Susan Brewster, executive director of the Emergency Financial
Control Board established to monitor Yonkers spending, said if the
city was found in contempt of court, Moody's Investment Co. would
suspend the city's BAA bond rating. Such a move would jeopardize
the city's financial future, she said.
</TEXT>
