<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Cyprus     08-02 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Cyprus,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cypriot President Appeals For Removal Of Turkish Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cypriot President George Vassiliou said
President Reagan accepted his proposal of persuading Turkey to
withdraw its troops and Turkish settlers from his divided island,
but a White House spokesman disputed that.
   Vassiliou, in an interview after the 30-minute White House
meeting Monday, said Reagan ``was favorably accepting those
principles.''
   Cyprus has been divided since a Turkish invasion 14 years ago.
Vassiliou proposed the demilitarization of the Mediterranean
country and the creation of a federalized republic.
   ``I said it would be beneficial to Cypriots, Turks and Greeks,
and act as a stabilizing role in the region,'' he said.
   ``I said Cyprus should be Cypriot,'' Vassiliou said of his
conversation with Reagan. ``The solution of the Cyprus problem is
very simple. It depends on the implementation of principles the
United States believes in. That means no foreign troops should be
in the country and human rights should be implemented.''
   However, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan did
not take a position on the Turkish-Cypriot problem, but merely had
endorsed using the United Nations' auspices to negotiate a
settlement to the longstanding dispute.
   Fitzwater said Reagan only generally favors withdrawal of
foreign troops, and there was no statement made about the Turkish
troops.
   ``The president has taken that position around the world, in
country after country,'' Fitzwater said. ``But what we said in
there (the meeting with Vassiliou) was that the proper place to
resolve it was the U.N.''
   Vassiliou has talks scheduled Aug. 24 in New York under United
Nations auspices with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Dentash.
   Greece and Turkey have stepped to the brink of war in recent
years because of long-standing differences over Cyprus and
oil-prospecting rights in the Aegean Sea.
   Turkey invaded and seized the northern part of the island in
July 1974, saying it was protecting the Tyrkish Cypriot minority in
the wake of a Greek-backed coup by supporters of union with Greece.
   The 120,000-strong Turkish Cypriot community, forming 17 percent
of the island's population, established a breakaway state in the
Turkish-occupied area in November 1983. Only Turkey has recognized
it.
   The reunification of the island is blocked by Turkey's refusal
to implement a series of U.N. General Assembly and Security Council
resolutions.
   These demand the withdrawal of the estimated 30,000 Turkish
troops and 50,000 mainland settlers brought to northern Cyprus
since the invasion, the abrogation of the breakaway move and the
return of 200,000 Greek Cypriot refugees, one-third of the
population, to their homes in the north.
</TEXT>
