<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PrimariesRdp     08-02 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Primaries Rdp,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voting in 3 States Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A referendum on casino gambling in Detroit and a GOP Senate
contest between two millionaires highlight Michigan's ballot today,
while Missouri voters decide whether to raise their lottery jackpot
and make a former first lady the Democratic candidate for governor.
   Missouri Democrats a~so are expected to nominate Rep. Richard
Gephardt for a seventh term and give farm activist Wayne Cryts a
second shot at Congress.
   Kansas also has primaries, but there are no statewide races and
only three congressional contests. In the 3rd District, GOP
incumbent Jan Meyers faces Charles B. ``Bat'' Masterson, 73, a
retired school administrator.
   The Detroit advisory referendx
opponents of gambling, who want to discourage the Legislature from
legalizing casinos. Similar referendums showed voters opposed tom
gambling in 1976 and 1982.
   Mayor Coleman Young believes casinos can bring desperately
needed money into the city and help lower the 9.6 percent
unemployment rate, a position that has pitted him against the
ministers and church members who have formed the core of his
constituency. All over the city on Sunday preachers used their
pulpits to make one last anti-casino pitch.
   Michigan's hottest statewide race is for the GOP nomination to
challenge Democratic Sen. Donald Riegle, who has no primary
opposition as he seeks a third term.
   Robert Huber and Jim Dunn, each of whom served one term in
Congress, have tried to portray Riegle as too liberal for Michigan
voters. They have had trouble attracting contributions and both
have spent more than $200,000 of their own money, while Riegle has
campaign funds of $4 million.
   Huber, the more conservative of the two, has sought to win
support from the partisans brought into the party by the Rev. Pat
Robertson's presidential campaign, and has prominently mentioned
his anti-abortion stand in ads.
   AIDS became an issue in the race last week when Dunn said in a
radio interview that he took ``a reasonable, rational, I think very
responsible approach to the problems that face this nation. Mr.
Huber has said that the reason people have AIDS is the wrath of
God, punishment from God'' of homosexuals and drug users.
   Huber, asked about Dunn's remarks, said ``I don't know whether
it's the wrath of God, but if it isn't it should be.''
   In Missouri, state Rep. Betty Hearnes, who calls herself a
compassionate friend of working Missourians, is considered the
Democrats' best bet for unseating Republican Gov. John Ashcroft.
   She's expected to face little trouble with her only primary
opposition, Lavoy ``Zaki'' Reed, a St. Louis area teacher who is
making his second bid for governor.
   Mrs. Hearnes, 61, is the wife of Warren Hearnes, who was
governor from 1965-73. If elected, she would be Missouri's first
woman governor.
   Gephardt, who filed at the last minute for a seventh term after
dropping his presidential bid, faces three little-known Democrats
in the St. Louis-area 3rd District.
   Cryts, who gained national publicity in 1981 when he took his
family's soybeans out of a bankrupt, padlocked grain elevator, is
favored to win the Democratic nomination for the 8th District
congressional seat. That would entitle him to a rematch with
Republican Rep. Bill Emerson, who won by 8,000 out of 150,000 votes
cast in 1986.
   A statewide measure asks voters to remove most spending
restrictions on the 2{-year-old lottery, a change supporters call
crucial in light of a $24 million drop in sales during the last
fiscal year. Officials say the decline was probably caused by a
lack of advertising.
   Currently, 45 percent of lottery proceeds must go for prizes, 45
percent to the state and 10 percent for administrative costs,
including advertising.
   Critics say the prize limit does not allow the lottery to
compete with neighboring states with higher prize structures. The
amendment would change the prize limit to a minimum of 45 percent,
and lottery officials would like to give out about 50 percent in
prizes. It also would permit the state to spend more on advertising.
</TEXT>
