<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0670,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Dead, Campers Shaken Up, After Bus Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with driver's name, four still
hospitalized Monday; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tour bus carrying 34 children and seven
adults veered off a road and down an embankment on the outskirts of
the state capital Monday, killing the driver, leaving four people
hospitalized and dozens of others with minor injuries, authorities
said.
   Authorities said they were investigating the possibility that
the driver, Dominic Boudreau, 42, of Biddeford, suffered some kind
of an attack that led to the crash. An autopsy report was scheduled
to be released Tuesday.
   The Maine Line Tours bus was taking 12- and 13-year-old boys and
their chaperones from Camp Cedar, a private, overnight camp on
Sebago Lake in western Maine, on a camping and fishing trip to Bar
Harbor when the accident occurred at 11:20 a.m., said Henry Hacker,
a camp director.
   Twenty-nine passengers were taken to the Kennebec Valley Medical
Center in Augusta for treatment, hospital spokeswoman Mary Plumer
said. Eight were taken to the nearby Togus Veterans Administration
Hospital, while others were sent for treatment to Waterville.
   A counselor and three children were hospitalized, two of them in
intensive care with broken bones, Plumer said Monday night. The
rest were sent back to Camp Cedar, said Hacker, who described their
injuries as minor.
   Witnesses said the 49-seat bus veered off Route 3, about seven
miles outside downtown Augusta. The bus traveled down an embankment
and rolled onto its side before coming to rest in a stand of trees.
   ``Eyewitnesses said it was going down the (road) and just (went)
right off the road into the trees, kabang. ... Fortunately it
wasn't any worse,'' said Albert L. Godfrey Sr. of the Maine Highway
Safety Commission, who was at the scene.
   Other witnesses said the accident looked much worse at first.
   ``The kids were laying all along here with the blood, they were
a mess,'' said Frances Cunningham, who lives near the scene of the
accident.
   ``They were all so scared, and they wanted their parents,'' said
another resident from nearby, Connie Boggs.
</TEXT>
