<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DanceBan     08-02 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dance Ban,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Plan First School Dance In Wake Of Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PURDY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students in this tiny Ozarks town are getting
ready for their first school dance now that a federal judge has
ruled that a century-old ban on such festivities is
unconstitutional.
   ``I want to get right on the stick and get it rolling,'' said
16-year-old Nancy Fox, president of the Purdy senior and junior
high school council. ``I think most of the kids are excited.''
   ``It's wonderful,'' added Jonathan Clayton, who graduated from
Purdy High School in May. ``It's my dream come true.''
   Clayton and Miss Fox's parents were among 21 plaintiffs who sued
the school board in 1986, claiming that the ban was inspired by
religious beliefs. On Monday, U.S. District Judge Russell G. Clark
agreed but didn't order the school to sponsor dances.
   Clark, whose court is in Springfield, said the rule in effect
promoted the religious beliefs of those in Purdy ``who believe that
social dancing is sinful.''
   School board attorney Ransom Ellis Jr. said that conclusion was
incorrect, although no decision has been made about an appeal.
   School board members cited other reasons for the ban, including
potential discipline and drinking problems.
   The board, whose district has 520 students, including about 250
in the junior-senior high school, could still seek to ban dancing
for other reasons, said William Fleischaker, an American Civil
Liberties Union lawyer who helped represent the plaintiffs. ``But
in my opinion that would be a foolish step.''
   Although dances were banned on school property, they have been
held at a town community center, and students have organized
junior-senior proms and held them in neighboring communities.
   The controversy escalated after the Class of 1986 failed to
persuade the school board to drop the ban, and dance supporters
held a rally like the one in the movie, ``Footloose,'' about a
fictional Texas town where dancing was banned.
   Miss Fox said her executive council and its adviser will meet
soon to plan a dance, which she said might be a back-to-school
celebration.
   ``We'll draw up a proposal to bring before the administration
... just like we would any other activity,'' Miss Fox said.
   Most students are happy the ban has been ruled unconstitutional,
she said.
   ``There may still be students who don't want to dance because of
their religious beliefs. But those who dance and want to dance, we
will have dances for them if all goes well.''
   Clark conducted a four-day hearing for the lawsuit in June. In
his order, he granted the plaintiffs' request for a symbolic $1
plus attorney fees.
   Church leaders in this southwestern Missouri town of about 900
people made no secret of their opposition to the school dances and
openly lobbied board members. At a spring school board election,
anti-dancing members were overwhelmingly re-elected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
