<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Homeless-Hotels 1stLd-Writethru a0452 08-02 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless-Hotels, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0452,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch Proposes Two-Year Plan to Board Up Hotels for the Homeless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT to unkept sted kept.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city announced plans Monday to stop putting
homeless families into hotels within two years, speeding up a
previous five-year commitment.
   The announcement by Mayor Edward I. Koch came during a
congressional hearing to determine whether the city was living up
to a promise to end the use of welfare hotels in exchange for
Congress' continued funding for the hotels.
   Congress is scheduled to vote Wednesday on whether to extend the
program another year.
   Some political leaders present at the hearing, including Rep.
Bill Green, R-N.Y., said the proposal might be an effective
political move but also might become an unkept promise.
   William J. Grinker, commissioner of the city's Human Resources
Administration, told the panel the ``problem will not be solved, we
will still have homelessness.''
   Under a plan developed earlier this year, the city said it would
stop using the hotels by the end of fiscal year 1993. It was
projected that 1,179 families would still be in hotels and 3,906
families would be in city operated transitional shelters by the end
of fiscal year 1990.
   Under the plan announced Monday, by the end of 1989, some 1991
families would be in hotels and 2,256 families in the transitional
shelters. By the end of 1990, no families are expected to be in
hotels and 3,534 would be in the shelters.
   One of the plan's key components, Koch told the panel, is that
``we will be providing 2,300 more Housing Authority and HPD
(Department of Housing, Preservation and Development) apartments to
homeless families over the next two years than we had anticipated
under the original plan.''
   Koch noted that Congress had changed its regulations recently,
allowing the city to give homeless families priority over families
on waiting lists.
   He said the plan would work only if a sufficient number of large
apartments and shelter units become available, and families
continue to enter and leave the hotel system at the same rate they
are doing so now _ and find apartments on their own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
