<HEAD>Hospital Ordered to Justify Hinckley Field Trip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: St. Elizabeths without apostrophe is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has given St. Elizabeths
mental hospital until Friday to submit treatment records supporting
its conclusion that residential assailant John W. Hinckley Jr.
should be allowed a day trip off hospital grounds.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker on Monday granted a
request by prosecutors for a court hearing on the hospital proposal
to let Hinckley go on a supervised ``recreational'' field trip with
other patients.
   Hinckley, who shot and wounded President Reagan and three others
on March 31, 1981, has been held at St. Elizabeths since 1982, when
he was acquitted of criminal charges by reason of insanity.
   Last year, the government successfully opposed an attempt by
hospital authorities to allow Hinckley to visit his parents over
the Easter weekend.
   The Secret Service said it opposed the hospital's latest plan,
which was outlined in a July 19 letter to the judge.
