<HEAD>Pryor Bill Would Require Registration of Consultants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. David Pryor, responding to allegations of
corruption in the nation's defense contracting, has proposed
requiring private consultants to defense contractors to register
with the federal government.
   ``The bill is intended to shed some sunshine on the
all-too-shadowy world of consultants. Bringing everything into the
light should cut down on the shady dealings,'' Pryor, D-Ark., said
after introducing the bill Monday.
   Pryor chairs the Senate Government Affairs federal service
subcommittee, which has held a series of hearings on the use of
consultants by Pentagon contractors.
   Prosecutors are investigating allegations that contractors'
consultants, many of them former Pentagon employees, paid bribes to
current Defense Department workers for inside information about
contracts. No charges have been filed.
