<HEAD>Glenn Presidential Committee Agrees to $30,000 Penalty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has closed the books on a case
involving the 1984 presidential campaign committee of Sen. John
Glenn, with the committee agreeing to pay a $30,000 civil penalty
for alleged violations of federal election law.
   The Federal Election Commission said Monday it had found
probable cause to believe that the Glenn committee and its
treasurer, William R. White, accepted excessive campaign
contributions, misreported cash and spending levels, and exceeded
spending limits in the 1984 presidential campaign.
   The information was made public in a voluntary ``conciliation
agreement'' between the agency and the campaign committee that was
released by the FEC. The agreement requires that the committee pay
a $30,000 civil penalty for the alleged violations.
   ``This is something we've negotiated out with the commission
over the last few months,'' said White. ``I guess both sides felt
that this was the best way to dispose of the matter.''
</TEXT>
