   George Bush is floating Gov. Carroll
Campbell's name as a potential running mate, but some political
leaders in South Carolina say its being done out of respect more
than a serious desire to see Campbell as vice president.
   Republicans and Democrats interviewed Monday said they believe
Bush is trying to boost his chances in the south and that former
Campbell political adviser Lee Atwater _ now Bush's campaign
chairman _ is maneuvering to boost an old friend's national stature.
   ``I see Lee Atwater _ not only his fingerprints but also his
toeprints _ all over this one,'' GOP state Sen. John Courson said.
   Campbell said Friday he is one of several people who have been
asked by the Bush campaign to submit background information.
   Campbell's chief of staff Warren Tompkins acknowledged the
attention extended Campbell's opportunities, but was careful not to
say those opportunities went beyond the Statehouse.
   ``It certainly doesn't hurt his opportunities and the chances
for re-election to a second term,'' Tompkins said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson Makes Official Return As `700 Club' Host</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson has returned to the
Christian Broadcasting Network as co-host of ``The 700 Club'' after
his unsuccessful run for the Republican presidential nomination.
   ``For better or worse, the health of this ministry depends on
this program. It is our bread and butter,'' the television
evangelist said Monday after the first broadcast of his revamped
program.
   Robertson's return also marked a departure from the previous
incarnation of the program.
   Robertson said the new format will be one-third news, one-third
ministry and teaching and one-third lifestyle features. During the
news section of Monday's program, Robertson and new co-host Sheila
Walsh presented stories about the Middle East, drugs in the
workplace, abortion demonstrations in Atlanta and the first in a
weeklong series on health and nutrition.
   ``We're going to add more people to our Washington bureau. We're
going to be covering more news,'' said Robertson, who has not ruled
out a future bid for the White House.
