<DOCNO> AP880802-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Shrine     08-02 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Shrine,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Takeshita Will Not Make Controversial Shrine Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita has decided not to
pay an official visit to a shrine dedicated to Japanese war dead on
Aug. 15, the 43rd anniversary of Japan's World War II defeat, a
government spokesman said today.
   Keizo Obuchi, chief Cabinet secretary, told a news conference
Takeshita ``will adopt the same stance as last year,'' when his
predecessor Yasuhiro Nakasone refrained from visiting the Tokyo
shrine for a second straight year.
   Among the 2.4 million Japanese war dead enshrined at Yasukuni
are 14 class-A war criminals, including wartime Prime Minister
Hideki Tojo.
   In 1985, Nakasone visited the shrine in his official capacity as
prime minister to mark the 40th anniversary of the war's end. The
visit was strongly criticized by China, South Korea and other Asian
countries that suffered the effects of Japanese militarism during
the war.
   Last year, the government said Japan must give appropriate
consideration to the national sentiment of its neighbors.
   Yasukuni Shrine was established in 1869 to honor Japan's war
dead. The military used the shrine, which was supported by the
government, to promote patriotism and militarism during the war.
   Government support of the shrine ended in 1945, at the end of
World War II. Japan's Constitution states that no religious
organization shall receive any privileges from the state or
exercise any political authority.
</TEXT>
