<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PrisonHostages 6thLd-Writethru a0459 08-02 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Hostages, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0459,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prison Uprising Ends Peacefully After 14 Hours</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with guards' identities,
conditions, with one listed as serious; picks up 8th graf pvs,
`Monday evening, ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COXSACKIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates complaining of harassment by
officers at a maximum-security prison took five guards hostage
Monday and held them for up to 14 hours before surrendering
peacefully early Tuesday, officials said.
   ``The crisis has ended,'' Gov. Mario Cuomo said.
   Four Coxsackie Correctional Facility guards were released at
12:45 a.m. Tuesday, said Cuomo spokesman Gary Fryer. One hostage
was taken out on a stretcher and the three others walked out under
their own power, he said.
   Late Monday, guard Warren Agostinoni was released.
   Agostinoni, 28, who was taken by ambulance to a hospital, said
Correction Department spokesman James Flateau. The guard was listed
in fair condition at Albany Medical Center with cuts and bruises,
hospital spokeswoman Peggy Pitcher said.
   The other former hostages also were taken there, with the most
seriously injured identified as David Pratt, 31. Pratt was in
serious condition with abdominal injuires, Pitcher said. The three
others _ Lewis Bloom, 41; Douglas Roberts, 37; and John Shipley, 32
_ were in good condition and were being treated for bruises, she
said.
   Monday evening, the inmates allowed the hostages to stand one at
a time before a window, giving prison officials their first look at
the five guards since they were seized more than nine hours earlier.
   Flateau said the guards looked to be in ``reasonably good
condition'' but that some appeared to have cuts and bruises. He
said the inmates allowed the guards to be seen ``as a show of good
faith, I guess.''
   Earlier, officials said the 32 inmates believed to be involved
were armed with homemade knives. But Flateau said Monday night that
he could not confirm any knives were involved and he said the
complaints with harassment were no longer being talked about.
   Flateau said that as of 11 p.m., the inmates had not given a
list of demands to prison officials. He would not discuss
negotiations other than to say they were ongoing.
   He said the inmates controlled the console that operates their
unit's gates and doors, which lead to other parts of the prison and
a recreation yard.
   Prison Superintendent John Twomey, assisted by a crisis
intervention team, communicated with some of the inmates, Flateau
said.
   ``There have not been demands made at this point as much as
complaints made by the inmates about harassment (by guards),''
Flateau said.
   ``Verbal harassment was the (complaint) they mentioned most
often, food complaints, things like that,'' Flateau said.
   How the takeover occurred was not known, Flateau said.
   The inmates were assigned to the prison's special unit for
prisoners with disciplinary problems, Flateau said.
   State troopers and local police with rifles blocked the entrance
of the prison, which houses 951 prisoners and is about 20 miles
south of Albany.
   All of the prison's roughly 180 guards were called to duty and
about 40 police officers were sent to the prison. All prisoners
were confined to their cells, Flateau said.
   Flateau said the families of the five guards had been contacted
and members of three of those families were at the prison.
   Outside the prison, guard Ralph Scott said inmates had been
warning for weeks that there might be trouble. In the last two
weeks, he said, prisoners' verbal and physical assaults on
corrections officers had increased.
   ``Every so often you hear something might happen, and I had a
feeling something was going to happen,'' Scott said.
   At a news conference in Albany, Cuomo said he did not think the
generally crowded condition of New York state's prisons contributed
to the incident because ``capacity is not a problem'' at Coxsackie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
