<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis Bjt   08-02 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Promises Door To Blacks; Defends Bentsen Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis chided rival George Bush for
refusing to address an Urban League convention and defended his own
running mate's support of Contra aid despite the Democratic
nominee's vocal opposition.
   ``I hope you will note who's here and who isn't here,'' Dukakis
told the Urban League convention Monday night, winning a standing
ovation from the black audience.
   Dukakis returned home late Monday and was spending today and
Wednesday tending to his duties as Massachusetts governor before
resuming campaigning Thursday.
   The applause Dukakis won for the Bush line was the loudest of
his speech, which was greeted cordially but not enthusiastically.
He also won loud applause when he mentioned former Democratic rival
Jesse Jackson, who endorsed Dukakis at the Democratic National
Convention.
   Dukakis praised Jackson's call for ``common ground'' and
promised to march later this month to commemorate the 25th
anniversary of Martin Luther King Jr.'s civil rights march on
Washington.
   ``Together we can remember the dream,'' Dukakis said.
   Urban League President John E. Jacob said at the opening of the
convention that the organization would have to pressure the next
president on issues such as civil rights and affirmative action.
   Dukakis disputed that.
   If he's elected, Dukakis said, ``next year the pressure is going
to come from the president.''
   There has been increasing pressure on Dukakis in recent weeks to
spell out what he thinks about Bentsen's support of aid to the
Nicaraguan rebels, and the question surfaced again Monday as Senate
Democrats, Bentsen among them, worked to craft a compromise aid
package.
   ``No. No. No,'' Dukakis said whether his running mate's support
for Contra aid bothered him. ``I didn't pick Lloyd Bentsen to be a
clone of Michael Dukakis. We agree on most things but we disagree
on some.''
   Still, Dukakis pressed his opposition to Contra aid, a favorite
policy of President Reagan.
   ``It's a failed and an illegal policy and it ought to stop,''
Dukakis told reporters. Referring to the peace plan drafted by
Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, he said, ``If we had
enthusiastically supported the Arias plan a year ago this mess
would be over with, the war would be over with.''
   Dukakis' appearance before the Urban League was no accident
began a week in which the candidate is expanding his effort to win
the support of black voters. His campaign is mailing literature
about his affirmative action and judicial appointments record to
nearly 7,000 black elected officials.
   Dukakis told the Urban League ``cramped ideals and the limited
ambitions of the past seven years'' have hurt blacks and other
minorities and said Reagan had engaged in reckless spending that
took money away from more important programs.
   Dukakis criticized the Reagan Justice Department's record on
civil rights and promised to appoint an attorney general ``who will
enforce the Voting Rights Act and the Civil Rights Restoration Act
and the Fair Housing Act Amendments of 1988.''
   ``We're going to have a president and a vice president who
understand that affirmative action is an essential part of making
the American dream come true for each and every citizen in our
country,'' he said.
   Bush, who will formally accept the GOP nomination in two weeks,
declined to address the Urban League. His campaign said the vice
president had a scheduling conflict.
   Dukakis had both good news and bad news on the home front Monday.
   A preliminary FBI inquiry into allegations the Dukakis
administration acted improperly in placing a prison in central
Massachusetts concluded without charges being filed. Law
enforcement sources said the review found no evidence of any
violations of federal law in the process, which had been challenged
by opponents of the prison plan.
   But his administration had to borrow $200 million to pay its
bills, a sign of a continued slump in state revenue collections.
The state also was forced to borrow money _ through short term
notes _ several times in the fiscal year that ended June 30.
</TEXT>
