<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Higher, Dollar Weakens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher while the dollar
weakened in slow trading in Tokyo Tuesday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which won 126.37 points Monday, gained another
40.02 points, or 0.14 percent, closing at 28,366.33.
   Volume in the first section totaled 800 million shares, down
from Monday's 900 million.
   The dollar opened at 132.65 yen and ranged between 132.30 yen
and 132.70 yen before closing at 132.40 yen, down 0.85 yen from
Monday's close.
   Dollar-sensitive stocks such as electricals and automakers
declined, following the dollar's slip below 133 yen overnight in
New York.
   ``Prices on the stock market were mixed following the upswing of
the yen,'' said Masahiro Umemori, a stock researcher at Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   Umemori said some real estate, construction and other issues
less sensitive to the dollar's value rose, but most other sectors
were mixed or weaker.
   Foreign exchange dealers said market participants did not expect
much market-moving news until Friday, when U.S. employment figures
are to be released in Washington.
</TEXT>
