<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Mumford     08-02 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Mumford,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poet Dies of Breast Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erika Mumford, a prize-winning poet,
died of breast cancer at her home. She was 53.
   Services were scheduled today in Harvard University's Memorial
Church for Mrs. Mumford, who died Saturday.
   She wrote three collections of poetry _ ``The Door in the
Forest,'' ``Willow Water,'' and ``The Karma Bazaar.''
   Her poems appeared in Ploughshares, Hudson Review, Yankee,
Sequoia and Sojourner. She received prizes from the Poetry Society
of America and Poet Lore and a fellowship from the Massachusetts
Artists Foundation.
   She was born in Geneva, Switzerland, and spent her childhood in
Germany, coming to the United States in 1946. She was graduated
from Radcliffe College in 1957 and received a doctorate in Celtic
languages and literature from Harvard in 1973.
   Mrs. Mumford is survived by her husband, four children and two
brothers.
</TEXT>
