<2ND_LINE>PM-Dissection Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Frog Dissection Protest Suit, Offers Alternative</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `As a ...' with one graf to clarify that
judge proposed alternative. SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Miss Graham ...'
with three grafs to UPDATE with school lawyer's quote and new state
law. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Apple later ...'; Jenifer is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal lawsuit brought by a girl who
refused to dissect a frog in biology class was dismissed after the
school agreed to let her use photographs of a frog that died of
natural causes.
   Victor Valley Union High School District officials said Jenifer
Graham, 16, can complete the coursework by using the pictures to
identify parts, precluding the need for her to dissect a frog
herself.
   U.S. District Court Judge Manuel Real, who proposed the
alternative plan Monday, dismissed Miss Graham's lawsuit against
the school district.
   She contended school officials violated her rights by ordering
her to dissect a frog that was killed for scientific use. Miss
Graham opposes killing animals for science.
   After her refusal to dissect a frog, Miss Graham, a vegetarian,
received a zero for that assignment, lowering her grade from A to
B. Her records also showed that she balked at her teacher's order.
   The girl's lawyers said finding a dead frog in good enough shape
to serve the purpose would be a problem, but they didn't say they
would appeal the ruling.
   ``If we have to station somebody down at the swamps or wherever
it is they live to see them die, we'll do it,'' promised school
attorney Joseph Arias.
   Meanwhile, a new state law, which takes effect Jan. 1, allows
students to be excused from lab dissections if they object on
religious or moral grounds.
   Miss Graham and her lawyers fought to allow her to use models of
a dissected frog. She gained national attention with her fight and
even appeared in a TV commercial for Apple Computers, demonstrating
a computer mock-up of a dead frog that she said would serve the
same purpose as a frog corpse.
   Apple later dropped that commercial because the company said the
animal rights issue was getting more attention than the computer
they advertised.
   The school objected to models, saying they could give Miss
Graham an advantage over other students and could jeopardize the
school's credibility with universities.
</TEXT>
