<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeerKill     08-02 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deer Kill,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wildlife Officials Call Early Hunting to Rid Ranchers of Hungry
Deer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leroy Horn raises cattle and grows alfalfa at
his rural central Nevada spread, but this year's harvesting is
being done by hungry deer that have broken his fences, trampled the
ground and nibbled his hay.
   Horn's ranch is one of scores in Nevada where thousands of
marauding deer have found green fields tempting in this drought
year. A special hunting season has been called to thin their record
numbers.
   ``The deer come and mow the alfalfa down,'' Horn said Monday.
``I've got 35 acres but they just eat it as fast as it grows.
   ``Every year it seems like a few more deer come back.''
   The Nevada Department of Wildlife has come to the rescue by
calling an emergency early hunting season to trim the state's
record 250,000 deer herd.
   Twenty antlerless deer tags will go on sale for the area where
Horn lives beginning Wednesday with 170 to 200 more available in
other rural areas to control the deer depredation, officials said.
The permits will be good for about two weeks.
   Additional hunts are likely before the normal October through
December hunting season, said David Rice, a department spokesman.
   ``This isn't the first time we've had emergency depredation
hunts,'' Rice said. ``But this is pretty bad this year because we
have a record deer population.''
   The number of deer is the largest since records began in the
early 1960s, Rice said.
   Opening the hunting season early and in specific problem areas
is the best way to reduce the deer population when it intrudes on
ranchers and farmers, he said.
   Even so, Horn said he doesn't plan to kill a deer. ``I'll leave
that up to the hunters.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
