<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Capitalism     08-02 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Capitalism,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Promiscuity, Unwanted Pregnancies On The Rise In Industrial
District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Promiscuity, homosexuality and unwanted
pregnancies are on the rise in Shenzhen, a district near Hong Kong
where most of the factories are funded from abroad, a newspaper
reported today.
   The China Youth News called the developments ``serious social
problems'' and attributed them to a lack of men in the area.
   The report, rare for its explicitness, was the paper's second in
a week on the lives of the part-time women workers of Shenzhen.
   The first focused on labor strife in the area, one of four
Special Economic Zones set up by China in 1980 for factories and
businesses funded partly or wholly by foreign capital. It said 21
strikes broke out in the area in 1986 and 1987 and told of worker
exploitation, making an unprecedented call for a labor law to
protect workers.
   Today's report said there were 250,000 part-time women workers
in Shenzhen, in Guangzhou province.
   The women are in a particular bind because not being permanent
residents of the area, not many men want to marry them. In China,
if a person doesn't have a residence permit for a certain area,
they cannot live there on a permanent basis even if they marry a
native.
   The report said that in one factory, a plastic bag enterprise,
the number of part-time women workers outnumber men by 50 to one.
   ``Here women are everywhere,'' the paper said, ``so the area is
now called a `Woman's Kingdom.' ''
   The paper said that to help part-time women workers, some
districts of Shenzhen have set up sports complexes, clubs and dance
halls.
   ``But with their thirst for love and sex, the newness of these
facilities quickly fades,'' it said.
   The paper quoted one young woman as saying: ``Who isn't willing
to fall in love. After we work all day, who doesn't want to lay
one's head against the chest of a man. Even if I'm not married, I'm
willing.''
   A psychologist working for the Public Securuty Bureau was quoted
as saying that ``the womens' hearts are like kindling wood. When
they meet the fire of love, the flames will rage.''
   The paper said that even though most of the women have
difficulty getting married, many are getting pregnant anyway.
   In the Shekou industrial district, the paper said, the number of
unwanted pregnancies jumped from more than 200 in 1985 to more than
800 in 1987, out of a population of 10,000 part-time women workers.
   In the Nantou industrial area, the paper said more than half of
the divorces were caused because husbands had affairs with
part-time workers, the paper said.
   ``In addition,'' the paper said, ``there is homosexuality and
prostitution.'' It did not elaborate.
   Reports on prostitution and homosexuality are almost
non-existant in the Chinese press. Even though today's report did
not go into detail about their extent in Shenzhen, the report was
significant in that it raised the issues.
   The Chinese officially treat homosexuality as an illness.
Prostitution, which plagued China before the revolution in 1949,
has in recent years been making a steady comeback in some urban
areas.
   The paper said the problem of part-time women workers would not
be easily solved in Shenzhen.
   ``Some people say, just bring in more part-time men workers,''
the paper said. ``But that won't do, because the jobs aren't
suitable and there will still be the problem of residence cards.''
   ``No matter what,'' the report said, ``this problem won't easily
go away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
