<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0488 08-02 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crackdown Continues: Two Prominent Dissidents Arrested In Burma</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs with unconfirmed reports of Sein Lwin
assassination attempt. Picks up 5th graf pvs: Also, pamphlets ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a further crackdown on dissent,
authorities in Burma arrested two prominent war heroes for
allegedly plotting against the week-old government of President
Sein Lwin, sources said today.
   The arrests came as Amnesty International, the London-based
international human rights group, criticized the hardline one-party
government for arresting up to 25 other opponents in recent days.
   The arrests of Ta Ya and Yan Nyang, who helped lead the fight
for Burmese independence during World War II, is part of an
apparent government attempt to to root out potential threats,
diplomatic sources in Rangoon said.
   Meanwhile, unconfirmed reports from the Burmese capital said
Sein Lwin was the target of an assassination attempt on Friday by
an assistant who wounded him slightly in the arm, then killed
himself, sources said.
   ``The rumors are widespread enough to be taken seriously but we
cannot confirm them,'' a western diplomat reached in Rangoon said.
   The official Radio Rangoon said today that Sein Lwin had met
with members of the ``central organs of power'' Monday and
delivered a speech.
   In other developments, Western sources said about 500 students
and some Buddhist monks gathered Monday at the Shwedagon Pagoda,
Burma's holiest shrine and a traditional center for protest.
   Also, pamphlets have been circulating in the Burmese capital
calling for a nationwide general strike on Aug. 8.
   On Monday, the official News Agency Burma acknowledged the
arrest of the government's most outspoken critic, Aung Gyi, and
nine other people.
   The agency said Aung Gyi and the nine ``associates'' were
arrested on Saturday for ``attacking the state'' and would be
punished under criminal law.
   Aung Gyi emerged as the regime's leading critic this year in a
series of letters decrying economic and political conditions in
authoritarian Burma.
   He singled out Sein Lwin for ``turning a blind eye'' to gross
human rights abuses while overseeing the suppression of student
riots in March and June. Hundreds were killed in the violence.
   News Agency Burma's list of those arrested included Associated
Press correspondent Sein Win and a number of aging, retired
military officers who fell out of favor with former leader Ne Win
in the 1960s.
   The U.S. State Department and other sources said they believed
as many as 25 people may have been arrested in the sweep of
dissidents that netted Aung Gyi. Rangoon has mentioned only the 10
cited in the official media.
   Amnesty International has expressed concern over the arrests of
Aung Gyi and what it said were 24 of his friends and political
associates.
   Amnesty said it believed they may have been arrested ``for the
peaceful expression of their non-violent political beliefs.''
   ``At last report, they were held incommunicado without charge or
trial in Insein Central Prison, near Rangoon,'' it said in a
statement released Monday.
   The London-based International Press Institute, a media watchdog
group, protested the detention of Sein Win in a letter to Sein
Lwin, according to Peter Galliner, director of the institute.
   Ta Ya and Yan Nyang were members of a closely knit group of
young Burmese nationalists known as the ``Thirty Comrades'' or
``Thirty Heroes.''
   Hoping to rid Burma of British colonial rule, they sided with
the Japanese in the early stages of World War II but later fought
with the allies against Japan's forces in Burma.
   Their leader, Aung San, negotiated the end of colonial rule and
would undoubtably have become the country's first leaders if he had
not been assassinated in 1947. Ne Win was also among the thirty.
   Sein Lwin, a hardline, former military officer, took over the
chairmanship of the ruling Burma Socialist Program party one week
ago and was named president.
   The 77-year-old Ne Win stepped down a few days earlier after a
26-year rule marked by isolationist economic policies and
intolerance of free speech.
   Virtually all the country's institutes of higher learning were
closed in June. They are scheduled to reopen in mid-August.
   ``The unanswered question is whether the students and public can
translate distaste for Sein Lwin into action and what response the
army will have,'' one knowledgeable diplomat said.
   This source and others have noted that while Sein Lwin's
emergence has fueled protest, his recent moves have also left his
opponents with few if any real leaders.
   However, there is increasing speculation that a sizable number
of army officers are troubled by recent developments and owe little
loyalty to Sein Lwin.
   Travellers coming from Rangoon said there has been some ``panic
buying'' in recent days and the price of basic commodities has
risen sharply.
   The black market rate of the Burmese kyat has risen to eight
times the official rate of 6 kyat for one U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
