<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-02 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Through Much Of The Nation As Heat Lingers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms swept from Michigan through South Dakota
early today as other storms thundered through the South, bringing
harsh winds and large hail. Temperatures remained high after a day
in which numerous heat records were broken.
   A tornado touched down briefly in a field just north of Nevis,
Nev., Monday night. No damage or injuries were reported. Hail
pummeled Holabird, S.D., and winds raced to 60 mph when
thunderstorms moved through the area.
   In northern Minnesota and southwest upper Michigan, strong winds
accompanying thunderstorms damaged trees and power lines in many
areas.
   Thunderstorms were spotty early this morning over central and
southeast Texas into parts of eastern Mississippi and western
Alabama. Other isolated storms hit parts of northeast Colorado,
northwest Arizona and southern Nevada, and from northern Georgia
into south central South Carolina.
   High temperatures continued to plague much of the nation early
today, following Monday's scorcher in which heat records were
broken in eight states.
   ``It's like a blast furnace out there,'' said Rich Naistat, a
forecaster in Minneapolis.
   Records were broken Monday in Michigan, Illinois, Iowa,
Wisconsin, South Carolina, Mississippi, Minnesota and Indiana.
   The night offered little relief. Temperatures were in the low to
mid 80s early this morning from the central Plains into the middle
and lower Missouri valleys into the western and central parts of
the lower Great Lakes.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from northern parts of the upper Great Lakes and the upper
Mississippi Valley into central North Dakota; showers and
thunderstorms developing through the eastern half of the Gulf Coast
region, Alabama, Florida and the along the coast of North Carolina;
showers and thunderstorms scattered through southwest Texas,
northwest Arizona, southwest Utah, and through parts of eastern
Colorado; showers through northwest Montana; and sunny and dry
throughout the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the low to mid 90s across
much of the nation; in the 70s and 80s along the Pacific Coast
through the Pacific Northwest, the northern Rockies and the
northern Plains into northwestern parts of the Great Lakes; in the
80s across the eastern half of New England; from the middle 90s to
105 degrees from the lower Great Lakes through the middle
Mississippi and lower Missouri valleys into central Kansas; and
between 100 and 110 degrees from the central California valleys
into the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 93 degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 partly cloudy; Boston 74 foggy; Buffalo 69
fair; Charleston, S.C. 77 fair; Cincinnati 75 foggy; Cleveland 77
fair; Detroit 80 hazy; Miami 83 windy; New York 76 foggy;
Philadelphia 77 hazy; Pittsburgh 75 hazy; Portland, Maine 66 foggy;
Washington 79 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 64 cloudy; Chicago 82 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
81 partly cloudy; Denver 66 fair; Des Moines 80 fair; Indianapolis
79 hazy; Kansas City 82 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 82 partly
cloudy; Nashville 80 fair; New Orleans 74 fair; St. Louis 83 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 69 fair; Anchorage 55 cloudy; Las Vegas 86
fair; Los Angeles 67 cloudy; Phoenix 87 cloudy; Salt Lake City 76
fair; San Francisco 60 fair; Seattle 64 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 72 fair; Toronto 68 foggy.
</TEXT>
