<BYLINE>RETRANSMITTING TO FIX CYCLE DESIGNATOR</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Say Arrests Foiled Attacks On Diplomats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli Embassy thanked Peru for arresting
three men suspected of being members of the Palestinian terrorist
group and said their capture prevented attacks against diplomats.
   In a statement released Monday, the embassy thanked ``Peruvian
authorities and police for having frustrated the criminal attempt
of Palestine terrorists to attack Peruvian citizens and diplomats
of Israel and other countries.''
   The government on Friday said it had arrested Hocine Bouzidi,
36, who they said carried Algerian identity papers; Mohamed
Abdelrahman Abed, 19, of Egypt; and Ahmad Assaad Mohamed, 19, of
Lebanon.
   The government said Bouzidi was suspected of helping plan
simultaneous December 1985 raids at the Rome and Vienna airports in
which 14 people were killed and 120 were wounded.
   Police said an Interpol report listed Bouzidi as being a Central
Committee member of the radical Abu Nidal group, a splinter group
of the Palestine Liberation Organization. Police said he also was
linked to the November 1985 hijacking of an Egyptian jetliner in
which 59 people were killed when Egyptian troops stormed the craft
in Malta.
   They said their investigation indicated the suspects may have
been planning attacks against Peruvian, U.S. and Israeli targets in
Peru.
   A police spokesman said documents were recovered showing the men
kept the U.S. Consulate, the Israeli Embassy, the Synagogue of
Israel in Lima and the Israeli-owned Shalom travel agency under
surveillance. government since 1980.
   Officials said Saturday the three might be deported but did not
name a country or say if any extradition requests had been
received. Police said Bouzidi has been in Peru since mid-June and
the others seven months.
</TEXT>
