<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     08-02 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiite Spiritual Leader Predicts Hostage Release By November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spiritual leader of Lebanon's most
radical pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem group was quoted today as saying
American hostages may be freed before the U.S. presidential
election.
   Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah previously has predicted that
the fate of the nine American hostages would be determined during
or after the Nov. 8 election.
   Today, an Arab-language weekly quoted him as suggesting for the
first time that freedom for the hostages may come sooner.
   ``I do not have any detailed information on the hostages issue
within the context of U.S.-Iranian relations,'' Fadlallah was
quoted as saying in an interview published by the Paris-based
Mostakbal magazine.
   ``But I have a feeling that the problem of the hostages is an
essential factor in the American presidential election because
their card will be of no importance after the elections,'' he was
quoted as saying.
   Fadlallah is spiritual leader of Hezbollah, or Party of God. The
group is believed to be the umbrella organization for Shiite
militants holding most of the 18 foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   ``My feeling is that the American hostages issue will be
completely resolved just as the issue of the French hostages was,''
he was quoted as saying.
   The last three French hostages in Lebanon were freed May 4, a
few days before the French presidential election.
   Fadlallah was quoted as saying the United States and Iran were
bound to normalize relations now that the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war
is nearing an end.
   On Monday, an Anglican archbishop just back from a mission in
Tehran said Terry Waite, the kidnapped envoy of the Archbishop of
Canterbury, and the other hostages might be released by the end of
the year.
   ``I would not be surprised if Terry Waite and the others were
released before the end of the year,'' David Penman, the archbishop
for Melbourne, said in Canterbury, England.
   The Church of England last week sent Bishop David Brown to
Lebanon to speak to Christian leaders about four Iranians who
disappeared in a Christian-controlled zone outside Beirut in 1982.
They were presumed kidnapped, and there been unconfirmed reports
they were killed.
   In addition to the nine Americans, the 18 foreign hostages
include three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian, an Indian, a West
German and two unidentified men. The longest held is Terry A.
Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, who was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
