<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Sears-Brand Names,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears to Sell Brand Name Appliances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest
retailer, said it will start selling appliances and home
electronics made by other companies.
   Sixty national brands, including Sears' Kenmore appliances, will
be available Thursday at 13 Indiana stores, the company said Monday.
   That is a first step in a plan to sell other brands at its
stores nationwide, said Michael Bozic, chairman and chief executive
officer of Sears Merchandise Group.
   Telephones, stereo equipment, televisions, electronic office
equipment and kitchen appliances are among the products to be
offered, said Marvin Stern, a company vice president.
   Sears now operates 819 retail stores and more than 3,000 other
catalog and specialty stores in all 50 states and Puerto Rico,
company officials said.
   Sears holds 25 percent of the country's appliance market and its
Kenmore brand is the country's biggest seller.
