<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Carlucci 1stLd-Writethru a0474 08-02 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Defense Chief Sees Top-Secret Soviet Bomber</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Carlucci inspecting Soviet bomber,
war games. EDITS to trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet military unveiled its new top-secret
Blackjack bomber to U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci today and
staged thundering aerial and artillery displays at two bases
normally off-limits to foreigners.
   Carlucci spent about 10 minutes in the cockpit of the strategic
bomber while foreign reporters were allowed within about 50 yards
of the sleek white jet. Soviet military brass were clearly
uncomfortable with the access accorded the visitors and refused to
tell reporters anything about the plane.
   ``Why do you want to know about the bomber? Why frighten
people?'' asked Col. Gen. Boris F. Korolkov.
   He refused to identify the aircraft, whose only markings were a
red star and a No. 12 on the tail.
   The Pentagon's reference book Soviet Military Power says the
plane is the world's heaviest and largest bomber, but does not give
exact dimensions.
   Jane's All The World's Aircraft, a respected British reference
book, says the plane, codenamed Blackjack by NATO, is known in the
Soviet Union as the Tupolev strategic bomber. It says the jet is
177 feet long, has a wingspan of 182 feet and weighs 550,000 pounds.
   The aircraft has been under development for 10 years, can travel
twice the speed of sound, has a flying range of 4,500 miles and can
be armed with bombs and cruise missiles, according to Jane's.
   No Western official had been shown the plane before Carlucci's
visit to the Kubinka airfield 30 miles west of Moscow.
   Jane's and the U.S. Defense Deparment predicted the Blackjacks
would be deployed this year. Korolkov said they became operational
``recently.''
   Carlucci first inspected a MiG-29 Fulcrum fighter jet before
turning to the nearby Blackjack. As he did, two Blackjack bombers
flew overhead in formation in the partly cloudy blue sky, and the
roar of their engines broke the silence of the largely deserted
airfield.
   Carlucci inspected the underbelly of the four-engine Blackjack
and then climbed orange stairs into the open bomb bay doors and
entered the cockpit. He told reporters later he could not give
technical details of the plane but compared it to the B-1 bomber of
the United States in that it can fly at low altitudes and carry
heavy payloads.
   ``I'm not a qualified intelligence officer,'' said Carlucci, a
former senior official with the CIA. ``I'm not a qualified
observer. They let me sit in the cockpit but I couldn't tell one
instrument from another.''
   The American defense chief, who arrived in the Soviet Union on
Monday for a four-day visit, said the tour was largely symbolic.
   ``It's a way of continuing the dialogue between our two military
establishments,'' Carlucci said.
   The Soviet military chief of staff, Marshal Sergei F.
Akhromeyev, climbed aboard a B-1 bomber at Ellsworth Air Force Base
in South Dakota last month.
   At Kubinka, Carlucci also inspected an Ilyushin-78 tanker plane
and an Mi-26 helicopter, and was treated to an acrobatic flying
display by four MiG-29s.
   Next it was the army's turn to put on a show for Carlucci. He
drove to the Taman Motorized Division Headquarters 12 miles to the
southwest to watch noisy and dusty war games.
   Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov, the host of Carlucci's
visit, stood next to his American counterpart on a two-story
building overlooking a vast field. Soviet Mi-24 helicopter gunships
shot out from behind the buildings, guns firing, and artillery
shells bombarded targets in the field, spewing gray-black smoke and
dirt.
   ``It's not very comfortable to drive,'' quipped Yazov as
infantry fighting vehicles bumped along the dirt.
   After the display, Carlucci asked Yazov's 10-year-old grandson
if he wanted to shoot like the soldiers. The grandson, Oleg Losik,
appeared to be too shy to answer.
   Later, Oleg, wearing a military officer's jacket to keep warm,
told a reporter the war games were ``very interesting'' and that
they were only the second he'd seen.
   On Wednesday, Carlucci heads to the Soviet Crimean Peninsula,
where he will visit the headquarters of the Black Sea fleet.
   Among those traveling with Carlucci are Ron Lehman, assistant
secretary of defense, and representatives of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff and State Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
