<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NudeBeach     08-02 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nude Beach,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Nude Sunbathing Not A Constitutional Right</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nude sunbathing on public beaches is not
a constitutional right, according to a judge who refused to grant
an injunction that would have reopened an environmentally protected
area to naturists.
   ``While nudity is the privacy of one's own property and nudity
in the context of artistic expression may be protected, it seems
clear that nude sunbathing on a public beach is not a right of
constitutional dimension,'' U.S. District Judge Ernest C. Torres
wrote Monday.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service closed a one-mile stretch of
Moonstone Beach in South Kingstown from April 1 to Aug. 31. to
protect two species of shore birds, the piping plover and the least
tern.
   The New England Naturist Association sued the federal
government, claiming their constitutional rights were violated by
the closure, which included a narrow strip of beach traditionally
opened to nude sunbathers.
   ``In this case, it is not nude sunbathing that has been banned
on Moonstone Beach. What has been prohibited is any use of the
disputed area,'' the judge said.
   Torres, who heard testimony in May, said the naturists had
``failed to demonstate a likelihood of success'' for their case.
</TEXT>
