<DOCNO> AP880802-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0841EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusThefts     08-02 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Thefts,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Warns Man To Stay Away From Buses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says buses are so near to his heart
that he stole as many as 100 of them was ordered to keep them at
arm's length for 10 years or go to prison.
   Patrick Carl Johnson, 23, put on uniforms and persuaded bus
company officials to let him drive buses away from their lots,
sometimes on jaunts of several hundred miles, police said.
   Johnson told police he loves buses so much that he has stolen
dozens, perhaps nearly 100, since 1986, they said.
   Visiting District Judge Randy Stout on Monday banned Johnson
from buses for a decade.
   ``Next time you set your foot on a bus, or go around a bus, you
can go to prison for 10 years,'' he said.
   Johnson pleaded guilty to stealing a 1983 Trailways Eagle bus
worth $195,000 on June 11. His punishment was 10 years of
probation, 30 days in Harris County Jail, 300 hours of community
service and $200 restitution for a broken window.
   Johnson was arrested after an eight-minute chase through narrow,
congested streets in Houston, police Sgt. David J. Klinger said.
   ``The officers said, `This guy can really drive a bus,'''
Klinger said. ``Even on those narrow streets he didn't hit a thing
except one street sign.''
   The sign broke the window.
   ``He took all those buses, and the total damages were $200,''
Klinger marveled. ``That's probably a better history of damages
than most of their drivers have.''
   Johnson told police, Klinger said, that his love for buses stems
from the time his mother dated a bus driver, and Johnson, then 11,
rode for hours at a time.
   Klinger said Johnson told him he never sped and one occasion his
stolen bus broke down after he took a group of his relatives on an
outing. Johnson called the same wrecker company that Kerrville Bus
Co. uses.
   ``I didn't want just anybody towing that bus,'' Klinger quoted
Johnson as saying. ``They might have torn it up.''
   Prosecutor Don Calvert said Johnson was careful about
maintenance of the buses and washed and refueled them before they
were returned or abandoned.
</TEXT>
