<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Khomeini 1stld-Writethru a0529 08-02 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Khomeini, 1st ld-Writethru, a0529,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Rally In Support Of Khomeni</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTs date of Khomeini's return in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian media reports said millions of
people rallied across Iran today in support of Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini and the Islamic revolution that brought him to power.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency compared the
gatherings to the demonstrations that swept Iran when Khomeini
returned from exile on Feb. 1, 1979, after the overthrow of the
Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   ``History is once again repeated to mark another occasion _ `To
renew allegiance to the Imam,''' IRNA said.
   The rally in Tehran was organized by Ayatollah Hussein Ali
Montazeri in support of Khomeini's decision, announced July 18, to
accept a year-old U.N. resolution calling for a cease-fire in the
8-year-old Iran-Iraq war, the press reports said.
   A rally was also held in the western city of Ahvaz, where
President Ali Khamenei addressed the crowd. The Iranian reports
indicated demonstrations were held in other cities, but gave no
specifics.
   Those participating in Tehran converged on the city's Azadi
Square early today to recite verses from the Koran, chant slogans
and listen to a resolution outlining support for Khomeini.
   Many carried pictures of relatives and loved ones killed or
taken prisoner in the Iran-Iraq war, IRNA said. It said the crowds
were served water and soft drinks because of the heat and air force
helicopters whirred overhead, dropping flowers on the crowd.
   The resolution read in Tehran included promises to obey all
Khomeini's orders, to recognize Montazeri as his successor and to
seek peace in the war with Iraq.
   It also called for revenge against the United States and Saudi
Arabia for the death of Iranians at last year's Islamic pilgrimage
in Mecca and condemned the United States for shooting down an
Iranian passenger jet.
   A U.S. Navy ship shot down the plane July 3 in the mistaken
belief that it was an F-14 fighter jet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
