<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HighwayRobbery     08-02 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Robbery,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Toll Taker Opened Her Own Lanes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida Turnpike toll booth
manager took over a lane and pocketed up to $15,000 in tolls,
officials said.
   ``It was the Lorna J. Hoff Expressway,'' said Tim Valentine, a
Palm Beach State Attorney official who headed the investigation.
   Ms. Hoff, 33, admitted to having pilfered ``several hundred
dollars'' worth of tolls ``two or three'' times following her
promotion to toll booth manager in March.
   But state officials estimated she could have taken as much as
$15,000.
   Department of Transportation and state attorney's office
investigators arrested Ms. Hoff on April 2 as she left the Palm
Beach Gardens Interchange with $844 and 750 toll tickets, according
to Valentine.
   Prosecutors agreed to drop charges when Ms. Hoff offered to pay
back the $844 and participate in a pre-trial intervention program.
They took into account her 10-year employment with the DOT and no
prior criminal record.
   The DOT, however, refused to consent to the deal and is pursuing
grand theft charges against Ms. Hoff, who was dismissed from her
$17,394-a-year job.
   John Berry, DOT chief of toll facilities, explained that further
investigation showed that Ms. Hoff may have diverted tolls from a
single lane about 14 times.
   Berry said evidence indicated that Ms. Hoff, who as manager was
not supposed to work a toll booth, took regular attendants off the
schedule and put herself on an operating lane.
   Her alleged scam was noticed because the regular attendants were
logged in for the day's work, but their end-of-day receipts were
not reported. In addition, he said, other attendants at the
interchange reported Ms. Hoff's behavior as suspicious.
</TEXT>
