<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Kidnap     08-02 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Kidnap,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight-Year-Old Boy Freed After 17 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOCRI, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old Italian boy was released by
his abductors today in the mountains of Calabria after a 17-month
kidnapping that prompted appeals for his release by Pope John Paul
II.
   Marco Fiora, kidnapped in Turin on March 2, 1987, walked to a
forest ranger's station in the Aspromonte mountains after being
freed at about 8 a.m., police said.
   The boy was immediately taken to a police barracks in this
southern Italian town, where he was examined by a doctor and
pronounced in fair condition, according to Lt. Col. Sabato Palazzo.
   Italian news agencies reported the boy looked exhausted and
there were rope marks on his wrists. Wearing a dirty white shirt
and pants held up by a string, Marco was given a bath and clean
clothes by the wife of a police officer.
   ``Mama, I'm okay, but I'm so scared,'' he said to his mother,
Piera, who spoke with him by phone from Turin.
   Marco was kidnapped by a gang of masked and armed bandits as his
parents were driving him to school. Riding in two cars, the bandits
blocked the Fiori's vehicle, beat the parents and sped off with the
boy.
   The kidnappers demanded a ransom of about $4 million. Marco's
parents, who run a garage and bakery in Turin, said they were
unable to pay the high sum. In December, the family delivered
$220,000 as a first ransom installment.
   News agencies said the father, Gianfranco Fiora, arrived in
Calabria a few days ago to pay the second installment. But the
ransom was never paid, and the kidnappers apparently decided to
free the boy because extensive police patrols had begun in the area.
   Numerous public appeals were made for Marco's release during the
17 months, including several by the pope, who last made an appeal
during a Sunday blessing in February.
   In May, four people were arrested in Turin and Calabria on
charges of complicity in the kidnapping.
</TEXT>
