<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     08-02 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,1st Ld-Writethru,a0490,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Palestinian, Strike Shuts Down Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with troops killing Palestinian, other
details, editing to conform and tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed an 18-year-old
Palestinian and wounded four others in clashes in the occupied West
Bank today as Arabs closed businesses for a second day to protest
deportations.
   The clash occurred in the West Bank's largest city of Nablus,
where soldiers opened fire after a military patrol was stoned, said
an official at Nablus' Al Ittihad Hospital.
   The victim, identitied as Alla Edin Al Aghbar, was hit by a
bullet in the stomach, the hospital official said.
   Two other Palestinian teen-agers were hit in the legs by bullets
in the same clash today, the hospital official said. The army said
it was checking the reports.
   In a second incident, soldiers shot and wounded two Arabs in the
legs in the town of Dura after masked Palestinians stoned a patrol
and tried to prevent Arab laborers from boarding a bus to work in
Israel, Arab news reports said.
   The army confirmed the clash but said it had no further details.
   The death raised to 236 the number of Arabs killed since the
uprising broke out Dec. 8. Four Israelis also have died.
   In a move prompted by eight months of Palestinian unrest, King
Hussein of Jordan announced Sunday he was severing legal and
administrative links with the West Bank that he ruled until Israel
captured it in 1967.
   Pro-Jordanian Palestinians in the territory were angered by the
move, but a majority praised the monarch for ceding control over
them to the PLO. The uprising has been led by underground leaders
tied to the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Arabs shuttered their stores and halted public transportation
today to protest the expulsions Monday of eight reputed leaders of
the uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Israeli army's chief prosecutor said the eight Palestinians
were expelled to deter further violence in the territories.
   Lt. Col. Amnon Strasnov said on Israel army radio that Israel
had ``no choice'' but to expel the eight. Western countries,
including the United States, say Israel's deportation policy
violates human rights.
   ``This step of expulsion is definitely a deterrent. People fear
it more than lengthy detentions,'' Strasnov said.
   He added: ``From a legal standpoint, they (the deportees) could
not have been put on trial. There is no acceptable evidence for the
court.''
   He did not elaborate, but a military official said the eight
could not be taken to court because the evidence was either
top-secret or sketchy. The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Monday's expulsions brought to 29 the number of Palestinians
deported since the uprising began Dec. 8.
   The deportees, six from the West Bank and two from the Gaza
Strip, were flown by helicopter to southern Lebanon and then placed
in waiting taxis taking them further north.
   Also Monday, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres acknowledged that no
progress would be made in solving the Arab-Israeli conflict until
after the November elections in Israel and the United States.
   Hussein's decision was a setback for Peres' Labor Party which
had campaigned for the so-called ``Jordanian option'' _ resolving
the dispute with the Palestinians by negotiating with Jordan.
   But Peres suggested Jordan could be drawn back into the peace
process if Labor formed the next government. ``The elections will
determine if the Jordanian option is dead or not,'' Peres said.
   In a related development, state-run Jordan television cancelled
weather reports and a Palestinian program for the Israeli-occupied
territories, the television's news editor said today in Amman, the
Jordanian capital.
   The editor, Alfred Asfoor, said the cancellations were part of
Hussein's move to sever administrative and legal links.
   ``I am sure that Palestinians there are disturbed by our
action,'' he told The Associated Press, adding that the programs
might be aired again in the future.
</TEXT>
