<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-Schools     08-02 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Schools,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Dismisses 4,000 School Intelligence Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 teachers assigned to
maintain security at schools and colleges were relieved of the
additional duty today, officials said. Many of the appointees had
been accused of spying for the government.
   An Education Ministry official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the four-decade-old practice of having each public
school appoint one of its teachers to be responsible for
``maintaining school security'' was abolished to help promote
democracy on campuses.
   The ministry notified about 4,000 public colleges, elementary
and high schools throughout the island Monday to dismiss the
security officers, ministry officials said. The affected employees
will retain their jobs as teachers.
   Many of the security officers have been accused of filing false
reports on outspoken teachers who did not agree with the ruling
Nationalist Party and its authoritarian rule in Taiwan.
   The Association for Promoting Teachers' Rights has said the
security system has interfered with freedom of speech on campuses.
The association was formed by hundreds of teachers last year after
Taiwan lifted martial law.
</TEXT>
