<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-QE2,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>QE2 Sails For New York With New Propellers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Queen Elizabeth 2 sailed from the port of
Southampton today in the early morning hours, six hours late on its
first voyage to New York since new $3.5 million propellers were
installed.
   The luxury liner, which departed at 2 a.m., was delayed because
the crew was testing the propellers, according to Eric Flounders, a
spokesman for the ship's owner, the Cunard Steamship Co. PLC.
   More than 1,700 passengers paid up to $5,950 for the voyage.
   The 19-year-old liner last year underwent a $190 million
overhaul at Lloyd Werft shipyard in Bremerhaven, West Germany. The
liner was sent back last month after a new, fuel-saving type of
propeller caused problems.
   Flounders said LLoyd Werft refitted the QE2 with traditional
propellers at a cost of nearly $3.5 million.
</TEXT>
