<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GravityBooster 1stLd-Writethru a0479 08-02 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gravity Booster, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Uncover Force That Boosts Gravity's Pull</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts throughout to clarify, include mention of Boynton
research in Washington; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experiment beneath the Greenland ice
sheet has fueled the debate over the existence of a ``fifth force''
in nature, and whether gravity might be more complex than Sir Isaac
Newton thought.
   Researchers last year lowered a gravity meter down a 1\-mile
hole and found that gravity diminished faster than expected,
indicating a second pull at work and was being reduced as the meter
descended, geophysicist Mark Ander reported Monday at a meeting at
the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
   The strength of the second pull is about one-fiftieth that
conventionally assigned to gravity, said Ander. The force has been
measured over distances ranging from 1,600 to 5,500 feet, enhancing
gravity by up to 3.9 percent.
   Other experiments have raised the possibility of a fifth or even
a sixth that either attract or repel objects in contradiction to
Newton's theories. The four known forces are gravity;
electromagnetism, which holds atoms together; the strong nuclear
force that holds atomic nuclei together; and the weak nuclear
force, which causes radioactive decay.
   Los Alamos scientists said their discovery may be the
theoretical fifth force or a component of gravity.
   ``Either way, we're saying something pretty big, something you
don't say every day in physics,'' Ander told The Washington Post.
``We're saying we appear to have the cleanest evidence to date of
something that cannot be explained by Newtonian gravity.''
   A change in the understanding of gravity may help physicists
formulate a long-sought ``unified field theory'' to explain all the
forces of the universe in a single equation. It also might lead to
recalculation of the masses of the stars and planets, and new
estimates of the universe's age.
   ``Gravity could be more complicated than Newton or even Einstein
thought,'' said Richard Hughes, a physicist at Los Alamos.
   Newton suggested in 1687 that gravity causes all bodies to
attract each other and that the attraction increases as the weight
of the objects increase and the distance between them decreases. He
suggested that gravitational fields should decline slightly as a
body moves down a shaft, but concluded that gravitational
acceleration is always the same.
   Australian scientist Frank Stacey said he found discrepancies
when he measured gravitational fields in a mine shaft in 1981. He
reported that the fields dropped off more rapidly than Newton's
conclusions suggested.
   Newtonian theory says gravity should change in a certain way
because, as a meter goes down, there is less matter below it to
exert a pull.
   Paul Boynton, a University of Washington physicist-astronomer,
reported last year that he had found evidence of a force that would
make a feather fall ever so slightly faster than an iron ball.
   Boynton suspended a 3-inch metal ring horizontally at the base
of 400-foot granite cliff in the North Cascade mountains near
Index, Wash. Half of the ring was aluminum, the other half
beryllium. Both halves had the same mass, which is what gives an
object weight when the object is pulled by gravity.
   Newtonian theory says the two halves should have been pulled
toward the cliff equally if only gravity was working. The aluminum
half twisted slightly toward the cliff and the beryllium half
rotated away, suggesting a force acting on the basis of the two
halves' chemical composition.
   Donald Eckhardt of the Air Force Geophysical Laboratory reported
late last year that gravitational-field measurements made from a
2,000-foot TV tower also revealed discrepancies. And, like Stacey's
findings, it suggested a force that attracts rather than repels.
   Ander said the Greenland experiment was concluded before
Eckhardt released his findings and that the researchers had not
expected to find a force that enhances gravity's pull. ``That was a
big surprise,'' he said.
   Others working on the Greenland project with Los Alamos were the
Scripps Institution at the University of California at San Diego;
Amoco Production Co.; Air Force Geophysical Lab; and the National
Science Foundation.
   Another experiment is under way in the Pacific Ocean a few
hundred miles north of Hawaii, with gravity measurements two miles
deep, Ander said. Some preliminary results are expected by the end
of the year.
   The team also hopes to test a deep hole in Antarctica near the
Soviet Union's Vostok station during 1990-91, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
