<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0501 08-02 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Officials To Investigate Railroad's Safety Procedures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with railroad official's
explanation for lack of signal lights. Picks up 12th graf pvs,
`Dobranetski said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY TABOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTOONA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warning signals along the track could have
prevented a head-on collision of two freight trains that killed two
crewmen and forced as many as 2,000 people from their homes for
three days, an investigator said.
   The signal lights had been vandalized after Rock Island Lines
abandoned the line in 1980, said Dennis Shaffer, vice president for
marketing of Iowa Interstate Railroad, which took over the tracks
in 1984.
   Signal lights warn train operators of approaching traffic.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigator Edward
Dobranetski also said the trains wouldn't have crashed Saturday if
they had followed their schedules. ``We don't know if one left
early or the other was running late,'' he said.
   The railroad, Shaffer said Monday, had complied with Federal
Railroad Administration regulations by operating trains through
orders transmitted by radio or telephone from dispatchers.
   The westbound train was to have cleared the track by 11:56 a.m.
_ while the eastbound train was not to have left Altoona until
12:01 p.m., Dobranetski said. Federal investigators, he said,
planned to check police logs and canvass residents to determine
exactly when the trains crashed, he said.
   The tracks, just east of Altoona in central Iowa, were to be
reopened this afternoon, officials said.
   Residents were allowed to return home Monday night after
firefighters spent three days battling burning alcohol from two
tanker cars they feared might explode, said Police Chief Britt
Adair.
   The bodies of William Peers of Des Moines and Larry Buckingham
Jr. of Winterset were recovered from beneath tank cars, which each
held 20,000 gallons of denatured alcohol.
   Dobranetski also said his team was checking on the hazardous
materials in the train and the safety devices and operating methods
used by the railroad.
   The highly volatile alcohol kept the situation tense throughout
the weekend. Fears of explosion delayed attempts to recover the
bodies as fires continued to burn from escape valves in the tankers.
   One of the cars burned itself out Monday but a foot-high flame
continued to burn on the other until Monday night.
   Federal officials interviewed the two employees on the eastbound
train who jumped to safety before the collision, Orville Harger,
51, of Johnston, and Dennis Schrader of Indianola.
   Dobranetski declined to discuss the interviews. The NTSB is not
expected to issue a ruling on the accident's cause for six to nine
months.
   The crash occurred when the Council Bluffs to Chicago train,
pulling 78 cars, collided with the westbound Newton to Des Moines
train, pulling eight cars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru a0523 08-02 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0523,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Fails In Central American Consensus Bid To Condemn
Nicaragua</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf, bgng, Last week xxx etc., to CORRECT that
Senate Republican leaders are preparing legislation that would
provide $27 million in humanitarian aide and a $20 million setaside
for military assistance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George P. Shultz and four Central American
foreign ministers called for peace and democracy in the region in a
watered-down declaration lacking the denunciation of Nicaragua the
U.S. envoy had sought.
   In fact, the document they issued Monday during the secretary of
state's eight-hour stop did not even mention Nicaragua by name.
   Only at a later news conference was the country named when
Shultz expressed continued U.S. support for the Contra rebels, who
after nearly 7 years of war reached a preliminary cease-fire accord
in March with Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   Shultz flew today to Buenos Aires, Argentina, the second stop of
a nine-country tour of Latin America.
   The final version of the declaration _ signed by Shultz and the
foreign ministers of El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa
Rica after a three-hour meeting _ called for ``peace, democracy,
security, social justice and economic development'' in the region.
   In the statement, the parties ``reaffirmed that authentic
democracy require, among other requisites, political pluralism,
freedom of association, freedom of the press, an impartial justice
system that guarantees due process, an apolitical armed forces, an
honest and open electoral system and respect for human and
individual rights.''
   The Sandinistas have been criticized for maintaining a political
monopoly and suppressing dissent and talks with the Contras on
forging a lasting peace have stalled.
   Senate Republican leaders are working on legislation in Congress
which would provide the Contras with $27 million in humanitarian
aid and include an additional $20 million that would be set aside
for possible new military assistance. President Reagan has
indicated he supports such a bill.
   The last congressional appropriation for military aid ran out in
February. It has not been renewed, largely pending the outcome of a
year-old regional peace plan that has so far proved ineffective.
   Shultz said the Contras ``are an important element, expressing a
strong desire for freedom and democracy in Nicaragua and we
continue to support them.
   ``I didn't come here basically to discuss that subject, and we
didn't have very much discussion of it, although I certainly hope
that we will extend funding for the Contras.''
   Monday's 10-paragraph document differed sharply from an initial,
10-page draft that harshly criticized Nicaragua as failing to live
up to the peace plan the five Central American presidents signed
Aug. 7, 1987.
   The original draft, written shortly after Shultz's last visit to
the four countries, was softened at the insistence of Guatemala and
Costa Rica, which apparently felt tough language would encourage
the Sandinistas to adopt an even harder line.
   Honduras, which favors the hard line against Nicaragua, made
public some of the criticism of the Sandinistas contained in the
initial draft, calling Guatemala's and Costa Rica's attitude
``incomprehensible'' and ``strange.''
   A Honduran statement Sunday said the original draft criticized
Nicaragua for not separating its army from the governing party and
denounced ``subversion against democratic governments'' by
Nicaragua.
   Shortly after he arrived in Guatemala on Monday, Shultz
contrasted what he described as democracy and growing prosperity in
the four nations with Nicaragua, where he said nine years of
Sandinista rule have virtually destroyed the economy.
   In Nicaragua, President Daniel Ortega on Monday accused the
United States of trying to encourage anti-Sandinista aggression
with Shultz' visit.
   ``We hope that common sense might prevail, because to want to
sign a death sentence against Nicaragua, because the United States
wants one, would be the equivalent of signing a death sentence
against Central America,'' he said during a ceremony on the
Sandinista air force's ninth anniversary.
   Ortega expressed ``hope that these (Central American)
governments might be sufficiently reasonable and pragmatic so as
not to fall in the trap that the United States is laying in
Guatemala.''
   The United States and the four nations shared common goals of
democracy, the rule of law and economic progress, but admitted
problems existed in reaching those objectives, Shultz told
reporters shortly after he arrived, as he went into a meeting with
Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo.
   Shultz's 10-day trip will also take him to Uruguay, Brazil and
Bolivia, and back to Central America Aug. 8-9 for meetings with the
presidents of Costa Rica, Honduras and El Salvador.
</TEXT>
