<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Vandals 1stLd-Writerthru a0546 08-02 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Vandals, 1st Ld - Writerthru, a0546,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cemetery Workers Arrested In Vandalism To Aquino's Tomb</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs ``The president...'' to CORRECT quote.
Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Aquino was shot...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today arrested two cemetery
workers who allegedly damaged the tomb of President Corazon
Aquino's husband, the president's spokesman said.
   Sen. Benigno Aquino's tomb apparently was damaged in hopes the
vandalism would cause the firing of two security guards with whom
the cemetery workers had recently had a fight, presidential press
secretary Teodoro Benigno said.
   The vandalism occurred Friday and was discovered Saturday when
authorities at Manila Memorial Park cemetery received a telephone
warning that a bomb had been planted in Aquino's concrete tomb, a
military official said.
   Maj. Hernando Patawaran of the Presidential Security Group said
the vandals pried loose a slab of concrete from the top of the
tomb. He said explosives experts found no explosives.
   Workers reinforced the tomb with steel sheets and resealed it.
   Benigno said the vandalism upset Mrs. Aquino.
   ``The president was very much affected by the news that the tomb
... was vandalized because if there is any tomb in the Philippines
today that draws universal respect and admiration, it is the tomb
of Ninoy,'' Benigno said. Ninoy was the former senator's nickname.
   Aquino was shot and killed at Manila airport on Aug. 21, 1983 as
he returned from three years of voluntary exile in the United
States. The murder fueled opposition to President Ferdinand Marcos
which culminated in the civilian-military revolt that ended his
20-year rule in February 1986 and propelled Mrs. Aquino to power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
