<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Dearden     08-02 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Dearden,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Dies After Battle With Cancer</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT4 of Aug. 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John Dearden, considered one of
America's most influential Roman Catholic leaders for his role in
modernizing church doctrines, left behind accomplishments that will
stand for centuries, church officials said.
   Dearden died from pancreatic cancer Monday. He was 80.
   ``As time goes by, Dearden's place becomes even greater,'' said
the Rev. Richard McBrien, chairman of the theology department at
the University of Notre Dame. ``He was already perhaps the leading
Catholic bishop when he retired. In the last several years, his
reputation has only grown. He was a giant.''
   Dearden, who headed the Archdiocese of Detroit from 1959 to
1981, voted in the elections of two popes and played a major role
in the Second Vatican Council, which from 1962 to 1965 launched
extensive doctrine changes, including departure from the Latin
Mass, greater emphasis on laypersons' roles and fostering greater
unity among all Christians.
   ``His work will be remembered for a long time,'' said Michael
Ghering, director of communications for the Grand Rapids Diocese.
``I think the most important thing right now is for the faithful of
the diocese to join together and remember him in prayer.''
   Dearden decided to become a priest when he was 16. He joined the
priesthood in Cleveland in 1932 and was a bishop in Pittsburgh
before coming to Detroit, where he worked to combat discrimination
and develop programs to help inner-city blacks.
   While considered liberal by some members of the church, he was
known to others as ``Iron John'' for his strict adherence to
traditional church rules and discipline.
   Dearden officially retired as archbishop of the 1.2
million-member archdiocese in 1980 after suffering a heart attack.
He continued to administer the diocese until May 1981, when he was
succeeded by Edmund Szoka, who was elevated in June to cardinal.
   Dearden founded the National Conference of Catholic Bishops and
was its president from 1966 to 19871. The conference worked to
adopt Vatican II philosophies in the United States and currently
addresses social, political and economic issues within the context
of Christian principles.
   Pope Paul VI named Dearden a cardinal in 1969.
   Dearden will lie in state at the Blessed Sacrament Cathredral
until Friday, when burial is scheduled at Holy Sepulchre Cemetery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
