<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0548 08-02 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Gunned Down at Apartment Complex</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with officer's death, quotes
from official; picks up 6th graf pvs, `A man...;' EDITS last graf
to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT G. WIELAND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An officer known as the oldest rookie in the force
died today of injuries from a shootout that left another man
mortally wounded, marking the fourth fatal attack on Dallas police
this year, authorities said.
   Officer Walter Williams, 47, was ambushed Monday night in the
parking lot of an apartment complex where he was investigating a
disturbance call, said Capt. John Holt.
   Williams, a five-year veteran of the department, was taken off
life support systems early today and died a few hours later, said
Lou Caudell, acting police chief. Two of the officer's three
children, his brother and his wife were at the hospital.
   Caudell said Williams joined the force in 1983 at age 42, making
him the oldest rookie. ``The younger guys called him `grandpa' and
stuff like that, but he liked it,'' Caudell said.
   A man whose name was being withheld was shot numerous times by
police and died at Parkland Memorial Hospital Monday night, Holt
said.
   Williams was answering a disturbance call at an apartment
complex when the shooting began about 10 p.m., Holt said. He and
his partner, officer Terry Caldwell, were talking to one of the
residents when they heard gunshots and went to investigate, Holt
said.
   They encountered a wounded woman on the way.
   ``One officer continued downstairs to investigate the
gunshots,'' he said. ``The second officer took the wounded woman
and placed her in apartment 206 where she would be safe and he
followed his partner downstairs.''
   But, as the second officer went downstairs, he heard more shots,
Holt said.
   ``As he got downstairs and rounded the corner he saw his partner
on the ground,'' the captain said.
   The second officer didn't see a suspect and called for
assistance.
   One of the assisting officers also was fired upon, Holt said.
   ``That man then charged the officers trying to get into the car
where the officer was going to get on the radio. The officers
returned fire _ a total of five officers returned fire _ he was
shot numerous times,'' Holt said.
   In January, off-duty Officer James Joe was killed while working
as a security guard at an apartment complex. Less than two weeks
later, Officer John Chase was shot to death by a homeless man who
police and witnesses said took his gun during a routine traffic
stop. And another officer was shot to death as he worked off-duty
at a grocery warehouse in west Dallas.
   Williams, who is from Elmore City, Okla., spent 20 years in the
military before entering police work.
</TEXT>
