<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hamadi     08-02 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Witness Links Hamadi to TWA Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second witness in the trial of
Mohammed Ali Hamadi has linked the defendant to the 1985 hijacking
of a TWA airliner to Beirut, according to evidence presented in
court today.
   Also today, court spokesman Falk Thomas told reporters that
pilots of the hijacked jet are scheduled to testify in September.
   Hamadi is charged with air piracy and murder in the June 1985
commandeering of TWA Flight 847 to the Lebanese capital. His trial
entered its fourth week today.
   Questioning witness Hazma Kassin, a Palestinian, Chief Judge
Heiner Mueckenberger read from a police report on Kassin's
recounting of a conversation with Hamadi's older brother, Abbas.
   Abbas was convicted in April of kidnapping two West Germans in
Beirut in an attempt to force West Germany to free his younger
brother.
   Quoting the police report, Mueckenberger told Kassim: ``You told
police, `Abbas told me that Mohammed was arrested because he was a
hijacker of the American airplane. Abbas said Mohammed is to be
extradited to the United States. Abbas didn't say how he knew about
this, but I assume that he had heard it from Mohammed.'''
   Kassim responded: ``It could be that I told that to the police.''
   ``Are you afraid to repeat it?'' Mueckenberger asked.
   ``No, but I can't remember now,'' Kassim said in the heavily
guarded Frankfurt courtroom.
   Kassim said he lived in Lebanon before coming to Germany in
1979. He now lives in the town of Merzig in Saarland state, near
the former residence of Abbas Hamadi.
   Mueckenberger said police questioned Kassim after Mohammed
Hamadi's arrest in January 1987, but did not specify the date.
   Last week Gaazi Yazbeck, a Lebanese man who lives in West
Germany and knows the two Hamadis, said that Abbas told him
Mohammed had ``something to do'' with the hijacking.
   ``He (Abbas) just said it, he was sort of bragging,'' Yazbeck
told the court. He said the conversation occurred at a bar in
Saarland state a few weeks after the hijacking.
   Mohammed Hamadi, who lived in West Germany from 1982 to 1984,
has not been asked directly about the hijacking.
   Flight 847 was seized after taking off from Athens on June 14,
1985, and diverted to Beirut. The gunmen killed U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem and held 39 Americans hostage for 17 days.
   Three other men who were allegedly involved in the hijacking
remain at large.
   Mohammed Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport on Jan. 13,
1987, after customs officials discovered liquid explosives in his
luggage.
   In a brief exchange today, Mueckenberger asked Hamadi if he had
been sick. The defendant responded: ``I don't want to discuss this
in public.''
   Thomas later said Hamadi has been ill and requested hospital
treatment when the court recesses for four weeks on Aug. 9. He
declined to specify the nature of the illness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
