<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PatientsRefused     08-02 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Patients Refused,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Turns Away Burn Victims Because of Nurse Shortage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two critically burned patients were turned away
from the only hospital in Denver with a special burn unit because
of a shortage of nurses.
   ``We are absolutely stretched to the limit,'' Sue Browning,
associate director of University Hospital, said Monday. ``We never
go on divert unless we are absolutely forced to do so.''
   Mark Bell, 17, with burns over 60 percent of his body, and
Clarence Kellogg, 76, with burns over 30 percent, were brought to
St. Anthony Hospital Central, which does not have a special burn
unit. St. Anthony officials tried unsuccessfully to get them
admitted to University's burn unit Monday.
   Bell, Kellogg and Mark Troudt, 25, suffered burns in an
explosion at Kellogg's home. A pilot light apparently ignited fumes
from a lacquer sealer the men were applying in the basement.
   Troudt suffered minor burns.
   Browning said staffing could not be arranged and even the most
serious emergencies are no exception under University Hospital's
new policy of diverting ambulances and patients. Only four of the
five beds in the burn unit were occupied.
   ``We don't have enough nurses to staff all the beds in the
hospital,'' Browning said. ``We are accepting every patient we can
possibly provide safe care for.''
   The two men remained at St. Anthony, officials said.
</TEXT>
