<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MspiKidnapping     08-02 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mspi Kidnapping,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Unheard From Three Days Before Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers of the wife of a
multimillionaire businessman have yet to tell him how much or where
to pay her ransom, even though only three days remain before their
deadline, officials said.
   ``There's been no contact,'' Wayne Taylor, special
agent-in-charge of the FBI in Mississippi, said Monday. ``We've got
leads, but no contact.''
   Taylor said a lack of communication was common in kidnapping
cases.
   FBI agents and police are investigating the disappearance of
Annie Laurie Hearin, 72. She was last seen by the family maid on
July 26.
   That day, Robert Hearin returned home and discovered a rambling,
typewritten letter and blood stains near the front door. The letter
said Hearin had wronged various groups and must pay several
individuals _ among them actor Vincent Price _ an unspecified
amount of money.
   If Hearin complied, his wife of 48 years would be returned after
10 days, the letter said.
   No further instructions arrived.
   Mrs. Hearin suffers an intestinal disorder known as ileitis, and
requires daily medication. Without medication, a person with the
condition would develop diarrhea and eventually could dehydrate and
die.
   Area churches have prayed for the safe return of Mrs. Hearin and
7-year-old Daffany Tullos, who also has been missing from her
Jackson home since July 26. Police say they don't believe the cases
are related.
   As president and chief executive officer of Mississippi Valley
Gas, Hearin's net worth is more than $100 million.
</TEXT>
