<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0510 08-02 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0510,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Official Calls For Maintaining Palestinian Rights In Jordan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Egypt calling for
Jordanian-PLO coordination. Pick up 5th pvs, The last...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO said today it is calling a special
session of its parliament to discuss King Hussein decision to cut
Jordan's legal and administrative links with the Israeli-occupied
West Bank.
   Egypt, meanwhile, called for coordination between Jordan and the
Palestine Liberation Organization in efforts to achieve Middle East
peace.
   A statement issued in Cairo by Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said Hussein's announcement Sunday did not mean Jordan
was abandoning its role in the quest for a Palestinian settlement.
   ``The advancement of the peace process ... requires a unified
Arab front based primarily on effective Jordanian-Palestinian
coordination,'' the statement said.
   The director of the PLO's Baghdad office, Azzam al-Ahmad, said
the organization's Central Council called for a meeting of the
400-plus member National Council within a month. The decision was
made during two days of meetings in Baghdad.
   The last National Council session, held in Algeria, came late
last year before the Palestinian uprising began Dec. 8 in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. The Central Council is the upper branch of the
bicameral National Council.
   On Monday, PLO foreign relations chief Farouk Kaddoumi called
during a closed Central Council meeting for the maintenance of
rights of Palestinians living in Jordan, PLO officials said on
condition they not be identified.
   King Hussein, in a televised speech, said he was cutting ties
with Palestinians in the West Bank because the PLO should be
primarily responsible for them.
   The PLO has been leading the uprising in Israel's occupied
lands. Most of the 850,000 Palestinians in the West Bank have
Jordanian passports, use Jordanian money and worship in
Jordanian-supported mosques.
   The Israelis do not recognize the PLO, but moderates among them
have expressed a willingness to talk peace with a
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation.
   On Saturday, Hussein dissolved Jordan's lower house of
parliament. Half of the 60 members of the Chamber of Deputies were
Palestinians from the West Bank. Three days earlier, he canceled a
$1.3 billion development project for the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In his speech Sunday, the king said, ``Jordan is not Palestine.
The independent Palsetinian state will be established on occupied
Palestinian land after its liberation, God willing.''
   The PLO sources said Kaddoumi praised Jordan's ``distinguished''
relations with the world's 5 million Palestinians and the PLO and
said, ``These relations will remain.''
   They said Kaddoumi emphasized the importance of maintaining
``all the rights acquired by the Palestinian people in Jordan.''
   More than half of Jordan's residents are refugees or immigrants
from Palestine and there are fears Hussein's action could lead to a
loss of some of the rights they now have.
   PLO officials said PLO chief Yasser Arafat has ordered PLO
officials not to make any public comment on Hussein's action until
the Executive Committee, which serves as a Cabinet, can review the
possible consequences.
   They said Arafat had canceled a trip planned to the Jordanian
capital of Amman next week.
   Kaddoumi also was quoted by the PLO sources as saying support by
some Arab governments for the Palestinian uprising was ``below
required levels.''
   They said he accused Syria of undermining the insurrection by
sponsoring attacks by PLO dissident factions on Beirut refugee
camps held by Arafat loyalists.
   ``Syria's role in the attacks against Palestinian camps is clear
as the sun itself,'' Kaddoumi was quoted as saying.
   ``If they (the Syrians) are really after strategic parity (with
Israel), they should have dropped their anti-PLO policies,
especially during the uprising.''
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
