<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--DrugTests-Police     08-02 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Drug Tests-Police,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>200 Police Applicants Fail Drug Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 police applicants were
rejected after admitting they used illegal drugs or testing
positive for illegal drug use, a department spokesman said.
   A total of 640 people applied to become officers during a recent
recruitment drive.
   Urine tests showed that some applicants used cocaine, marijuana
or prescription drugs not issued to them, Chief John Pialorsi said
Monday. Others admitted during polygraph examinations they had used
illegal drugs.
   The urine samples were tested by the sheriff's office; the
results were verified by an independent laboratory.
   Sheriff Jim McMillan said he was not surprised. ``That shows you
just what we've been saying about the drug problem out there,'' he
said.
   But the sheriff said he does not think that drug use is a
problem among those who already wear police uniforms, although the
department does not test officers for drug use because of
constitutional questions.
   Testing of applicants is required by state law.
</TEXT>
