<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JudicialConference     08-02 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judicial Conference,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Justice Speaks In Favor Of Alternatives To Court Trials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arbitration and other methods of solving
legal disputes should be explored to save time and money for an
already overburdened judicial system, Chief Justice William
Rehnquist said today.
   State courts must lead the way, he told participants at the
annual Conference of Chief Justices.
   ``They have to be the pioneers in this,'' he said.
   Rehnquist called such alternatives to civil trials ``the wave of
the future.''
   However, Rehnquist said alternatives cannot be used in some
cases, such as those involving legal aid and complicated matters
such as the breakup of the American Telephone & Telegraph Co., but
can be a solution ``for the great body of cases.''
   Seventy to 90 percent of all civil cases are settled before
trial, said Carl F. Bianchi, administrative director of Idaho state
courts, but what is new is the ``enthusiastic packaging and
selling'' of alternatives.
   Bianchi said there are more than 800 alternative programs around
the country, ranging from state-financed programs to a canine court
in Los Angeles, which uses an animal trainer to solve disputes
between dog owners and plaintiffs.
   While half the nation's law schools offer courses in dispute
resolution, a Harvard Law School professor said he believed
attorneys will not encourage alternatives to trial because that
results in smaller fees.
   ``The pressure for change is going to come from judges and
courts and court administrators on the one hand, and from clients
on the other hand,'' said Frank E.A. Sander, who also is chairman
of the American Bar Associaton's Standing Committee on Dispute
Resolution.
   Rehnquist also told participants that a committee of the
Judicial Conference of the United States, chaired by retired
Justice Louis Powell, has been appointed to look into the review
process of capital punishment cases.
   The committee will try to determine if the combined review
process of capital sentences in state and federal courts takes too
much time, and ``whether there's coherence and rationality'' in the
process, Rehnquist said.
   Rehnquist said the U.S. Supreme Court ruled 12 years ago that
capital punishment was constitutional and that he believes courts
should not stop executions.
   The highest judge or justice in each of the 50 states, the
District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands, American
Samoa and Guam were invited to attend the five-day conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
