<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalWaste 1stLd-Writethru a0509 08-02 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Waste, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>50 Hospitals Illegally Dumping Infectious Waste</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates and adds quotes throughout, confirming published
report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half the city's 83 private and
municipal hospitals have been sending infectious waste out with
regular garbage, city officials confirmed today.
   The Environmental Control Board has fined 50 hospitals a
combined $481,000 from November 1985 to May of this year for the
illegal practice, the Sanitation Department said, confirming a
report in today's New York Post.
   ``This has been a problem for a long, long time,'' said Andrew
McCarthy, spokesman for the state Department of Environmental
Conservation. ``It's getting attention now because of the beach
problems.''
   Hospitals that have been fined lose their city pickup service
for as long as six months, forcing them to use more expensive
private carriers, said Vito Turso, spokesman for the Sanitation
Department.
   None of the 40 state-licensed, private infectious-waste carriers
are monitored by the Sanitation Department.
   Brooklyn U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney said last week that his
office is investigating whether ``criminality in the carting
industry'' may be partly to blame for the medical waste that has
been washing ashore this summer, forcing the closure of beaches in
New York, New Jersey and Connecticut.
   City law requires that infectious hospital waste be
``red-bagged'' _ separated from general waste and removed out of
state or incinerated under controlled conditions at a temperature
of at least 2,000 degrees.
</TEXT>
