<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Coleman     08-02 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coleman,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parole Denied For Wayne Carl Coleman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parole board announced today it has denied
parole for Wayne Carl Coleman, originally sentenced to die for his
part in the 1973 slayings of six members of a family but sentenced
to life in prison following a retrial.
   The decision by the Board of Pardons and Paroles, reached July
22, also said the panel would not review Coleman's case again for
eight years _ in July 1996.
   Coleman was one of three men originally convicted of murder and
sentenced to death for the May 14, 1973, slayings of six members of
the Ned Alday family. A federal appeals court ordered them retried
in 1985.
   Coleman and George Elder Dungee both received life sentences
this year. Carl Isaacs, alleged to be the mastermind, was again
sentenced to death.
   Parole board spokesman Silas Moore said Coleman's case came up
for an automatic review by the board when the retrial jury imposed
a life sentence. Coleman has already served 15 years in prison, and
prisoners are eligible for parole consideration after seven years.
   Policy allows the board to set future review dates from one to
eight years in the future.
   Coleman was notified of the action in a letter dated July 22.
Moore said the decision was not announced until today because most
of the board's administrative officers were at a seminar away from
the Capitol last week.
</TEXT>
