<HEAD>IRA Attack Injures Six Soldiers In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with IRA claim of responsibility, other
details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected land mine blew up
an army Land Rover in the County Tyrone village of Carland this
morning, slightly injuring six part-time soldiers, police said.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility for
the attack in a message to news organizations.
   On Monday, an IRA bomb ripped through a British army barracks in
north London, killing one soldier and injuring nine.
   After this morning's attack, the soldiers struggled out of the
Land Rover and guerrillas lying in ambush opened fire with machine
guns. Soldiers in the vehicle that was attacked or in another
nearby army Land Rover returned fire, a police spokesman said. The
guerrillas escaped.
   Police said the six members of the locally recruited Ulster
Defense Regiment were treated for minor injuries at South Tyrone
Hospital in Dungannon and released. One suffered a broken arm.
   The police spokesman, who by custom was not identified, said the
explosion occurred at 9:30 a.m. on the Cookstown Road in Carland, 4
miles from Dungannon and about 35 miles west of Belfast, where at
least two army Land Rovers were on patrol.
   The area was sealed off and security forces were investigating,
the spokesman said.
   Last month near Coalisland, a few miles away, security forces
found an 800-pound bomb abandoned by the IRA because cattle had
eaten through the command wires.
</TEXT>
