<2ND_LINE>PM-Trooper Arrested,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dog Finds Cocaine on FHP Trooper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state trooper was in custody today after a
drug-sniffing dog found six kilograms of cocaine in her rental car,
an FBI spokesman said.
   Jacqueline Denise Robinson, 27, of Miami, was already under
surveillance by the Florida Highway Patrol and FBI and was spotted
receiving a package from a man at the Florida Turnpike's Pompano
Beach rest station Monday afternoon, said FBI spokesman Joe Del
Campo.
   She then headed north on the Turnpike, but her rental car broke
down and an trooper with a drug-sniffing dog named Ulf stopped to
help.
   Ms. Robinson flashed her FHP identification, but the dog smelled
drugs, and a search of the car turned up six kilograms of cocaine,
said Del Campo.
   The arrest was coincidental to the investigation, said the
agent. He said he had no information on the man who allegedly
handed her the package.
   Ms. Robinson, who had been on the force for a year, was
suspended at the scene by FHP Commander Col. Bobby Burkett, said
Del Campo, and was taken to the Dade County Jail.
   She was charged with possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute, and if convicted faces a minimum mandatory sentence of
10 years up to a life term, and a possible fine of $4 million.
