<HEAD>U.S., Thai Troops on War Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAKORN RATCHASIMA, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. jet fighters streaked
across rainy skies to strafe a hill in northeastern Thailand on
Tuesday, as U.S. and Thai forces climaxed war games aimed at
repelling a supposed invasion of Thailand.
   The half-dozen F-16 fighters were joined by helicopters, armored
personnel carriers and tanks in the assault on the hill in Nakhorn
Ratchasima, 140 miles from Bangkok.
   The exercise is the seventh of an annual series dubbed ``Cobra
Gold,'' and this year involves 15,000 troops.
   The exercise began last month, and on July 23, 400 Thai and
American marines assaulted a beach in Cholburi province about 80
miles south of Bangkok.
   The radio station of the Vietnamese-installed government in
Cambodia has condemned the games as ``hostile acts.''
   Thailand considers the 9{-year-old Vietnamese occupation of
Cambodia its top security threat. To bolster its defense
capabilities, Thailand recently took delivery of a squadron of
F-16s bought from the United States, its key Western ally.
