<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Writers     08-02 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Writers,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PEN President Says Writers Won Victory Against Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Polish PEN Writer's
club, banned by the government five years ago, said Tuesday that
official permission to resume the group's activities was won
without concessions.
   ``We have won a victory,'' said Juliusz Zulawski, who was the
club's president when the group ran afoul of communist authorities
in the early 1980s.
   ``It is very important because this happened without any
concessions on our part,'' Zulawski told The Associated Press in an
interview.
   Minister of Culture Aleksander Krawczuk gave Zulawski, 77, a
letter Monday from the mayor of Warsaw authorizing the writer to
hold new elections for the club's leadership.
   ``There were no political conditions. There will be free
elections (of new club officers), probably this September,'' he
said.
   The government suspended the club's activities in 1981 when
martial law was imposed and banned it in 1983, charging it had been
taken over by anti-government and anti-socialist elements.
   Since the club was banned, its offices and official charter have
been overseen by a government commision.
   ``The commission was removed yesterday and I have full access to
our office,'' Zulawski said.
   He declined to speculate on why the government had decided to
recognize the group again, adding that its membership has remained
the same.
   A softening in the government position was signaled in June,
when an official newspaper printed a letter from 150 writers and
intellectuals demanding the club's reactivization.
   After the government banned the club, its members and the
international PEN Organization refused to recognize the new
commission.
   Zulawski said the international group will recognize the
reformed club and its leaders.
   He said the future of the club is far from certain.
   ``It is impossible to predict whether the government will
interfere again,'' he said. ``No one knows what will happen.''
</TEXT>
