<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeathPenalty     08-02 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Penalty,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Reverses One Bey Conviction, Orders Resentencing On
Second</HEAD>
<BYLINE>JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court today reversed one
conviction of the youngest murderer sentenced to die under New
Jersey's 6-year-old capital punishment law, but ordered him
resentenced _ possibly to death _ for a second slaying.
   The court ruled that Marko Bey's constitutional rights were
violated when police persisted in questioning him about the slaying
of 19-year-old Cheryl Alston of Asbury Park, despite his wish to
remain silent.
   Because of the improper interrogation, the court ruled, Bey's
confession to beating and strangling Miss Alston with her bra
should not have been admitted into evidence. The court reversed the
conviction and sent the case back to the lower court for a new
trial.
   The court also ruled that Bey, who was 17 at the time of the
Alston slaying, should not have been subject to the death penalty
because he was a minor. After the murders, the Legislature modified
the death penalty so convicted murderers cannot receive a death
sentence if they are under 18 at the time of the homicide.
   But Bey remains exposed to a possible death sentence for the
murder of Carol Peniston, 46, of Asbury Park. Bey turned 18 less
than two weeks after Miss Alston died on April 2, 1983, and about
two weeks before murdering Mrs. Peniston.
   Although the court ruled the conviction for Mrs. Peniston's
murder should stand, it reversed Bey's death sentence for that
killing because of a trial error. But the court ordered him
resentenced and said he could again receive the death penalty.
   ``We're real pleased that the conviction was reversed in the
Alston case. We would have been more pleased had the conviction
been reversed in Peniston as well,'' said Bey's attorney, Judith
Borman.
   Citing a recent decision by the U.S. Supreme Court, the state
court ruled that instructions given the jury could have prompted
them unfairly to dismiss factors about Bey that may have caused
them to be more lenient.
   In death penalty cases, juries first decide the guilt or
innocence of the defendant. If guilty, a sentencing phase is held
during which defense lawyers present evidence of mitigating factors
to support sparing the defendant's life, while prosecutors present
aggravating factors that would warrant a death sentence.
   The court ruled that in the sentencing phase of the case
involving Mrs. Peniston's death, the judge improperly told the jury
it must agree unanimously if it is to consider a mitigating factor.
   Bey is one of 29 people on death row in Trenton State Prison. He
was the youngest inmate on death row until the conviction of Philip
Dixon, 21, last year of sexually assaulting, stabbing with a
railroad spike and then drowning a 13-year-old girl.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-YonkersDeseg 2ndLd-Writethru a0590 08-02 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0590,0831</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Finds Yonkers In Contempt Over Desegregation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with 2 grafs to update with council members
found in contempt. Subs 9th graf, `Sand insisted...' with 1 graf
and grafs 17-18, `Vice Mayor...' with 1 graf to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge found the city of Yonkers in
contempt of court today because the City Council failed to pass a
housing desegregation resolution.
   Calling Yonkers ``a national symbol of defiance to civil
rights,'' U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand imposed a fine of $100 a
day, doubling daily, to begin today. The fine would surpass the
city's $337 million operating budget by the 23rd day.
   The Yonkers City Council voted Monday night against endorsing a
court-ordered desegregation plan for 800 units of affordable
housing to be built by private developers throughout the city north
of New York City.
   Three of four council members who voted against the resolution
also were found in contempt today and fined $500 per day, beginning
today. The fourth, Vice Mayor Henry Spallone, was given at least a
one-day adjournment to hire a lawyer.
   ``The city of Yonkers is in contempt because it chooses to be in
contempt,'' Sand said after a one-hour hearing in federal court in
Manhattan. ``It does not find itself inadvertently in that
position.''
   An attorney representing the city, Michael Sculnick, had argued
against the contempt ruling, saying, ``Fines of that magnitude are
devastating and will bankrupt the city in three weeks.''
   Earlier, Yonkers Mayor Nicholas Wasiscko had said he hoped the
judge would see ``good faith'' in the closeness of the 4-3 vote and
delay the fines.
   Wasiscko, who voted for the desegregation plan, said he would
call for another council meeting this week to reconsider the issue.
   Sand insisted the fines were ``remedial, not punitive,'' because
they would end if the council changed its vote. Sand has said that
if the defiant council members remained in contempt until Aug. 10,
they would face prison.
   Monday's vote came after a raucous hourlong meeting highlighted
by shouts and jeers from the 150 people in the chambers and about
300 outside. One person was arrested for disorderly conduct and one
person was ejected from the meeting.
   In 1980, the U.S. Justice Department charged that Yonkers, a
city of 195,000 people, had intentionally segregated its housing
and schools for 40 years.
   The east side of the state's fourth-largest city is
predominately white, middle to upper class. It borders the wealthy
towns of Scarsdale and Bronxville. The west side is older, more
industrial, and mostly black and Hispanic. It adjoins New York
City's poorest borough, the Bronx.
   In 1985, Sand found Yonkers liable. It was the first time school
and housing segregation were linked.
   The city's Board of Education began an integration plan in 1986.
That year, Sand ordered the city to build 200 units of low-income
housing on the east side and 800 others throughout the city _ 160
low-income homes, the rest for moderate incomes.
   Sand ordered the council to pass a resolution by Monday
supporting the plan. It could not pass the actual plan because it
must first hold a state-mandated public hearing before voting on a
zoning matter.
   The council has wavered in the face of public opinion.
   Spallone, the judge's most vociferous critic, demanded an
investigation into the city's low-income housing and into Sand's
law practice. Spallone charged that Sand was violating state law by
forcing the vote before the public hearing.
   ``The judge feels above the law,'' he told a cheering crowd.
``This judge can no longer address this case.''
   Council member Peter Chema said it was not ``solely a black and
white issue, but a green issue'' that involves real estate
development.
   Chema said Sand, who lives in the exclusive Westchester enclave
of Pound Ridge, was being ``autocratic not democratic.''
   Council member Nicholas Longo called Sand's actions ``a typical
case of the hypocrisy of the rich and elitist looking down upon
those who must work for everything they have.''
   While six of the seven council members, including Wasiscko,
campaigned last November on opposing Sand, the council agreed to a
consent decree in January after Sand threatened to fine the city
into bankruptcy.
   But residents vehemently against the decree began showing up in
force at council meetings, sent bullets in the mail to the
councilmembers and picketed Sand's Manhattan and Pound Ridge homes,
causing some of the councilmembers to backtrack.
   Even the U.S. Supreme Court's refusal to hear the city's appeal
hasn't daunted opponents of the housing.
   Sand proposed creating an independent commission to build the
housing to circumvent city politicians.
   But the Justice Department argued that a commission would be
``effectively letting the city off the hook once again'' and would
allow the city to ``flout with impunity'' the court order.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
