<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Namibia 1stLd-Writethru a0619 08-02 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Namibia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>South Africa Offers To Begin Withdrawing From South-West Africa On
Nov. 1</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 8 grafs with additional detail.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa has offered to
begin withdrawing its troops from South-West Africa on Nov. 1,
Foreign Minister Pik Botha said today.
   Botha said South Africa made the offer today in Geneva during a
new round of peace talks on southern Africa. The talks involve
South Africa, Angola, Cuba and U.S. mediators.
   Botha also said the South African proposal calls for elections
in South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, on June 1 next year.
   ``It follows that the total withdrawal of Cuban troops from
Angola will be completed by June 1, 1989,'' Botha said.
   An estimated 50,000 Cuban troops now are in Angola supporting
the country's Marxist government.
   Botha said the South Africans want a cease-fire in the
13-year-old Angolan war to go into effect Aug. 10.
   Botha said this would give United Nations almost three months to
prepare for the implementation of U.N. Resolution 435, which calls
for South Africa to grant independence to Namibia.
   South Africa and the United States support the rebels of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in
their fight against the Angolan government. An estimated 3,000
South African troops are in southern Angola fighting alongside
UNITA.
   Botha gave no indication how the Cubans and Angolans have
responded to the South African offer.
   However, the offer is the first time South Africa has offered a
specific date for the implementation of Resolution 435.
   South Africa, backed by the United States, has insisted that
independence for Namibia must be linked with a Cuban troop
withdrawal from Angola.
   Cuba and Angola have said that such a withdrawal could take up
to four years, while the South Africans and the United States are
seeking a much shorter timetable.
   South Africa's mandate over South-West Africa was terminated by
the United Nations in 1966. But in defiance of several U.N.
Security Council resolutions, it has retained control of the
country, which possesses considerable mineral wealth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
