<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0602 08-02 0970</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0602,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Gives Bush Campaign Present: Plant-Closing Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds full identification of Dukakis in 5th graf, On the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, nearing the Republican presidential nomination,
flew to Chicago today for a foreign policy speech after receiving a
campaign present from President Reagan.
   While Bush headed west for what aides said would be a major
address, Reagan said he had decided to let a bill he opposes _ to
require companies to give workers 60 days notice before closing
plants _ become law without his signature.
   That could relieve some of the campaign pressure on Bush from
Democrats who have been using the issue to suggest the
administration lacks compassion for workers.
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff who accompanied him to
Chicago, said Reagan's decision ``will make it more difficult for
the political game to be played over the plant-closing issue.''
   On the other side, an aide to Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis, who has argued strongly in favor of a notification
provision in federal law, said of the decision: ``I think it's a
testament to the people around the nation who supported this bill
that it's finally going to be in effect.''
   Asked if Reagan's decision takes an issue away from Dukakis,
spokesman Dayton Duncan said, ``Not at all. The point is that
Ronald Reagan and George Bush tried to stop it. Where is George on
this? He used to oppose it.''
   Reagan, in a statement read by spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, said
the action was being taken to get the issue over with and have
Congress ``get on with the nation's business.''
   But Fitzwater also noted that the Democrats had been hitting
Republicans hard on the issue, and he said when asked if Reagan was
acting on political considerations, ``Certainly they're a part of
the equation.''
   Monday night in Detroit, Dukakis continued efforts to win over
former supporters of Jesse Jackson, telling a national civil-rights
organization that government can help ``transform the cycle of
poverty into a ladder of opportunity.''
   Earlier in the day, Reagan had asserted that Dukakis would
destroy that opportunity.
   Reagan's remarks Monday on behalf of a Senate candidate provided
the only Republican campaign salvo. Bush remained at the White
House while continuing to work on choosing a running mate.
   In a speech before the National Urban League in Detroit, Dukakis
accused the Reagan administration of having ``cramped ideals and
limited ambitions'' and spending huge amounts of money on wasteful
projects rather than helping blacks and poor people.
   ``We have to transform the cycle of poverty into a ladder of
opportunity, and that ladder must be sturdy and strong for all our
citizens,'' he said.
   ``Some people say it can't be done,'' he said. ``I say we
haven't tried.''
   Reagan, speaking to a fund-raiser for Sen. William V. Roth,
R-Del., took the Massachusetts governor to task for declaring in
his nomination acceptance speech that ``the Reagan era'' is ending.
   ``Does he want to end the era of lower tax rates and higher real
income for families, record numbers of jobs, low inflation and
interest rates, steady growth and respect, not just lip-service for
families?'' Reagan asked.
   He said that if the Democratic ticket is elected, ``all of us
may be picking up the pieces.''
   Dukakis' running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, was working
on welfare legislation today on Capitol Hill.
   Jackson, at home in Chicago, spoke by telephone Monday with New
York Mayor Edward I. Koch as part of an effort to make peace at
least long enough to help Dukakis win the election.
   Koch criticized Jackson during the New York primary race, saying
Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for Jackson, who supports
Palestinian self-determination.
   ``I hope to work in support of Dukakis and then we'll continue
the ideological battle at another time,'' Koch said.
   Jackson did his part locally for Dukakis, telling some 5,000
members of the American Postal Workers Union: ``Bush believes
government is a tool for private industry. Dukakis believes the
government is a tool for public service.''
   Monday night in Charlotte, N.C., Jackson emphasized his own
defeated campaign for the presidency during remarks to nearly 6,000
people at the AME Zion Church.
   ``Politics is not a one-round fight,'' Jackson said. ``It's not
even an even fight. Sometimes referees, judges and the rules are
all stacked against you. And yet you can't surrender. You can't
lose by a forfeit. You can't have a glass jaw. You have to hang on
in there.''
   ``There are no more impossible dreams,'' he said. ``I'm taking
the ceiling off dreams every day. I may or may not make it to the
White House, but our children will. And they must.''
   Jackson referred directly to Dukakis only once, a brief mention
that the Massachusetts governor garnered more primary votes than he
did.
   In a continuation of a legal battle that flared last week, the
Federal Election Commission asked an appeals court to side with its
decision that the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign should get $46 million
in funds despite Bentsen's re-election campaign for the Senate.
Bentsen's challenger for the Senate seat and the Republican
National Senatorial Committee contend the presidential and
senatorial campaigns give Bentsen an unfair financial advantage.
   Dukakis had some welcome legal news waiting for him on the home
front. Law enforcement sources who spoke only on condition they not
be named said the FBI has informed Massachusetts that it found no
evidence that the Dukakis administration leaked confidential
information on prison-siting plans to developers who then bought
land and offered to sell it to the state.
   The allegations, lodged by opponents of plans to build a 500-bed
state prison in rural New Braintree, Mass., had been cited by
Dukakis critics to attack the good-government pledges at the center
of his presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
