<1ST_LINE>u i PM-IrishAttack 5thLd-Writethru a0614 08-02 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish Attack, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0614,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>IRA Attacks Claim 2 Lives In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs, IRA claims responsibility. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs ``Belfast police...'' Minor editing thereafter to conform.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today in a busy
shopping area, killing a policeman, and a soldier was shot and
killed after being dragged from a store in west Belfast, police
said.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army claimed responsiblity for
both attacks. Earlier today, the IRA said it launched a morning
ambush on an army patrol in which six part-time soldiers were
wounded. On Monday, the IRA blew up a British army barracks in
north London, killing one soldier and injuring nine.
   Belfast police Sgt. Harry Hussey said the bomb that killed the
police officer went off at 3:40 p.m. under a car in a main street
in Lisburn, 11 miles southwest of Belfast. At least 18 people were
injured by flying debris, Hussey said.
   About 20 minutes later, a gang accosted a member of the Ulster
Defense Regiment, a locally recruited and predominantly Protestant
unit of the British army, in a shopping center in Roman Catholic
west Belfast, Hussey said.
   The part-time soldier, who was shopping with his wife, was taken
outside and fatally shot, Hussey said.
   Today's string of attacks in Northern Ireland began this morning
when a land mine blew up near a Land Rover in the County Tyrone
village of Carland, slightly injuring six Ulster Defense Regiment
soldiers.
   After the explosion, the soldiers struggled out of the Land
Rover and guerrillas lying in ambush opened fire with machine guns.
Soldiers in the vehicle that was attacked or in another nearby army
Land Rover returned fire, a police spokesman said. The guerrillas
escaped.
   Police said the six injured men, all local recruits, were
treated for minor injuries at South Tyrone Hospital in Dungannon
and released. One suffered a broken arm.
   The police spokesman, who by custom was not identified, said the
explosion occurred at 9:30 a.m. on the Cookstown Road in Carland, 4
miles from Dungannon and about 35 miles west of Belfast, where at
least two army Land Rovers were on patrol.
   Last month near Coalisland, a few miles away, security forces
found an 800-pound bomb abandoned by the IRA because cattle had
eaten through the command wires.
   The predominantly Catholic IRA is fighting to drive the British
from Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite the province
with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
