<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Blast 4thLd-Writethru a0623 08-02 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Blast, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0623,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombed Barracks Easy Terrorist Target, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to reflect IRA claim of responsiblity. SUBS
14th graf pvs ``There was no..'' to conform. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government ordered a security review of all
military bases after an IRA bomb killed one soldier and injured
nine at a north London army barracks considered an easy target for
a terrorist attack.
   In Northern Ireland today, the IRA killed a part-time soldier
and a policeman and wounded six soldiers in three separate attacks.
Eighteen bystanders were injured in one of the attacks.
   Security was reported so lax at Inglis Barracks in suburban Mill
Hill that the perimeter fence was riddled with holes and broken
traffic barriers were still unrepaired after two months.
   The barracks houses the Directorate of Defense Postal and
Courier Services, where a staff of 250 handles mail for British
armed services personnel around the world. It also houses some
personnel from the Royal Engineers, the Royal Navy and the Women's
Royal Army Corps.
   ``This was a soft target and this makes it an extremely cowardly
attack,'' Archie Hamilton, minister of state for the armed forces,
said of Monday's blast. ``We don't keep the military apart from the
community but we will obviously now have to review our security
arrangements.''
   Conservative Party legislator John Gorst, whose parliamentary
constituency includes the barracks, said security was appalling.
   ``With the benefit of hindsight, I think it would be crystal
clear that it would be possible to move into this place with
impunity and to move around without being challenged,'' he said.
   Monday's 7 a.m. blast, the fifth IRA attack since May against
British military targets outside Northern Ireland, knocked down
most of a two-story brick dormitory and started a fire.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility in a message to
the bureau of the British domestic news agency Press Association in
Belfast, Northern Ireland.
   The 15 men living in the dormitory were in bed when the
explosion tore out the first floor, an army spokesman said. The
building can accommodate up to 70 people.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated province with
the Republic of Ireland.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who is on a trip to Australia,
today condemned the attack, describing it as ``a negation of
democracy.''
   ``It is again another lesson why no one, but no one, should
support the IRA or any form of terrorism,'' she said. ``They don't
like the results at the ballot box, so they turn to bombing,
maiming and killing.''
   Early today, a suspected land mine blew up near an army vehicle
in Northern Ireland, slightly injuring six part-time soldiers,
police said. The IRA claimed responsibility for the 9:30 a.m.
explosion in the village of Carland, about 35 miles west of Belfast.
   The IRA said it also was behind a bombing today in Lisburn, 11
miles from Belfast, in which a policeman was killed and 18
passers-by were wounded. The IRA also said its members shot and
killed a part-time soldier today after pulling him out of a store
in west Belfast.
   The blast in London raised new fears for British armed forces
personnel at home and abroad, because Inglis is only one of
hundreds of small, lightly guarded British bases.
   Reporters who went to the barracks after the blast found the
5-foot-high, wire mesh perimeter fence riddled with holes. One
section had a 50-foot gap.
   Monday's explosion was the first fatal attack by the IRA in
mainland Britain since guerrillas blew up Mrs. Thatcher's hotel
during a political convention in Brighton in October 1984. She
narrowly escaped injury, but five other people were killed in the
assassination attempt.
   On March 6 in Gibraltar, British commandos killed three unarmed
IRA guerrillas who were said to have been on a bombing mission.
   In apparent retaliation, the IRA resumed attacks on British
military targets in continental Europe after a 14-month lull.
   In the past three months, three British servicemen have been
killed and 12 other people injured in four machine-gun and bombing
attacks in West Germany and Holland.
   The soldier killed Monday was identified as 23-year-old Michael
Robbins, a lance corporal in the Royal Engineers.
</TEXT>
