<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Solarz-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0524 08-02 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Solarz-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with State Department consulting on
peace-keeping force; picks up 2nd graf pvs, Rep. Stephen.</NOTE>
<HEAD>By PAUL PAGE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is consulting with several
of its allies about the possibility of establishing an
international peace-keeping force in Cambodia once Vietnam pulls
out its troops, the State Department said today.
   An international force is one of several measures being
discussed by the Vietnamese-backed government of Cambodia and the
three main guerrilla factions fighting to overthrow it, said deputy
spokesman Phyllis Oakley.
   ``We have been consulting with our friends,'' she said, but
added that ``this is in a very preliminary stage.''
   The Phnom Penh government held a first round of talks last week
in Indonesia with the guerrillas and representatives of Vietnam to
work out a plan for the withdrawal of all Vietnamese troops from
the country.
   The United States, the Soviet Union and China have all pledged
to support efforts to find a solution.
   The State Department comments followed a call by the chairman of
a key congressional panel to set up an international force to
prevent the Khmer Rouge from returning to power.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., also urged the United States and
other western governments to prevent the re-emergence of the Khmer
Rouge, which he said ``could very easily lead to another holocaust
in Cambodia.''
   ``I think the West needs to do much more than what it has been
doing in order to prevent such a dreadful eventuality from coming
about,'' Solarz, chairman of the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee
on Asian and Pacific affairs, said on the CBS-TV ``This Morning''
program.
   The Khmer Rouge are accused of killing hundreds of thousands of
people from 1975 to 1978 while trying to turn Cambodia into a
primitive agrarian society.
   Vietnam ended the Khmer Rouge reign when it invaded Cambodia in
1978 and Vietnamese troops have occuped the nation since then.
   Vietnam has pledged to withdraw its remaining 120,000 troops by
1990, but is demanding assurances that the Khmer Rouge, led by Pol
Pot, will not return to power. But the Khmer forces remain the
strongest of the three resistance groups fighting the Hanoi-backed
government in Phnom Phen.
   Talks between Vietnam, the resistance forces and other southeast
Asian nations were held last week in Indonesia, but little progress
was reported.
   Solarz called on the United States and other nations to pressure
China to end its military assistance to the Khmer Rouge and urge
Thailand to deny the Khmer guerillas the use of Thai territory as a
base.
   But he indicated more than diplomatic pressure is needed against
a Khmer army Solarz called a ``ruthless gang of murderers.''
   ``We need to prevail upon the Vietnamese to accept the
establishment of an international peace-keeping force which could
be sent into Cambodia as the Vietnamese withdraw in order to
provide some insurance against the return of the Khmer Rouge to
power,'' Solarz said.
   Dith Pran, a Cambodian who escaped captivity under the Khmer
Rouge and now works as a photographer for The New York Times,
appeared in the same interview as Solarz and urged western
governments to isolate the Khmer Rouge.
   ``I'm afraid another holocaust (could happen),'' said Pran,
whose escape was dramatized in the film ``The Killing Fields.''
</TEXT>
