<2ND_LINE>PM-Emergency Landing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landing Gear Collapses As Commuter Plane Lands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to update with crew identities. Plymate cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five passengers and two crewmen escaped
injury today when the nose gear on an Allegheny Commuter plane
collapsed during an emergency landing at Indianapolis International
Airport, officials said.
   ``It was a delicate situation, but the pilot put it down very
gently and smoothly and he made it a happy ending,'' said Bob
Spitler, managing director of administration for the Indianapolis
Airport Authority.
   The crew of Flight 3876 was identified as pilot Roger Plymate
and copilot Arman Avakian, both based at Indianapolis, according to
Mickey Bowman, vice president for scheduling and planning of
Allegheny Commuter.
   The twin-engine turboprop Beechcraft left Indianapolis for
Owensboro, Ky., about 10 a.m. and the landing occurred at 11:08 a.m.
   Spitler said the pilot was preparing to land at Owensboro when
instruments showed the landing gear would not lock in place.
   ``He came back to Indianapolis because he could burn off fuel
and we have longer runways and more rescue equipment,'' said
Spitler.
   ``He held the nose gear off and then just let if fall down very
slowly,'' said Spitler. ``He skidded down the runway on his nose,
scraped the bottom of the plane and bent the propeller tips and
came to rest about 5,500 feet down the 7,600 foot runway.
   ``There was no further damage and no fire. The five passengers
left quickly and were taken to the main terminal by bus.''
   Spitler said crews were working to remove the crippled plane
from the runway.
</TEXT>
