<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Iraq     08-02 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Iraq,190</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States sharply criticized Iraq
today for its use of chemical weapons against Iran, after a U.N.
team found the Iraqis were using deadly gases in large quantities.
   ``We condemn Iraq's use of chemical weapons,'' said deputy State
Department spokesman Phyllis Oakley. ``There can be no
justification whatsoever for this practice, and we condemn its use
anywhere.''
   The United States has in the past made its views on the subject
known to Iraq, she added. Mrs. Oakley declined to say whether a
similar message had been conveyed to Iraq since the U.N. report was
released Monday.
   A team that visited Iran and Iraq last month found that Iraq is
continuing to use mustard and nerve gas ``on an intensive scale''
despite frequent pleas that it stop.
   The U.N. inquiry was requested by Iran, which charged that Iraq
had killed thousands of people in the spring with chemicals. At
Iraq's request, the team later went to Baghdad but its report about
Iran's use of chemical weapons was much less detailed.
   The secretary-general is conducting talks with both sides on
ending their eight-year war and implementing a cease-fire.
