<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TBTeacher     08-02 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TB Teacher,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TB Patient Rehired, Gets Back Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERNANDINA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school teacher who was fired
when she got tuberculosis nine years ago and whose case eventually
went to the U.S. Supreme Court has accepted a non-teaching position
with the school district and $125,000 in back pay.
   Gene Arline said Monday she would accept the Nassau County
School Board's offer to rehire her and pay the back wages ordered
by U.S. District Judge John H. Moore II.
   Mrs. Arline, a third-grade teacher, was fired after suffering a
relapse of the tuberculosis she had as a child.
   The Supreme Court ruled the ailment was a disability and that
Mrs. Arline was protected under a 1973 law prohibiting institutions
receiving federal funds from firing a person because of a handicap.
   The high court sent the case back to Moore, who told the board
it could rehire Mrs. Arline and pay her $125,470 in back pay or
sever all relations with her and pay $768,724.
   Mrs. Arline told the board she was afraid of potential public
outcry should she return to the classroom. The board said she could
work as an elementary school resource aid, handling teaching
materials.
</TEXT>
