<DOCNO> AP880802-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CraterLakeStudy     08-02 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crater Lake Study,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Prepare For Voyage To Bottom Of Crater Lake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRATER LAKE NATIONAL PARK, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists using a
one-person submersible craft plan Wednesday to make the first of 20
dives looking for hot springs at the bottom of Crater Lake, the
deepest lake in the United States.
   At a news conference on the lake rim, National Park Service
officials and researchers said they hope to confirm the existence
of thermal vents on the lake bottom and gather data on many other
features of the unusual body of water.
   Scientists began assembling gear for the unprecedented dive
Monday. The submersible craft, called ``Deep Rover'' and designed
for ocean exploration, was scheduled to be placed in the lake today.
   The lake, which resulted from the explosion of Mount Mazama
nearly 7,000 years ago, is 1,932 feet deep and is famous for its
clear, cobalt-blue water.
   The water's clarity is the main reason for the exploration of
the lake, which comes about halfway through a 10-year study
launched by Congress in 1983.
   Scientists in the 1970s noticed that a small device used to
measure the clarity of Crater Lake barely could be seen at 85 feet
below the lake's surface. Before then, the device frequently could
be seen as deep as 115 feet.
   Scientists theorize vents below the lake's floor may be altering
the clarity by stirring up sediment and plant life in the lake,
which has no inlets or outlets.
   Oregon State University researchers Jack Dymond and Robert
Collier will take turns manning the submersible vessel on the
dives. They discovered small vents on the lake bottom last summer
using a remote control diving device, and say there is sufficient
evidence to indicate the vents are hydrothermal _ that is, the
water coming from them is heated somehow.
   Dymond said it would ``require a remarkable coincidence of
events to justify any other hypotheses'' because of the chemical
differences found near the vents.
   Although the focus of the project is a search for geothermal
activity, the scientists are looking at it as a general study of
the famous lake, Dymond said.
   The lake has an ``incredible and complex volcanic, glacial, and
explosive history,'' he said.
   Officials said the major advantages of the Deep Rover, which
resembles a clear, plastic bubble, are its mobility and the
exceptional visibility the operator has, virtually 360 degrees.
Extending arms on the device can be used to collect water samples
and to probe into the vents.
   Dymond said it will allow the scientists to see crater walls
below the surface that for the most part have never been observed
before.
   The exploration will be based on Wizard Island in the lake. As a
result, the regular tour boat runs to the island have been
suspended until the end of the project Aug. 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OscarBack     08-02 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oscar Back,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Oscar Back To 20th Century Fox</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oscar awarded to 20th Century Fox for the
development of CinemaScope has been ordered off the auction block
and back to the studio for safekeeping until its ownership is
decided.
   The statuette for technical achievement, which is smaller than
the figurines handed to producers, actors and directors, was
scheduled to be auctioned Tuesday with two other Oscars at the
Collectors' Bookstore in Hollywood.
   But Superior Court Judge Miriam Vogel agreed with an attorney
representing the studio Monday that there were enough unresolved
questions about the Oscar's custody to prevent it from being sold.
   She set an Aug. 24 hearing on the matter.
   ``This is a real travesty of justice,'' said Collectors'
Bookstore owner Malcolm Willits after the ruling. ``Those
Indian-givers. Fox, after 34 years of not even missing it, is now
demanding it back.''
   Willits said the Oscar, presented in 1954, has been in the
possession of Esther Roberts, who was personal secretary for 15
years to late Fox President Darryl Zanuck.
   He declined to say why Roberts wanted to sell the statuette.
   Willits said Roberts discovered the Oscar in a back room at Fox
the year Zanuck accepted it. When she asked her boss about it,
Willits said Zanuck told her it had no sentimental value to him and
she could have it.
   But Fox attorney Louis Meisinger claimed in his lawsuit to stop
the auction of the statuette that Zanuck ``was acting in the
absence of any corporate resolution or other authorization'' when
he gave his secretary the Oscar.
   Willits countered that the powerful Zanuck ``reigned supreme''
at the studio and in the entertainment industry, and controlled at
that time a majority of Fox stock. He said it was obvious that
Zanuck needed to consult no one about giving away the statuette.
   Vogel ordered Collectors' Bookstore not to sell, conceal or
diminish the value of the statuette, and extended the order to
Roberts.
   Meisinger said the studio's legal claim on the Oscar evolved
through an agreement it signed with the Motion Picture Academy of
Arts and Sciences upon receipt in 1954 to offer the statuette back
to the Academy before selling it.
   The Academy since relinquished those rights to the studio, and
Fox argues that Roberts must offer the Oscar to it for a $10
consideration before she can sell it.
   Meisinger estimated the statuette's value at $3,000, and the
studio on Monday posted a $6,000 bond for its possession.
   Willits said he thought it would bring $10,000 at auction
because it was awarded to a major studio for an important
contribution.
   In CinemaScope, special lenses compress and distort images
during filming, while special projector lenses correctly
reinterpret the film on a special wide screen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
