<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US     08-02 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks on U.S. Bases Resume After Interruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and Filipino negotiators
Tuesday resumed talks on the status of U.S. military bases but gave
no indication of progress on the issue of compensation for the use
of the bases.
   After a meeting lasting more than two hours, the two panels
issued a statement saying they would meet again Wednesday. They
refused to answer questions.
   Tuesday's session was the first since talks broke off a week ago.
   According to the statement, the negotiators discussed
compensation _ the main problem _ as well as security around the
sites and the issue of criminal jurisdiction over U.S. troops.
   Filipino officials said last week that U.S. inflexibility over
compensation was responsible for the interruption in the talks.
   The United States pays the Philippines $180 million in military
and economic aid each year in exchange for the use of Clark Air
Base, Subic Bay Naval Base and four smaller facilities.
   Sources close to the talks said the Filipinos demand a raise of
at least $1.2 billion, but the Americans have refused. The sources,
who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the Americans were
willing to increase compensation only by $360 million.
   The Americans have proposed that the Philippine side also
consider as compensation the $500 million the bases spend annually
in salaries to Filipino employees and on local purchases, the
sources said.
   After announcing the resumption of the talks Tuesday, Foreign
Secretary Raul Manglapus said, ``Our position has already been
subjected to change and we are not about to change it again.''
   A source, who asked not to be identified, said that during
Tuesday's session, U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt and Manglapus
secluded themselves from the rest of the negotiatiors to discuss
the question of compensation.
   The sources said the Americans were reluctant to agree to a
drastic increase in compensation because of uncertainty over the
status of the bases after their lease expires in 1991.
   The lease may be extended by a formal treaty ratified by
two-thirds of the 23-member Senate, where opposition to the bases
is strong.
   The Senate in June approved a bill banning nuclear weapons and
nuclear- powered ships from Philippine territory. The United States
opposes such legislation because of its policy refusing to confirm
or deny the presence of U.S. nuclear weapons.
   President Corazon Aquino, whose term expires in 1992, has
pledged to honor the current agreement, but refuses to say whether
she will support an extension.
   The talks are part of negotiations that began four months ago to
review a 1947 agreement giving the Americans the right to operate
military bases in the Philippines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SurgeonInvestigation     08-02 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Surgeon Investigation,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Heart Surgeon At `U' Subject Of Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Minnesota Hospital is
investigating its chief heart-lung surgeon for allegedly ordering
an associate to perform a bypass operation on a patient considered
dead before surgery began, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
   Hospital officials also are looking into an allegation that
Stuart Jamieson or one of his assistants left a pair of surgical
forceps in another heart patient's chest, then failed to inform the
patient, the patient's family or operating room personnel when the
instrument was removed during a second operation, the Minneapolis
Star Tribune said in a copyright story.
   Jamieson, chief of cardiothoracic surgery at the University of
Minnesota Hospital and director of its Heart-Lung Institute,
declined to comment, but spokeswoman Sue Swenson said Jamieson has
denied all the accusations in interviews with hospital officials.
   ``What you have are rumors that are the product of professional
jealousy,'' Ms. Swenson said. ``Dr. Jamieson has decided not to
dignify them with a response.''
   Jamieson, a former director of Stanford University Medical
Center's heart-lung transplant program, was hired by the university
in March 1986 to develop a similar program, the first in the
Midwest.
   The newspaper quoted sources who said that Jamieson overruled a
heart surgeon in his department on May 5 and ordered her to perform
a coronary artery bypass on a 43-year-old woman. Minutes earlier,
the surgeon had canceled the operation because she believed the
patient was dead.
   However, about 10 minutes after the operation was canceled, the
surgeon notified operating room nurses the bypass would be
performed after all, on orders from Jamieson. After the operation,
the patient remained attached to a mechanical heart pump but never
regained consciousness, the newspaper said.
   A hospital pathologist who performed an autopsy concluded the
surgery had been unnecessary since the woman either was clinically
dead at the time or had no chance of surviving the bypass operation.
   The woman's medical insurance carrier was billed more than
$22,000 for that operation and for a second, exploratory operation
hours later in which doctors attempted to stop internal bleeding.
   Jamieson also is under investigation for allegedly failing to
disclose that a pair of forceps had been left in the chest cavity
of a 78-year-old man who underwent a coronary artery bypass April
15, the newspaper said.
   The forceps were discovered in a routine chest X-ray, but the
three X-rays showing the location of the forceps have been missing
from the patient's medical records since shortly after the second
operation was performed, the newspaper said.
   The patient's insurance company was billed about $19,000 for the
two operations, the newspaper said.
   Jamieson has told hospital officials that no forceps were found
in the patient's chest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
