<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PostalSales     08-02 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Sales,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postage Stamps To Be Sold in Banks, Subway Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postage stamp sales are a big success in
supermarkets and are being extended experimentally to banks and
subway stations, Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank reported
Tuesday.
   Frank told the Postal Service board of governors meeting in
Seattle that the mail agency and SeaFirst Bank of Seattle have
agreed to a one-year experiment selling stamps through the bank's
automatic teller machines.
   The teller machines will sell stamps at banks and at some postal
facilities where they will be installed said Frank, whose statement
was released here.
   At the same time, he said, vending machines will be installed in
stations of the Washington Metro subway system for one year to
dispense postal items as well as Metro materials.
   An earlier test of selling stamps through supermarkets has
proved widely popular, Frank said. Stamp sales have expanded to 22
major grocery chains with 13,000 outlets across the nation.
</TEXT>
