<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya     08-02 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Gives President, Police Expanded Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Tuesday voted unanimously to
amend the constitution to give the president greater control over
the judiciary and to broaden police arrest power.
   The changes were pushed through Parliament just five days after
Attorney General Matthew Muli proposed them in the official Kenya
Gazette.
   Clergymen and the Law Society of Kenya opposed the changes,
warning that they would weaken constitutional checks and balances
and erode individual liberties.
   The changes empower the president to fire a High Court or Court
of Appeals judge without having to go through the current tribunal
process and without giving a reason.
   Parliament also voted to expand from 24 hours to 14 days the
period in which police can hold a person suspected of a capital
offense before bringing him to court.
   There normally is a 14-day period between the time a bill is
proposed and Parliament debates it. But legislators voted Tuesday
to reduce the waiting period for debate on the constitutional
changes to the elapsed five days.
   Joshua Angatia was the only member of the 201, one-chamber
legislature to vote against the procedural change that allowed for
the quick debate and vote.
   The bill was read three times, as required by law. Votes were
taken only on the second and third reading.
   The vote on the second reading was 151-0 in favor of the
constitutional changes. By the time the third vote was set, more
members had entered the chamber and the bill passed 160-0.
   Kenya, by law, is a one party state and the approval of the
constitutional changes had been expected.
   Tuesday's bill was the 10th amendment to the constitution since
1969.
   In December 1986, Parliament amended the constitution to remove
tenure for the offices of attorney general and auditor-general.
   Lawyers and clergymen fought against those changes, saying they
reduced the independence of the attorney general and the
auditor-general.
   The constitution was written in 1969 to update a bulky 1963
independence constitution which had become cumbersome because of
numerous amendments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
