<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-02 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sybil Ludington is foaming at the mouth
again and Putnam County officials are considering having her head
cut off.
   Decapitation is one proposal for the repair of a statue of
Sybil, who was 16 in 1777 when she rode through the countryside
warning the colonists that the British were burning Danbury, Conn.
   The statue, of Sybil on a horse, overlooks Lake Gleneida in
downtown Carmel.
   The problem is white corrosion around the mouth of the statue,
which makes it look as if Sybil is foaming. The corrosion has been
removed several times but always returns.
   County Legislator Lynn Greenwood said a foundry in Beacon has
recommended that the head be removed to get at the source of the
corrosion.
   A company in Connecticut, however, says it can correct the
problem while keeping the statue intact. Both estimates are under
$10,000.
   The statue is valued at $150,000. It was a gift to the county
chapter of the Daughters of the American Revolution in 1962 from a
sculptor in Danbury.
   Sybil's story has been the subject of a postage stamp, a song, a
poem and a play.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fort Worth's efforts to promote tourism
fell apart _ literally _ when an envelope containing pamphlets and
the city's ``Fun Guide'' tore in the mail.
   The package was mailed to a fictitious ``Priscilla Whiteside''
in San Francisco. Unknown to the tourism bureau, the address
funneled mail to Consumer Reports Travel Letter so the editors
could rank responsiveness to tourists' requests.
   The travel letter received only the fun guide and ranked Fort
Worth the worst of the 46 cities that sent mail to ``Priscilla
Whiteside.''
   Tom Hanlon, director of Fort Worth's tourism bureau, called a
news conference Monday after USA Today publicized the travel
letter's findings. His staff, he said, will begin designing a new
cover folder that he hopes won't break apart.
   Fort Worth wasn't the only city with mail trouble. Los Angeles
sent an elaborate package that arrived as the 60,000-circulation
monthly magazine was going to press. As a result, the City of the
Angels was unranked.
   The big winners were San Francisco, Houston, Cincinnati,
Portland, Ore., Milwaukee and Long Beach, Calif.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When television engineer Brent Perry wanted
his relationship with his girlfriend to progress from ``The Dating
Game'' to ``The Newlywed Game,'' he turned to a 30-second spot.
   The 26-year-old KOTV operations engineer bought the time in the
middle of his station's noon newscast to air his marriage proposal
to Sandra Vanderlugt, a teacher at Victory Christian School.
   ``I wanted to do something completely original when I asked her
to marry me,'' Perry said.
   Wearing a tuxedo and reciting his proposal in verse, he taped
the spot in front of Gilcrease Museum. On Monday, the first
anniversary of the couple's relationship, Perry said they watched
television together.
   ``It was perfect timing because they had just gone to a
commercial on the news so I just turned up the TV and there I
was,'' he said.
   ``She couldn't believe it. She kept asking me if this was really
me on TV,'' Perry said. ``The important thing was, she said yes, so
I felt like it was all worth it.''
   Perry said he and Miss Vanderlugt plan to be married next year.
</TEXT>
