<2ND_LINE>PM-Alien Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Acquits Two In Alien Smuggling Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 4th to update with reaction to verdict.
Subs 8th graf pvs, `But U.S...' to delete now-extraneous first
reference to Lutz.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lutheran minister and a journalist
accused of smuggling two pregnant Salvadorans into the United
States were acquitted today by a federal jury.
   The U.S. District Court jury, which was given the case Monday
afternoon, returned innocent verdicts on all counts after 4{ hours
of deliberations.
   The Rev. Glen Remer-Thamert, 44, had been charged with one count
of conspiracy and two counts each of transporting, harboring and
inducing Ines Campos-Anzora and Cecelia Elias-Alegria to enter the
United States.
   Demetria Martinez, 28, had been charged with one count of
conspiracy to violate immigration laws and two counts each of
transporting and inducing the women to enter the United States.
Their trial began July 13.
   Outside court, Remer-Thamert called the verdict a victory for
the sanctuary movement, a grassroots effort that has been going on
since 1980 to aid refugees from Central America.
   Ms. Martinez said she hoped the ``victory will encourage other
reporters to get out and find out what the government has to hide
in its role in the situation in El Salvador.''
   U.S. Attorney William Lutz said he believed there was good
evidence the Salvadoran women entered the country illegally and
were transported illegally.
   ``But the question was one of intent and the jury disagreed with
our position on what the intent was,'' he said.
   U.S. District Judge John Conway on Monday denied a defense
motion for a mistrial made on the basis of evidence introduced
early in the trial regarding two mail fraud charges against
Remer-Thamert. Conway has thrown out those charges, ruling the
prosecution had not presented sufficient evidence.
   Alice Hector, attorney for Remer-Thamert, portrayed her client
as a religious man who believed he could legally help two refugees
under then-Gov. Toney Anaya's proclamation declaring New Mexico a
sanctuary state.
   Ms. Martinez's attorney, Tova Indritz, contended her client went
as a journalist on the August 1986 trip to bring the women to
Albuquerque and was protected by the First Amendment guarantee of
freedom of the press.
   But Lutz said the case concerned the smuggling of illegal aliens
to put their babies up for adoption and then send the mothers back
to El Salvador.
   ``It's about two people who thought they were above the law,''
said Lutz.
   He called the situation of the two Salvadoran women an American
tragedy. ``Cecelia and Ines are victims,'' Lutz said.
   Lutz also said the defendants knew Anaya's proclamation was not
valid, citing the fact that they took a back road to avoid the U.S.
Border Patrol in bringing the women from El Paso, Texas, to
Albuquerque.
   But Ms. Hector said it made sense for Remer-Thamert to believe
he was acting legally because of the declaration.
   She said that in 1986 there were conflicting statements about
the meaning of the sanctuary declaration, which does not contain
the words ``symbolic proclamation.''
   Ms. Hector also cited statements the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service made at the time that people would be
deluded into relying on the proclamation.
   ``If they thought no one would believe it, why did they warn
people about it?'' she said.
   Ms. Indritz said Ms. Martinez, who writes for the Albuquerque
Journal and National Catholic Reporter, made no arrangements for
the women and did not help them.
   Ms. Martinez testified she never wrote about the women because
she feared it could jeopardize their safety or their families in El
Salvador.
   ``The mere fact someone does not write an article does not mean
she was not engaged in news gathering,'' Ms. Indritz said.
   The attorney also attacked the credibility of the two
Salvadorans, who testified as prosecution witnesses. She said their
testimony contradicted other evidence and testimony and at times
they contradicted themselves.
</TEXT>
