<HEAD>Nurse Sentenced In Attempted Murder Of AIDS Patient</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT that sentencing was Monday,
sted today.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse was sentenced to nine years
in prison on a no-contest plea to trying to kill an AIDS-stricken
lawyer by posing as a doctor and prescribing a lethal dose of
insulin.
   Superior Court Judge Laurence J. Rittenband on Monday sentenced
Hal Speers Rachman, 42, to seven years on the attempted murder
charge and two years for his no-contest plea to five counts of
forgery.
   Police said Rachman stole $30,000 from the man by forging
withdrawal slips from his savings account and using stolen credit
cards.
   Rachman's pleas entered July 18 were part of a deal with
prosecutors who agreed to dismiss seven counts of credit card
forgery and one count of grand theft.
   Rachman, a registered nurse who worked with a temporary nursing
service, was accused of calling St. John's Hospital and Health
Center on Sept. 20, 1986, and ordering insulin for an AIDS patient
he had taken to the hospital three days earlier.
   The patient was given the insulin and fell into a coma. He was
revived but died four days later. An autopsy showed he died of
AIDS-related cancer.
