<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugTests     08-02 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Tests,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Railroad Workers Challenge Police Drug Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three railroad employees forced to undergo
drug testing after they found a corpse on a stretch of track have
accused police of violating their constitutional rights.
   The Railway Labor Executives Association, representing the men
in a federal lawsuit, claims police acted unconstitutionally
because there was no probable cause and because they ignored
provisions on worker testing outlined in the Federal Railroad
Safety Act.
   According to the complaint, filed July 13, the three Soo Line
employees were working on a switch engine early May 29 in a
Minneapolis train yard when they discovered the corpse on the
tracks near the Nicollet Bridge.
   The plaintiffs alleged there was no evidence the dead man had
been involved in a train crash or had been struck by a train, yet
police took the three in for drug and alcohol testing.
   The men were made to undergo urine tests, which came back
negative, without probable cause or suspicion they were impaired by
alcohol or drugs or were in any way involved in the man's death,
according to the suit, which names Police Chief Anthony Bouza.
   Police also violated the Federal Railroad Safety Act, which
delegates to the U.S. secretary of transportation the authority to
set appropriate regulations and standards for all areas of railroad
safety _ chemical testing included, the suit alleged.
   Police are pre-empted from testing railroad workers except as
permitted by the federal act and this incident was not an
exception, it contended.
   The lawsuit asks the court to find that the testing of the three
men was unconstitutional and that testing in such situations is
governed by federal regulations.
   Steve Fredrickson, assistant Minneapolis city attorney who will
handle the case, said he couldn't comment on the suit until he had
conferred with Bouza about the department's position. Bouza said he
wouldn't not comment until he had read the complaint.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
