<DOCNO> AP880802-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireDeaths     08-02 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Deaths,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Death Totals Stuck on Plateau</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's fire deaths shrank just a fraction
last year to 5,810, the sixth year that preventive strategies
failed to make a significant dent in the death toll, the National
Fire Protection Association said Tuesday.
   The number of civilians who died in 1987 decreased less than 1
percent from 1986's total of 5,850 deaths, according to the report
compiled by the Quincy-based association. Firefighter deaths were
not included in the totals.
   Reasons for the six-year plateau in the death toll include
waning interest in home safety, a slowing in development of fire
retardant home products, which made significant advances in the
last decade, and growth in the high-risk populations of the elderly
and the very young, said Dr. John R. Hall Jr., the association's
director of fire analysis and research.
   ``We're somewhat grasping at explanations, too,'' Hall said.
``Fire is so complicated that you can't say for sure you know
what's driving it. We've reached a point where those national
strategies like smoke detectors that were big enough and effective
enough ... have leveled off.''
   Home fires killed 4,570 people last year, down 1.8 percent from
4,655 in 1986, but they still accounted for 78.6 percent of all
fire deaths.
   Since 1984, there has been little progress in installing smoke
detectors and about one-third of those already in place are
inoperable, many because of dead batteries, Hall said.
   Fires caused by smoking materials remain the leading cause of
fatal home blazes, Hall said. The most common fires are caused by
cigarettes smoldering in couches or chairs, he said.
   Outdoor fires were up 10 percent, with 56,000 more brush, grass,
wildland, crop and timber fires, an increase partly blamed on
drought conditions.
   ``You've got an arson problem in outdoor fires. You've got a lot
of carelessness, then if you drop the weather situation on top of
that, what might have been a small fire turns into a large fire.''
   The South led all regions with a fire death rate of 29.0 per
million population, a regional rate that was 21.1 percent higher
than the national average of 23.9 per million. The higher incidence
of fire deaths in the South is partly due to its large population
of rural poor, Hall said.
   The number of civilians injured in fires totaled 28,215 in 1987,
a 5.2 percent increase from the previous year that brought figures
back to the levels of 1984-85.
   The Northeast region had the highest civilian fire injury rate
with 126.4 fire injuries per million population, but that was
similar to other regions, the report said.
   Property damage increased 4.9 percent to $7.04 billion, in
keeping with inflation, the report said.
   Breaking the impasse on fire deaths will require more widespread
education programs, renewed attention to home smoke detectors,
wider use of residential sprinklers and improvements in products
typically involved in home fatal fires, such as cigarettes and
lighters, said Michael J. Karter Jr., a senior statistician with
the association and author of the report.
   National Fire Prevention Week in October will focus on
installing and maintaining smoke detectors, Hall said.
   ``Our biggest obstacle right now is trying to break through that
misguided belief in personal invulnerability. All we can do is
point to the numbers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Pizza-Hospitals     08-02 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Pizza-Hospitals,0130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pizzas in Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Little Caesars Inc. is opening a pizza restaurant
in Mount Carmel Mercy Hospital _ the first pizza restaurant inside
any hospital in the United States, the pizza maker said.
   Visitors, doctors, nurses and patients _ if their doctors
approve _ are able to order from the restaurant beginning Tuesday,
said Lisa Ilitch Murray, spokesman for the chain.
   The trend follows the installation of fast-food hamburger
restaurants in several hospitals across the nation.
   It's good business, said Rose Dill, Mount Carmel's director of
marketing and public relations. ``We wanted to be able to offer a
good restaurant for visitors and our employees and at the same time
decrease overhead that existed when running our own coffee shop,''
she said.
</TEXT>
