<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-SpeakingFees     08-02 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Speaking Fees,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Common Cause Counts $9.8 Million in Speaking Fees to Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special-interest groups gave $9.8 million in
speaking fees to members of Congress last year in hopes of
influencing legislation, the public interest lobby Common Cause
said Tuesday in arguing that the practice should be banned.
   ``Members of Congress simply cannot fully meet their public
responsibilities when they are indebted to private interest groups
who are paying them large honoraria fees,'' said Common Cause
President Fred Wertheimer.
   Large amounts of money are going into the pockets of legislators
with direct jurisdiction over matters of interest to the interest
groups, the group said.
   ``These fees are being used to try to influence congressional
decisions,'' said Wertheimer. ``Honoraria fees are undermining the
integrity of Congress and should be banned outright.''
   At the same time, House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, endorsed
the concept of a ban on outside speaking and writing fees if it is
linked to a pay raise for members of Congress.
   Wright disagreed with the contention that the fees influence
lawmakers in their policymaking, but he acknowledged there is an
appearance of a conflict of interest that warrants banning the
practice.
   ``I've seen the growth in honoraria by trade associations and
the appearance of it has been made to look evil, so let's get rid
of it,'' Wright told a group of reporters at a luncheon Monday.
``It would be a very healthy thing for Congress.''
   A Common Cause study found that senators received a total of
$3.1 million in honoraria in 1987, according to their financial
disclosure reports, an average of $31,000 each. House members got a
combined total of $6.7 million, averaging $15,500 apiece.
   The averages don't tell the full story, however. Some members
refuse to accept honoraria, and others _ particularly committee
chairmen and influential senior members _ are in positions to
garner far more than the average amount.
   House members are allowed by law to keep for their own use an
amount of outside earned income up to 30 percent of their salaries.
That meant they could keep as much as $25,885 in 1987. Senators
could keep up to 40 percent of their salary amount, or $34,993.
Amounts received in excess of those limits had to be donated to
charity.
   Current congressional salaries are $89,500 a year, but a
presidential commission appointed to study the politically delicate
pay issue has recommended that they be raised to $135,000.
   Some forms of income, such as book royalties, are not included
in the lid on outside earned income. Wright's receipt of more than
$60,000 in such royalties is among six counts now under
investigation by the House ethics committee.
   The Common Cause study focused on the House and Senate Commerce
and Banking committees as particularly subject to honoraria
payments from groups with interest in their legislative areas.
   Members of the House Energy and Commerce Committee got a total
of 905,000 in fees from interest groups in 1987, nearly half of it
from communications, energy and health interests with legislative
matters under the panel's jurisdiction, the study found. Senate
Commerce Committee members received $662,000, one-quarter of it
from communications and transportation interests.
   The House and Senate Banking committees each received in excess
of $600,000 in speaking fees last year. For the House panel, nearly
half came from financial interests, and for the Senate committee,
the proportion was 26 percent.
   For Rep. Doug Barnard, D-Ga., the leading honoraria recipient on
the House Banking Committee, 70 percent of his $36,780 came from
financial groups, the study found. Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio, the
panel's senior Republican, received $25,050, 89 percent of it from
financial interests.
   Among interest groups, the top givers in the study were the
American Trucking Associations, which gave $117,500 in fees to 21
senators and 62 House members; the National Association of
Broadcasters, which gave $114,300 in honoraria; the Securities
Industry Association, $110,000; the Tobacco Institute, $102,000;
and the investment firm Paine Webber, $100,688.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
