<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     08-02 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendents in Ethnic Violence Remanded for Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criminal cases have gone to court against 20
people charged in ethnic rioting in the Caucasus, and Communist
Party leaders from Azerbaijan and Armenia met to discuss ways to
ease remaining tensions, Tass said Tuesday.
   The riots erupted Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijan city of Sumgait,
leaving 32 people dead, 26 of them Armenians, and more than 200
people injured.
   The unrest began amid an emotional Armenian campaign calling for
the mountainous region of Nagorno-Karabakh to be annexed by Armenia.
   The disputed Nagorno-Karabakh region has been part of Azerbaijan
since 1923. Its population is more than three-quarters Armenian,
but it has no common borders with the Armenian republic.
   The official Soviet news agency quoted the Soviet prosecutor's
office as saying that 94 people had been arrested to date in the
Sumgait rioting, ``among them murderers, rapists and robbers.''
   In addition, Tass said 200 apartments in Sumgait were ransacked,
about 50 cultural and service facilities damaged, and 40 cars
vandalized and some set on fire.
   Sixteen criminal cases involving 20 defendants in the rioting
have been submitted to court, Tass said. It gave no indication of
when trial would begin, or where.
   On July 8, the Soviet Supreme Court and the prosecutor's office
transferred the legal cases against the rioters out of Azerbaijan
and into courts of the Russian republic.
   That demand had been voiced by Armenian activists, who said the
courts in Azerbaijan were incapable of ruling fairly in cases where
Azerbaijanis were accused of attacking Armenians.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet intervened in the dispute on
July 18, ruling that the district will remain in Azerbaijan and
calling for measures to develop the district's economy and culture.
   The Presidium, the nation's top executive body, also dispatched
an envoy to the area, Arkady Volsky, as its representative and that
of the Central Committee, the Communist Party's policy-making body.
   Tass said Volsky met Tuesday with Armenian party chief Soren
Arutyunan and Azerbaijan party boss Abdul Rakhman Vezirov in
Stepanakert, capital of the Nagorno-Karabakh region.
   The leaders discussed how to fulfill decisions of the party and
state leadership on bringing the situation back to normal in
Nagorno-Karabakh and stimulating the area's economic and social
development, Tass said.
   Armenians have accused the Azerbaijani leadership of ignoring
the needs of the region's Armenian population.
   ``It is impermissible that the decisions adopted by the party
and the government are so far being fulfilled in an unsatisfactory
manner by union ministries and agencies, by republican and regional
bodies,'' Tass said.
   The participants in the Stepanakert meeting called for
``exhaustive measures'' to rectify the situation, Tass said.
   It did not say what steps were considered, only that ``a number
of constructive proposals were worked out to ensure a fuller
utilisation of the possibilities of both republics to accelerate
the social, economic and cultural development of the
Nagorno-Karabakh autonomous region.''
</TEXT>
