<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1456EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0457 08-02 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says It Will Not Accept U.N.-Declared Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with statements from Iraq and Iran. Edits
to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iraqi official said today his
government would never accept a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war if
it were declared by the U.N. without Iraq's consent.
   Riyadh al-Qaysi, Iraq's former U.N. ambassador, also told
reporters, ``We demand face-to-face talks in the interest of real
peace, rather than a temporary truce.''
   ``We will not accept a fait accompli, no matter in what form or
from which quarter it comes,'' said Al-Qaysi, a member of the Iraqi
delegation in the current U.N. peace talks with the foreign
ministers of Iran and Iraq.
   On Monday, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said he
would declare a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war after receiving
the report from a U.N. cease-fire team and consulting the Security
Council. The U.N. chief said he also might consult with
representatives of Iran and Iraq.
   ``The D-Day (beginning of a cease-fire) does not depend on the
parties,'' the secretary-general said.
   His statement fueled speculation that he was trying to pressure
Iraq to drop its demand for face-to-face talks before a cease-fire
and to agree to an early peace. Iran has been pressing Perez de
Cuellar to announce a cease-fire and has said it will comply at
once.
   Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati of Iran reaffirmed today
that his government believes the secretary-general is obliged to
declare a cease-fire, even if Iraq is opposed.
   ``The secretary-general is mandated to declare a cease-fire,''
he told reporters after meeting with some members of the Security
Council. He said Iran accepts the secretary-general's ideas on a
troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange and other elements of a peace
plan.
   Earlier today, Francois Giuliani, spokesman for the
secretary-general, said the U.N. chief does not intend to act
unilaterally. ``It is not his intention to declare a cease-fire
unilaterally,'' Giuliani said. ``Theoretically he can do so,
practically he will consult.''
   No meetings were scheduled today between the secretary-general
and Iranian or Iraqi envoys.
   Iran's announcement on July 18 that it was finally accepting a
year-old U.N. cease-fire resolution came after it suffered a string
of battlefield defeats, and was followed by a series of Iraqi raids
into Iran.
   Iraq accepted the cease-fire resolution last year, but has been
demanding face-to-face talks with Iran before a truce takes effect.
   The announcement of a cease-fire date would put pressure on Iraq
to compromise and drop its insistence on direct talks, which have
hampered a week of U.N.-mediated negotiations between the warring
nations.
   The Security Council resolution provides for a cease-fire,
withdrawal to recognized borders, a prisoner exchange, peace
negotiations and an investigation to determine which side started
the war.
   Perez de Cuellar said a U.N. military team is now in Amman,
Jordan, preparing its report. He said he is to receive it on
Wednesday.
   ``I will be in touch with members of the (Security) Council and
then I will decide on a D-Day,'' the Peruvian said.
   The secretary-general said that once a date for a cease-fire is
decided, he will begin consulting nations that could provide about
250 military observers to monitor the truce and troop withdrawal.
   Perez de Cuellar on Monday held his sixth meeting with Velayati
since talks began last week. He has met three times with Foreign
Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq.
</TEXT>
