<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCrash-Hearings     08-02 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Hearings,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friend Took Mahoney's Keys Away, Then Returned Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED M. NATT JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A friend of the man charged in a church
bus crash that killed 27 people testified Tuesday that he took the
driver's pickup truck keys away before the accident but returned
them because ``he wasn't drunk enough that he couldn't drive.''
   ``I had ridden with him earlier that night,'' added Taylor Fox,
who was at a friend's house with Larry Mahoney before the accident.
``He told me he was going home.''
   But when he watched Mahoney leave, Fox recalled, Mahoney drove
past the turn to his house.
   Fox was among the first witnesses at the hearing by the National
Transportation Safety Board, which is investigating the May 14
crash. NTSB officials have said the hearing will focus mainly on
drunken driving and bus safety.
   NTSB Chairman James Burnett, interviewed Tuesday on NBC's ``The
Today Show,'' said the licenses of drunken drivers should be
revoked on their first offense ``through a speedy process rather
than through a process that's severely delayed and the judicial
system.''
   Asked Tuesday whether he would have done anything differently,
Fox said, ``I would have kept his keys ... but you can't predict''
that type of accident.
   Both Fox and Phil Downey, who was also at the house with
Mahoney, said Mahoney was holding a beer when he pulled up to the
house a few hours before the crash.
   Downey said Mahoney apparently ``had had a few,'' but added, ``I
wouldn't say he was drunk.''
   An expert on the effects of drinking and driving, however,
testified that Mahoney's blood-alcohol level of .26 percent _ more
than 2{ times the legal limit in Kentucky _ would have ``massively
impaired'' his driving ability.
   ``I would estimate that he drank about a case ... 24 cans'' of
beer, said Dr. Herbert Moskowitz of the Southern California Researh
Institute.
   Mahoney, 35, has pleaded innocent to 27 counts of murder, 13
counts of first-degree assault, 44 counts of first-degree wanton
endangerment and one count of drunken driving.
   The crash was the deadliest involving an allegedly drunken
driver, according to the NTSB.
   A third witness, Clint Bradley, who was heading south to
Louisville shortly before the accident, said he saw Mahoney pass
him going south on I-71. He said Mahoney's truck was weaving and
tailgating a tractor-trailer rig.
   Bradley got off the interstate at a Carrollton exit to buy some
cigarettes. When he returned to the highway, he said, Mahoney was
heading north in the southbound lane.
   Bradley said he flashed his lights and honked his horn at him.
   The NTSB will report on the crash's probable causes and
recommend how to avoid similar accidents. Recommendations could be
directed toward federal, state and local officials, as well as bus
manufacturers, but the board has no power to require implementation.
   Since the crash, Gov. Wallace Wilkinson ordered officers
enforcing the state's liquor laws to increase inspections of bars,
liquor stores and other establishmentsd that sell alcoholic
beverages to intoxicated customers.
</TEXT>
