<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kerr-McGee     08-02 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kerr-McGee,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Six of Seven Safety Hazards Corrected at Henderson Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at Kerr-McGee Chemical Corp.
say they have corrected six of the seven safety hazards cited by
state officials last month at their Henderson plant.
   Spokeswoman Annita Bridges said the company is appealing the one
citation that has not been corrected. She confirmed that citation
involves storing ammonium perchlorate, a rocket fuel oxidizer, on
asphalt pads. Ms. Bridges said she does not know why the state
opposes the asphalt pads.
   Fines for the Kerr-McGee citations exceed $5,200, according to
federal records.
   The seven citations were issued by the Nevada Division of
Occupational Safety and Health and disclosed last week by company
officials.
   Ms. Bridges said the citations were issued following inspections
made at a time when the plant was not in operation.
   Kerr-McGee shut down production for a period following an
explosion at the nearby PEPCON plant, the only other facility in
the country producing the critical oxidizer used in the space
shuttle and military rockets.
   Kerr-McGee resumed production following a series of inspections
by safety officials.
   PEPCON announced last week it will build a new plant in Cedar
City, Utah.
   The May 4 explosion killed two people, injured 326 and caused
$73 million in property damage.
</TEXT>
