<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HomeSales     08-02 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New-Home Sales Surged 8.4 Percent in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes surged 8.4 percent in June
as rising mortgage rates spurred the biggest increase in sales in
four months, the government reported Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said sales of new single-family homes
climbed to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 734,000 units in
June, the highest sales level since February 1987.
   The June increase followed a revised 0.6 percent decline in home
sales in May and was the biggest one-month advance since an 11.9
percent sale rise in February. The government also revised upward
the level of sales for March, April and May, showing more strength
in the residential market than previously believed.
   Analysts said these developments were encouraging signs, but
they cautioned against too much optimism, primarily because of a
belief that mortgage rates are headed still higher.
   ``Demand is still there as long as interest rates can stay at a
reasonable level,'' said Kent Colton, executive vice president of
the National Association of Realtors. ``But we are concerned that
for the rest of the year, the pressure on rates will be upward.
That means that this is probably the peak as far as sales are
concerned.''
   Richard Peach, an economist with the Mortgage Bankers
Association, said part of the sales push in June came from attempts
by home buyers to close deals before rates went higher.
   Peach noted that the Federal Reserve boosted interest rates
twice in May and once in June in highly publicized moves to dampen
inflationary pressures.
   Fixed-rate mortgages now stand at 10.5 percent on average. James
Christian, chief economist for the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, predicted they would hit 11 percent by the end of the
year.
   But even with the continued rise in rates, Christian predicted
that new-home sales would total 650,000 units this year, down only
3 percent from the 1987 pace.
   ``The upward revisions in sales back through March indicate the
housing market was doing pretty well through the spring,'' he said.
``People have confidence that the economy will remain strong and
they don't have to worry about going out and making a commitment to
buy a home.''
   Prices of new homes were up sharply in June, with the median
price at $117,800, up $7,800 from May. The median price means half
the homes sold for more and half for less.
   The average price of a home was up as well, climbing 5.7 percent
to $141,200.
   Analysts said much of the price increase reflected the
geographic composition of the sales increase. Sales were up sharply
in the Northeast and West, the two regions with the highest home
prices.
   The sales advance was led by a 28.9 percent rise in the West,
where sales totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 245,000
units. Sales in the Northeast climbed 15.5 percent to 119,000 units.
   Sales fell 4.2 percent in the South to an annual rate of 273,000
units. Sales were down 1 percent in the Midwest to a rate of 97,000
units.
   For the first six months of the year, new-home sales were 3.2
percent lower than in the same period a year ago.
</TEXT>
