<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PostalIncome     08-02 0128</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Income,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rate Hike Puts Postal Service in Black</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The higher postage stamp prices that took
effect April 3 boosted the Postal Service out of the red, the
agency reported Tuesday.
   The mail service said it had net income of $48 million for the
quarter between March 12 and June 3. In the same quarter a year
earlier, the agency had lost $171 million.
   Senior Assistant Postmaster General Comer S. Coppie said
quarterly revenue was 1.6 percent higher than expected, primarily
because the new rates took effect a week earlier than originally
planned and mail volume was higher than anticipated.
   In addition, the Postal Service received $10 million in
unplanned revenues for nationwide delivery of an AIDS pamphlet from
the U.S. Surgeon General.
