<DOCNO> AP880802-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Namibia     08-02 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Namibia,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Proposes Cease-Fire in Angolan War, Withdrawal from
Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa on Tuesday
proposed a cease-fire next month in the Angolan war that would lead
to a withdrawal of foreign troops from Angola and independence for
South-West Africa by next June.
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha, speaking in the capital of Pretoria,
said South African delegates made the offer Tuesday in Geneva,
where a new round of peace talks began.
   The talks involve South Africa, Angola, Cuba and U.S. mediators.
   The proposal marked the first time South Africa has offered a
specific date for granting independence to South-West Africa, also
known as Namibia, and was seen as a major development in efforts to
resolve the 13-year-old Angolan war.
   ``If these proposals are accepted, it is the South African
government's firm belief that there will be no losers,'' Botha said.
   ``The sovereignty of Angola will be without question, South-West
Africa will have gained independence and ... peace will have been
restored,'' he said.
   Botha said that if the cease-fire offer is accepted, South
Africa would withdraw its estimated 3,000 troops from southern
Angola by Sept. 1.
   On Nov. 1, South Africa would begin withdrawing from South-West
Africa under the guidelines of U.N. Resolution 435, which calls for
independence in the territory.
   Botha said the South African proposal envisions elections in
South-West Africa on June 1, 1989, provided Cuba has withdrawn its
estimated 50,000 troops from Angola by the same date.
   Cuba and Angola did not immediately comment on the proposal and
Botha said he could not say how they had responded at the Geneva
talks.
   Cuban troops are in Angola supporting the country's Marxist
government. South Africa and the United States support the rebels
of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
   The South African proposal calls for the cease-fire to be
monitored by committees established at the current round of talks
in Geneva. Botha's statement did not specify who would do the
monitoring, although in the past he has proposed a U.N. presence.
   Botha said that if a cease-fire were to begin Aug. 10, it would
give U.N. officials almost three months to prepare for South
Africa's withdrawal from South-West Africa under the terms of
Resolution 435.
   South Africa, backed by the United States, has insisted that
independence for South-West Africa must be linked with a Cuban
troop withdrawal from Angola.
   Cuba and Angola have suggested a four-year timetable for the
Cuban withdrawal, while the South Africans and the United States
are seeking a much shorter time period.
   South Africa's mandate over South-West Africa was terminated by
the United Nations in 1966. But in defiance of several U.N.
resolutions, it has retained control of the country, which
possesses considerable mineral wealth.
   Among other issues addressed by the South African proposal are:
   _ The South-West Africa People's Organization, whose guerrillas
have been fighting for independence for 22 years. South Africa says
they must stop launching raids into South-West Africa from their
bases in southern Angola.
   _ African National Congress bases in Angola. South Africa says
the ANC, the main black group fighting to overthrow South Africa's
white government, has seven major military bases in Angola, and the
Pretoria government wants those bases closed down.
   _ Financial assistance for Namibia. South Africa spends billions
of dollars annually on South-West Africa. It is looking for someone
else to help the territory pay its bills, and has suggested the
five permanent members of the United Nations Security Council.
   The South African plan does not mention UNITA. The group's
leader, Jonas Savimbi, wants a power-sharing accord with the
Angolan government, but the country's Marxist leaders have so far
refused to negotiate with the guerrilla movement.
   None of the negotiating teams in Geneva made any comments
following Tuesday's session. The talks were scheduled to continue
Wednesday and Thursday.
   The Geneva talks are the fifth round of negotiations started in
May. Participants agreed last month on a basic set of 14 principles
that would lead to the withdrawal of all foreign forces from Angola
and the granting of independence to Namibia. No timetable was
agreed on.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
