<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Domenici-Veep     08-02 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Domenici-Veep,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domenici Planning Support Group For Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Pete Domenici says he doesn't think it's
likely he'll be chosen as George Bush's running mate, but he's
making some plans just in case.
   ``I still believe it's a long shot, but I can't go down (to the
convention in New Orleans) without a support group and without some
plans,'' he said.
   Domenici, R-N.M., said he would talk to New Mexico's convention
delegation and has already contacted some of his former staff
members for support at the convention.
   He mentioned one possible problem that could be brought up if he
were to be chosen _ ``the fussing with President Reagan'' over the
federal budget in 1986. The White House and the Senate Budget
Committee, which Domenici chaired at the time, were at odds over
how to cut the federal deficit.
   If he is chosen by Bush and if they are elected in November,
Domenici said, he has some science-related ideas for his own role
in the White House.
   ``I'd clearly want to define a few roles,'' he said. ``I'd like
to be the science and technology coordinator for the federal
government and bring the private sector into play.
   ``I'd like to see better use of the national laboratories and a
better organization of our effort in science,'' he said Monday.
``It's fragmented now. There's no continuity.''
   Domenici said he first learned last month he was on Bush's list
of possible running mates while flying from Albuquerque to
Washington on Air Force II with the vice president.
</TEXT>
