<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1901EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MapleLabeling     08-02 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maple Labeling,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>St. Johnsbury Producer Fined As Part of Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A maple syrup producer has agreed to pay
$25,000 in fines as part of a settlement following allegations that
the firm mislabeled maple products.
   Maple Grove Farms of Vermont Inc. in St. Johnsbury neither
admitted nor denied any wrongdoing. But it agreed to pay the fines
to the state and to reimburse the $10,000 it cost the Vermont
Department of Agriculture to investigate the matter.
   The company also agreed to make a $15,000 donation to maple
research at the University of Vermont.
   The complaint included allegations that the company labeled
maple syrup at a higher grade than it should have been and sold
products carrying labels such as ``pure Vermont maple candy'' that
included cane sugar.
   Maple Grove President William Callahan III said in a prepared
statement that the company was being ``taken out to the woodshed
for some problems beyond our control and others for which we can
make little argument.''
   He said the company agreed to the fine to avoid a costly legal
battle.
   The settlement followed an investigation by the attorney
general's office.
   ``We've just come through the two absolute worst years in the
maple business, not only in terms of quantity but also in terms of
quality,'' Callahan said in a telephone interview. ``It was
difficult to have syrup at the higher end of grade range. It would
not withstand the test of time.''
   As part of the settlement, Maple Grove is to notify customers
that some sryup sold in 1987 and during the first three months of
1988 may have darkened, fallen below grade or been misgraded. Some
changes in labeling also were agreed upon on containers that
contain syrup not produced in Vermont.
   Maple Grove also agreed to recall maple candy sold between April
1987 and April 1988. The candy is to be re-labeled as a
maple-flavored product or destroyed.
   Steven Wallach of the Vermont Department of Agriculture said
that while inspectors are continously sampling maple products, no
other companies were involved in this investigation.
</TEXT>
