<HEAD>Veteran Physical Education Prof Named Temporary College Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westfield State College trustees chose a
veteran faculty member and former field hockey coach Tuesday to
temporarily head the troubled college following the resignation of
President Irving H. Buchen.
   Buchen quit last week after his use of college trust funds for
personal expenses came under scrutiny and criticism.
   He also had been under fire for waiving entrance requirements
for his 16-year-old daughter. She attended the college and lived in
a dormitory during the fall semester last year although she had not
graduated from high school.
   ``We are very fortunate to have someone of her intellect,
ability and common sense to oversee the supervision of the college
during this period,'' said John St. Clair, chairman of the
trustees, in announcing the appointment of Tilia J. Fantasia.
   Buchen was hired by Westfield State 15 months ago, succeeding
Francis J. Pilecki, who left amid charges of sexual misconduct with
male students, and a furor over a $10,000 payment by trustees to
one of the students. He was cleared of criminal charges.
