<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrunkenDriving     08-02 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drunken Driving,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beer Industry Official Supports Drunken Driving Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of an association of beer
distributors voiced support Tuesday for a bill that would encourage
states to crack down on drunken drivers.
   ``Beer wholesalers don't need the business of drunk drivers,''
Ronald R. Rumbaugh, president of the National Beer Wholesalers'
Association, told the Senate Commerce consumer subcommittee. ``We
don't want their business. In fact, we want to put them out of
business.''
   The subcommittee heard from Rumbaugh and other private and
government officials about proposed legislation offering increased
federal aid to states that adopt several strict plans intended to
prevent traffic accidents caused by drunken drivers.
   Among them are the immediate confiscation of a driver's license
when the operator fails a chemical test for intoxication or refuses
to take such a test. The state would have 15 days to suspend the
license or return it to the operator.
   Twenty-three states and the District of Columbia already have
programs in which drivers' licenses can be suspended through
administrative action, rather than by the courts, according to the
Insurance Institute for Highway Safety.
   ``By encouraging states to adopt tough laws that have proven to
be effective, the bill will save lives,'' said Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., the measure's chief sponsor.
   An official of the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration said his agency opposed the legislation.
   George Reagle, associate administrator for traffic safety, said
the bill had such tight procedures _ such as allowing only 15 days
to decide on license suspensions _ that most states would not be
able to benefit from it.
</TEXT>
