<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0704 08-02 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0704,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglicans Call For Freeing of Hostages; U.S. Bishop Hopeful</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf `About White' to CORRECT spelling of name to
Waite</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's Anglican bishops urged
governments Tuesday to press for the release of hostages held in
Lebanon, and an American bishop said he was optimistic after months
of talks with Iranian officials.
   A resolution passed unanimously by the 525 bishops said
governments ``with influence'' should pressure kidnappers in
Lebanon to free foreign hostages, who include Anglican church envoy
Terry Waite and nine Americans.
   Mostakbal, an Arabic-language weekly published in Paris, quoted
the spiritual leader of Lebanon's most radical pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslem group Tuesday as saying American hostages may be freed
before the U.S. presidential election in November.
   Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah's organization is Hezbollah, or
Party of God, which is believed to be the umbrella for groups
holding most of the 18 foreign hostages.
   Episcopal Bishop Robert C. Witcher of Long Island, N.Y., said he
began talks in April with Iranian officials accompanying victims of
chemical weapon attacks in the Iran-Iraq war who were taken to New
York for treatment.
   ``I would say from my conversations with the Iranians that they
really want to solve this problem,'' Witcher said in an interview
after addressing the Lambeth conference of Anglican bishops in
Canterbury.
   The resolution, which welcomed U.N. efforts for a cease-fire in
the 8-year-old war, also condemned the use of chemical weapons and
said ``further use by any country should immediately be met by
punitive sanctions.''
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual head of the
Church of England and worldwide Anglican Communion, has made new
efforts to free Waite and the other foreigners.
   Australian Archbishop David Penman returned last week from Iran
and the Rt. Rev. John Brown, bishop in Cyprus and the Persian Gulf,
was in Lebanon seeking information about four Iranians who
disappeared in a Christian area of the city in July 1982.
   Penman said Monday he believes the Western hostages will be
released after national elections in November in Israel and the
United States.
   Runcie has tried to learn the fate of the Iranians as part of an
attempt to get Iran to use its influence with kidnappers holding
foreign hostages. Unconfirmed reports say the Iranians, all
Moslems, were killed.
   ``The grief of the families of hostages is universal, knowing no
boundaries of religion or nationality,'' he said at the conference.
   About Waite, who disappeared in January 1987 after leaving his
hotel to negotiate for the release of Americans, Archbishop Runcie
said: ``He was kidnapped more than 18 months ago, 561 days ago, and
it is day by day that the families of hostages count their misery.''
   The hostage held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Witcher, 61, said he met Iranian officials for the first time at
St. John's Episcopal Hospital in the New York City borough of
Queens _ part of his diocese _ where several Iranian Kurds gassed
in the war were treated.
   He said in an interview he continued talks with the Iranians
``at the hospital, at their office in the embassy and at their
homes.'' Witcher said he had not discussed the talks with the State
Department.
   ``They (the Iranians) said they would deliver the message to
Tehran and left it at that,'' the bishop said.
</TEXT>
