<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Young-Bond 1stLd-Writethru a0645 08-02 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Young-Bond, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Reports On Police Handling of Bond Allegations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with more details from report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen months after it was appointed, a panel
that looked into the handling of drug abuse allegations against
former state Sen. Julian Bond by his wife has concluded its work
with only one recommendation _ that standard operating procedures
in the Atlanta Police Bureau be redefined.
   The committee of civic leaders was appointed by Mayor Andrew
Young in April 1987 to look into how police and other city
officials handled Alice Bond's allegations that her estranged
husband and other prominent Atlantans abused cocaine. Bond denied
using drugs.
   In its report to the mayor Monday, the panel did not address the
conduct of any city officials.
   Co-chairmen Jesse Hill Jr. and Thomas R. Williams wrote that the
redefinition of police procedures the panel called for ``will
probably occur during the (police department's national)
accreditation review, which the panel understands is presently
under way.
   ``However, if this does not occur, a management study of the
department and its standard operating procedures should be
conducted.''
   Young ``really didn't have anything to say about the report,''
said his spokesman, Nehl Horton. ``He thanked them for their hard
work.''
   Public Safety Commissioner George Napper could not be reached
for comment. He was testifying Tuesday in Washington before a
Senate committee about gun control.
   Mrs. Bond made her allegations to Atlanta police narcotics
investigators in March 1987.
   She later withdrew the allegations after a call from Young.
There were accusations at the time that the mayor pressured Mrs.
Bond and that the white officers who talked to her manipulated the
statement to implicate black officials.
   The panel made five observations about the Police Bureau in its
report.
   It said standard operating procedures frequently were not
followed, that levels of competence in the Police Bureau are
varied, that residual racial problems exist in the bureau, that
internal security and confidentiality are lax, and that discipline
is inconsistently administered.
   The bulk of the six-page report complained about roadblocks to
the panel's work resulting from media and court activities, saying,
``we regret the combination of circumstances that rendered
concerned, well-meaning citizens not as effective in this challenge
for our community as we would have preferred.''
   ``The initial delay came with the investigation by the federal
grand jury. This investigation resulted in no indictments. The next
delay came with the request from The Atlanta Journal and The
Atlanta Constitution that all of the panel's meeting be opened to
all media and the public.''
   The panel's refusal of that request resulted in a lawsuit that
eventually resulted in a ruling from the Georgia Supreme Court that
the panel was not subject to the state's open meetings laws.
   The panel did not meet during those court proceedings.
   The investigation also was hindered by a restraining order
obtained by radio and televison stations that prohibited the
Atlanta Police Department's Office of Professional Standards from
handing over the so-called ``Bond Report,'' a review of the charges.
   ``Without this report, the panel, without any funding to employe
investigators or other staff, was stymied in its efforts to conduct
a timely and adequate review,'' the report said.
   ``Its subpoena power had been declared illegal by the Supreme
Court of Georgia. It was clear that the newspapers and television
stations had as much or more documentation of relevant information,
in that they had obtained copies of the Alice Bond interview tape,
the confidential memo from the interview officers ... directed to
Chief (Morris) Redding summarizing the Alice Bond interview, as
well as a copy of the complete detailed Office of Professional
Standards' report.
   In addition, the panel said, ``the mayor's pardon of all police
officers mooted most of what remained for the panel's
investigation'' and it decided its work was concluded.
</TEXT>
