<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YonkersDeseg Bjt   08-02 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, Bjt,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Finds City in Contempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Tuesday imposed fines that could
bankrupt the city of Yonkers because of its defiance of a housing
desegregation order and suggested that Gov. Mario Cuomo remove
recalcitrant council members from office.
   ``There does have to come a moment of truth, a moment of
responsibility, a moment when the city of Yonkers seeks not to
become the national symbol of defiance to civil rights, heaping
shame upon shame upon itself,'' said District Judge Leonard Sand.
   Ruling that Yonkers was in contempt for not approving his plan
to desegregate housing, Sand fined the city $100 for the first day
and said the amount would double each succeeding day. After 22
days, the fines would swallow the city's entire $337 million budget.
   Sand also found three of four councilmen who voted against his
plan in contempt and fined them $500 a day. The fourth had his case
adjourned so he could get a lawyer. The judge also said the council
members could go to jail if they remain in contempt until Aug. 10.
   The council members have said they would appeal the contempt
finding and the penalties, but no quick hearing is likely and all
previous attempts to appeal Sand's rulings have failed.
   Sand's action came after two years of threats against Yonkers
for failing to build low- and middle-income housing after he ruled
i 1985 that the city had segregated housing and schools
intentionally over a 40-year period. It was the first time a judge
had tied school segregation to housing segregation.
   On Monday night, the City Council voted 4-3 against the
court-ordered package of bonuses, financial incentives and zoning
variances to attract developers to build 800 units of affordable
housing throughout the city.
   Michael Sculnick, the city's outside counsel, asked the judge
not to fine the city because it was the council, not the city,
which had taken the action. The fines would ruin the city's fiscal
standing, he said, noting that Moody's Investors Service has said a
contempt finding would jeopardize the city's bond rating.
   But Sand said the council had been aware of the implications of
its actions all along and called its action a ``competition to see
who can attract the greatest notoriety ... who will be the
political martyr without regard for what is in the best interest of
the city of Yonkers.''
   Saying the council was unable to govern in a ``fiscally
responsible manner,'' Sand urged the state to step in.
   The city was saved from bankruptcy in 1984 by a state bailout
and has its finances supervised by a state-run Emergency Financial
Control Board, which can remove council members for fiscal
irresponsibility.
   When Sculnick said that might be an unfair burden on the state,
Sand angrily replied, ``Unfair to have a responsibility when a city
of almost 200,000 totters on the brink of bankruptcy, makes itself
a symbol of defiance to a federal court and acts in a manner so
devastatingly adverse to the interest of its citizens? It's too
much to ask state officials to respond?''
   After the ruling, a spokesman for the governor said only that
Cuomo's office and the Financial Control Board were monitoring the
situation. On Monday, Cuomo said it would be ``inappropriate'' for
the state to intervene.
   Mayor Nicholas Wasiscko, who has supported the desegregation
plan, said he would contact Cuomo Tuesday but would not ask for the
removal of council members.
   If the council doesn't reverse its opposition to the plan and
the state doesn't intervene, Sand could form a housing commission
to build the new housing without council approval.
   Attorneys for Nicholas Longo, Peter Chema and Edward Fagan said
they opposed the plan because of procedural deficiencies in the
resolution. Sand set an evidentiary hearing for Monday, but still
found them in contempt.
   Vice Mayor Henry Spallone, the most vociferous opponent,
appeared without a lawyer and had his case adjourned until at least
Wednesday.
   Fagan said he would consider resigning from the council but
Longo and Spallone said they would not resign. Chema declined
comment.
   After the court session, officials were greeted outside the
courthouse by about 100 demonstrators chanting, ``Don't get mad,
get a new mayor,'' referring to Wasiscko's support for the plan,
and ``No justice, no peace.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
