<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-UN     08-02 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-UN,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Envoy Says Iraq Won't Accept Unilateral Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iraqi envoy declared Tuesday that
his government will reject any attempt by the United Nations to
impose a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war with Iraq without
previous consent from Baghdad.
   ``We will not accept a fait accompli, no matter in what form or
from which quarter it comes,'' said Riyadh al-Qaysi, Iraq's former
U.N. ambassador and now a member of the Iraqi delegation to U.N.
peace talks.
   Qaysi repeated Iraq's demand for face-to-face talks with Iran
before any truce. He said Iran's insistence on an immediate
cease-fire and rejection of direct talks at this time shows ``what
they are aiming at is simply a cease-fire which they so urgently
need after their successive defeats.''
   He said, ``We shall never give the Iranians that chance (to use
a truce to regroup).''
   Qaysi was reacting to reports that Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar might unilaterally declare a cease-fire in the
war, even if Iraq rejects it. That would increase pressure on Iraq
to agree to an early peace settlement and drop its demand for
direct talks.
   But Perez de Cuellar later told reporters, ``I am prepared to
continue discussions with all parties concerned and I think `fait
accompli' is a little of imagination of those who use the word and
don't know what it means.''
   He and U.N. officials emphasized Tuesday that the U.N. chief did
not intend to declare a cease-fire unilaterally, although he has
the power to do so.
   They said he would consult first with the head of U.N.
cease-fire fact-finding team, Gen. Martin Vadset, who arrives
Thursday from the region, then the Security Council and possibly
the foreign ministers of Iraq and Iran.
   Perez de Cuellar held no official meetings Tuesday with Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati or Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq
Aziz. He has been seeing them since last week.
   On Monday night Perez de Cuellar told reporters, ``Listen, D-Day
(the day a cease-fire begins) does not depend on the parties.''
   Asked if he might announce D-Day if Iraq remains opposed, the
U.N. chief said: ``That is a decision which I have to take in any
case in consultation with the members of the Security Council.''
   Perez de Cuellar told reporters on Tuesday he may be in touch
with the Iraqi and Iranian foreign ministers as well.
   Iran rejects direct talks with Iraq before a cease-fire, troop
withdrawal and prisoner exchange.
   Iranian Mission spokesman Amir Zamani told reporters Tuesday
that Qaysi's statement was ``a demagogic argument'' because it
claims Iran does not seek a lasting peace, only a temporary truce.
   An estimated million people have died in the Iran-Iraq war that
began in September 1980.
   Iran resisted for a year a U.N. Security Council demand for a
cease-fire, but last July 18, the Tehran government abruptly
announced it would go along. Now it accuses Iraq of procrastinating.
   Qaysi said that Resolution 598 ``is not simply a cease-fire. It
is a peace plan and that has to be negotiated face-to-face to test
the real intentions of Iran.''
   On Tuesday Francois Giuliani, spokesman for the
secretary-general, told reporters the U.N. chief does not intend to
act unilaterally. ``Theoretically he can do so; practically he will
consult.''
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati reaffirmed Tuesday
that his government thinks the secretary-general is obliged to
declare a D-Day to begin a cease-fire, even if Iraq is opposed.
   Mahallati said the Security Council should consider imposing an
arms embargo against Iraq if it does not accept a truce. He also
said the council should act swiftly to condemn Iraq by name for
repeated and large-scale use of outlawed chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
