<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Cyprus     08-02 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cyprus,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Of Cyprus Disavows Union With Greece</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou of Cyprus pledged
Tuesday his country would not seek union with Greece if Turkish
troops departed.
   ``The concept of union with Greece is not anymore considered a
realistic objective,'' Vassiliou said at a news conference.
   Turkey invaded the island in 1974 ostensibly to protect the
minority Turkish Cypriot population against the possibility that
Cyprus would unite with Greece.
   Greek Cypriots form about 70 percent of the country's population.
   Vassiliou said most want Cyprus to develop as an independent
country with Greek and Turkish Cypriots living in peace.
   But he stressed the estimated 30,000 Turkish troops and 50,000
Turkish settlers must leave. They are concentrated in the north
where there is a separate Turkish Cypriot state.
   Vassiliou, who met on Monday with President Reagan, has proposed
the creation of a federalized republic and the demilitarization of
Cyprus.
   He will hold talks in New York on Aug. 24 with Rauf Denktash,
leader of the Turkish Cypriot community, under United Nations
auspices.
   Vassiliou said he hoped the meeting was the first step toward a
settlement.
   If the Turkish troops and tanks depart, he said, Cyprus will
give up its right to have its own military forces and dismiss its
army of 10,000.
   ``The several hundred million dollars saved would be diverted to
economic development, especially the Turkish Cypriot community,
which has fallen behind,'' he said.
   ``Today, the free part of Cyprus has a healthy economy,'' he
said earlier in a speech. ``Our standard of living is high. We are
farming, we are producing, we are trading, we are investing, we are
growing.
   ``And I must emphasize that this near miraculous recovery of our
country was achieved in the face of the Turkish occupying forces.
But despite our success, the real potential of Cyprus cannot be
realized because of the presence of this occupation force which
prevents the Turkish Cypriot community from contributing and
sharing in Cyprus' growth.''
</TEXT>
