<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Blacks-Japan     08-02 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blacks-Japan,460</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Black Caucus Calls on Japan To End Derogatory Advertising
^By JIM STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Congressional Black Caucus and
other lawmakers on Tuesday called on Japan to end advertising and
marketing practices that are derogatory and offensive to blacks in
the United States.
   The lawmakers accused three Japanese firms of producing products
and mannequins which show blacks in a stereotypical and degrading
light. They are the Sanrio Co., Sogo Department Store and Yamato
Mannequin Co.
   Rep. Mervyn M. Dymally, D-Calif., the caucus chairman, suggested
blacks might boycott Japanese products if changes are not made. He
said the portrayal of blacks in marketing and advertising in Japan
is insensitive and racially inflammatory.
   Dymally made public a letter to Japan's Prime Minister, Noboru
Takeshita, urging him to call a meeting with Japanese businessmen
``to formally bring an end to the negative stereotypic
representations of black Americans once and for all.''
   ``As pressure mounts for national boycotts of Japanese
products,'' Dymally added, ``it is imperative that your country
sends a clear message that it understands and is sensitive to the
political environments in which it does business.''
   Kenichiro Ide, a spokesman for Sanrio, told the Washington Post
last month that the firm's line of toys, which portray Little Black
Sambo with large white eyes and a round, black face, was not meant
to offend blacks.
   He said they should be seen in a humorous and friendly light,
adding, ``Nobody in Japan regards this as racist.''
   Sogo Department Stores and Yamato Mannequin Co. also have said
they had no racist intentions.
   Masaaki Honjo, spokesman for Sogo, told the Post the store had
no intentions of discriminating. Kauhiro Nakajima, an official with
Yasmato, said the black mannequins, ``show strong personality,
energy and charm.'' He also said that it was the company's
conclusion that the exaggerated racial features on the mannequins
were not racist depictions of blacks.
   However, members of the caucus, as well as Reps. Julian C. Dixon
D-Calif., and Robert T. Matsui D-Calif., disagreed.
   ``When officials repeatedly apologize for offensive racial slurs
by calling them `humorous' and seeing no harm done, it is not a
faux pas, an aberration, a gaffe or a slip of the tongue. It is a
dangerous mind set,'' Matsui said.
   Dixon said Japan ``is not an isolated colony that could hide
behind the defense of ignorance. It is a worldwide, economic giant
... a leader in overseas investment in an era of global travel. ...
It has the new responsibility to act like a world leader.''
   Dymally and other caucus members also complained about Japan's
becoming South Africa's No. 1 trading partner at a time when the
United States is encouraging other nations to join its partial
trade boycott against that country's white minority government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0187 </DOCNO>
