<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Unrest     08-02 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Unrest,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Close Three Soweto Schools After Disruptions, Damage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials suspended classes at
three high schools in the huge Soweto black township outside
Johannesburg on Tuesday, the day after widespread disruptions and
damage to school property.
   Students threw stones at security personnel, damaged school vans
and intimidated other pupils into leaving classes when education
inspectors arrived at the schools Monday, officials said. No
injuries or arrests were reported.
   Peet Struwig, acting chief director of the Department of
Education and Training, said he would recommend schools remain
closed until ``parents can give assurances that normal teaching can
be resumed without further disruptions.''
   Campus unrest and school boycotts occurred during the 1984-86
period of nationwide violence in most black urban areas, but
violence and boycotts have been only sporadic in the past 18 months.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, the largest black
labor federation, reported Tuesday that 16 members of affiliated
unions had been detained in recent days. It said most were union
officials involved in labor disputes with management.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for
varying periods during the state of emergency in effect since June
12, 1986.
   In downtown Durban, police cordoned off the area and detonated a
grenade workers found in a manhole.
   Three black people were killed and five stabbed or burned when
groups of blacks attacked houses, vehicles and individuals in five
Natal province townships overnight, police reported.
   National police headquarters in Pretoria reported these
incidents in its unrest report for the preceding 24 hours:
   _One attacker was fatally stabbed during an assault on a house
in Amanzimtoti, outside Durban.
   _Two men were stabbed by crowds, one fatally, in two separate
attacks in Nhanhlakahle, near Greytown. Two houses were attacked in
the area, during which a black woman was shot to death and three
women were burned.
   _A crowd attacked a private vehicle in Hammarsdale and stabbed
one of its occupants; a bus was stoned in Georgetown, and a house
was firebombed in Sweetwaters, resulting in the arrest of a black
man.
   _A man fired at a security patrol in Kwanobuhle, outside
Uitenhage in eastern Cape province, wounding an officer.
   No further details were given in any of the cases.
   State of emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest,
security force action, treatment of detainees, some forms of
protest and a wide range of statments the government classifies as
subversive.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
