<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EconomicOutlook     08-02 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economic Outlook,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Report Says Inflationary Pressures Increasing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation is beginning to see increasing
inflationary pressures, with prices rising for a wide range of
products from metals and paper to food, the Federal Reserve Board
said in a review of the economy Tuesday.
   The outlook, based on reports from all 12 regional Federal
Reserve banks, found that bottlenecks were beginning to develop in
some sectors of the economy. U.S. industry is now operating at 83.1
percent of capacity, the highest level in eight years.
   ``Capacity constraints and shortages have developed in some
(Federal Reserve) districts and materials price increases are
widespread,'' the summary of the report concluded.
   The report, known internally as the ``tan book,'' will be used
as a starting point for discussions when Fed policymakers gather in
two weeks to map monetary strategy.
   The central bank has instituted a series of small
credit-tightening moves this year in an effort to dampen growing
inflationary pressures. Those efforts have pushed a variety of
interest rates, including mortgage rates, higher, with many
analysts forecasting further tightening in the months ahead as
price increases continue unabated.
   Price increases for metals, paper and food were widely noted in
the reports from the various Fed districts. Several districts
reported shortages for such manufactured products as steel, valves,
motors and chemicals.
   ``In this environment, manufacturers are reportedly choosing to
hold higher inventories and are finding it easier to raise their
own finished goods prices,'' the report said.
   It said tight labor markets were being reported in some areas as
the current economic recovery, now almost six years old, continued
at moderate to strong levels in most areas.
   On other economic issues, the report found:
   _The impact of the drought varies considerably, even within a
state. Corn and wheat crops have suffered extensive damage, but
recent rains may be enough to save much of the soybean crop.
   _Retail sales have been generally lackluster, with only the
Atlanta and Minneapolis regions reporting any real strength. Sales
of clothing and furniture have been particularly weak, although
demand for autos has rebounded.
   _Residential construction is below levels of a year ago, but
non-residential construction showed signs of higher activity in
some regions of the country.
</TEXT>
