<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HospitalStrike     08-02 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Strike,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Registered Nurses Strike Six Hospitals Over Pay Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 2,000 registered nurses demanding
higher pay went on strike Tuesday at six major hospitals, joining
nearly 1,700 service employees who walked off the job last week.
   ``We're really behind other RNs in the area, and in view of the
nursing shortage, that becomes a patient-care issue,'' said Paula
Fillari, a nurse at Saint Francis Memorial Hospital in San
Francisco.
   But the five hospitals in San Francisco and one in neighboring
Daly City said they would continue to provide good care despite the
first widespread strike here by nurses in 14 years.
   The hospitals said they were flying in temporary nurses,
transferring some patients and planned to restrict surgery to
emergencies and defer admissions.
   ``We have a labor pool in place to continue providing quality
patient care,'' said Terry Hastings, a spokeswoman for Children's
Hospital in San Francisco.
   The strike by members of the California Nurses Association
followed a breakdown in talks with a federal mediator shortly
before midnight Monday. The union rejected a revised offer by the
employers, and picket lines went up at 7 a.m. when overnight shifts
ended.
   Nurses, many in white uniforms, walked in quiet, orderly lines
outside hospital entrances, carrying signs reading: ``Thou shalt
not commit scabbery. Love thy nurses as thyself,'' ``Why is there a
nursing shortage?'' and ``Really needed, little noticed.''
   ``None of us like being out here. There's a lot of personal
agony doing this,'' Fillari said.
   Other affected hospitals were Children's, Marshal Hale, Mount
Zion and St. Mary's in San Francisco and Seton Medical Center in
Daly City. The six negotiated jointly as Affiliated Hospitals of
San Francisco.
   The same hospitals, along with Pacific Presbyterian Hospital in
San Francisco, were struck July 26 by 1,700 licensed vocational
nurses and service workers in a dispute over sick leave and health
benefits. Registered nurses at Pacific Presbyterian, also part of
Affiliated Hospitals, do not belong to the California Nurses
Association.
   Pay has been the chief issue in the dispute.
   The nurses group originally asked for 15 percent raises for each
year of a two-year contract but later changed its proposal to 11
percent the first year and 10 percent the next. Nurses also sought
higher pay for working on weekends and regular pay raises for
veteran nurses.
   On Monday night, Affiliated Hospitals made a new proposal that a
spokeswoman said would bring nurses parity with those working at
Kaiser Foundation hospitals in the San Francisco Bay area.
   The hospitals' previous offer included 5 percent increases for
each year of a three-year contract.
   Monday night's proposal called for a 7 percent increase the
first year with an extra 2 percent for nurses with 10 years or more
of service, a 5 percent increase effective Jan. 1, 1989, and
another 6 percent the following year, Affiliated Hospitals
spokeswoman Janis MacKenzie said. Nurses with 15 years or more
tenure would get another 2 percent in the final year.
   The nurses association, however, called the offer unacceptable
and declined to present it to its members.
   Registered nurses at Affiliated Hospitals earn from about
$31,000 to about $36,000 for day shifts and up to $43,000 a year
for night shifts.
</TEXT>
