<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MedflyEradication     08-02 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medfly Eradication,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sterile Fruit Flies Released in Second Phase of Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials unleashed millions of sterile pink
Mediterranean fruit flies over a 16-square-mile area Tuesday in an
effort to breed the agricultural scourge to extinction.
   The release of 4 million sterile flies, including the afternoon
release by an airplane strafing the San Fernando Valley, is the
second phase of a two-pronged battle to get rid of the voracious,
crop-destroying pest.
   Last week, agriculture officials bombarded the area with the
pesticide malathion. Any survivors of that attack should be so
outnumbered by the swarms of sterile flies that they will mate only
with sterile flies, said Robert Donley, deputy director of the
county Agriculture Commission.
   ``They breed themselves out of existence,'' explained Donley.
   Cardboard buckets laden with sterile Medflies were carried by
truck throughout the area and released starting at 10 a.m.
   Officials will release about 20 million flies over four days
this week and continue the procedure each week for about two months
to cover two potential generations of Medflies, which have a
lifespan of about a month, Donley said. Inspectors continued to
monitor traps scattered in trees throughout the area. Sterile flies
attracted by the baited traps can be distinguished by their
fluorescent pink dye.
   ``The color isn't visible to the naked eye,'' Donley said.
``When collected in traps, they are looked at under black lights to
see if they are sterile ones.''
   The Medfly threatens the state's $14 billion-a-year agricultural
industry because it lays eggs in more than 250 varieties of fruits
and vegetables. The flies usually enter the state on fruit brought
back from Hawaii by tourists.
   Six flies had been found recently in the San Fernando Valley, a
100-square-mile area that includes a number of bedroom suburbs
northwest of Los Angeles, Donley said. No new flies were found
Monday or Tuesday, he said.
   The use of sterile flies helped eradicate a Medfly infestation
last summer in eastern Los Angeles County.
   The cobalt-treated sterile flies are raised in Hawaii at a
laboratory established after California's 1981 Medfly infestation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
