<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     08-02 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomats Say Soviet, Afghan Troops on Offensive Around Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Afghan troops are on the
offensive around Kabul in an attempt to stop guerrilla attacks on
the Afghan capital, Western diplomats reported Tuesday.
   They said 15-20 rockets had hit Kabul in the past week, killing
at least 19 people, but the number was lower than for comparable
periods recently.
   Diplomats said Kandahar, Afghanistan's second largest city,
probably will be the next major troop withdrawal point as the
Soviets try to meet the Aug. 15 deadline for pulling at least
50,000 Red Army troops out of the country.
   The Western sources quoted East European diplomats as saying the
Soviets already had begun leaving Kandahar. The southern city,
Afghanistan's ancient capital, is under siege by guerrillas.
   An estimated 100,000-115,000 Red Army soldiers were in
Afghanistan when the Soviets signed a U.N.-mediated agreement April
14 to pull its forces out. The withdrawal began May 15, with half
to be gone by Aug. 15 and the rest by Feb. 15, 1989.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting in Afghanistan after a
communist coup in April 1978 and Soviet military forces were sent
to the country in December 1979.
   Diplomats said Soviet and Afghan troops, officers of the Khad
secret service and members of the presidential guard were trying to
drive the insurgents away from Kabul.
   They said the defenders moved into the besieged Paghman area
nine miles west of Kabul late last week. The town of Paghman is
said to have been abandoned by its civilian population.
   Other troop movements southwest and northwest of the city also
have been reported, said the Western sources, all of whom spoke on
condition of anonymity. Some reports from diplomats and guerrillas
have said Soviet soldiers were being brought in from northern
Afghanistan.
   Soviet officials say 35,000 soldiers have left Afghanistan since
May 15 and the diplomats say Kandahar will be the next city whose
defense will be turned over to government troops.
   Estimates of the number of Soviet troops in Kandahar range from
2,000 to 8,000.
   Azim Nasser-Zia of the National Islamic Front, one of the
strongest guerrilla organizations in Kandahar, said about 6,000
Soviet soldiers are in the area.
   Guerrillas have operated in Kandahar since the war began, making
regular forays into the city, and most Soviet soldiers in Kandahar
are at the heavily fortified airport.
</TEXT>
