<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Quake     08-02 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-Quake,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Rocks Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake rattled windows in Tokyo and
shook the metropolitan area Tuesday night, but police said it
caused no immediate damage.
   The tremor measured 5.1 on the Richter scale and was centered
six miles under the sea off the Izu Peninsula, 75 miles southwest
of Tokyo, the Central Meteorological Agency said.
   It was among the strongest in a week of tremors in the Izu
region. The agency said 24 quakes were recorded Monday, most of
them minor, but seismologists said they do not expect a major
earthquake soon.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. A reading of 5 could cause considerable damage in the
local area, and an earthquake measuring a 6 could cause severe
damage.
</TEXT>
