<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0705 08-02 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0887</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma Detains Two More, Assasination Attempt Rumored</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 5 grafs after 10th pvs, Initial reports ... UPDATING
with AP president's letter to Burmese president. PICKS up 11th graf
pvs, The U.S. ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's new leadership, continuing its
campaign to stamp out dissent, arrested two aging war heroes who
allegedly plotted to overthrow the week-old government, Western
diplomats in Burma said Tuesday.
   Reports of the latest arrests came amid rumors that Sein Lwin,
the country's leader, was the target of an assassination attempt
Friday by a personal assistant who wounded him slightly in the arm
and then killed himself.
   ``The rumors are widespread enough to be taken seriously but we
cannot confirm them,'' said a Western diplomat reached in Rangoon,
the Burmese capital. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The London-based human rights group Amnesty International,
meanwhile, expressed concern over the arrests last week of Aung
Gyi, the country's most vocal dissident, and as many as 24 of his
friends and political associates.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Ta
Ya and Yan Nyang were arrested Monday in connection with
underground pamphlets calling for the overthrow of Sein Lwin.
   The two were members of ``Thirty Comrades'' _ a group of young
men who in December 1941 mixed blood from their arms in a silver
bowl and vowed to liberate Burma from British colonialism.
   The men at first fought with the Japanese, then switched
allegiance to the allies battling Japan's forces in their homeland.
Their leader, Aung San, negotiated the end of colonial rule and
would have become one of the country's first leaders had he not
been assassinated in 1947.
   On Monday, the government announced it arrested Aung Gyi and his
associates for allegedly ``attacking the state.''
   A list of the detainees released by the official News Agency
Burma included a number of retired military officers who had fallen
out with former leader Ne Win in the 1960s as well as Associated
Press correspondent Sein Win.
   Initial reports on the government announcement did not mention
Sein Win as one of those listed.
   Louis D. Boccardi, president and general manager of the AP, said
in a letter to Sein Lwin, dated Tuesday, that The Associated Press
is ``deeply concerned'' over Sein Win's arrest and detention and
``would appreciate further information and a clarification of the
charges'' against him.
   Boccardi asked that an AP representative be allowed to visit
Sein Win and expressed hope the family already had that privilege.
   Boccardi said a reported charge of ``attacking the state''
against the correspondent ``does not comport with our long
knowledge of'' Sein Win.
   He said that until his arrest, Sein Win ``was in daily contact
with officials and media there in his attempt to report
impartially, honestly and accurately on the situation in your
country.''
   ``In his conversations with other AP correspondents and
executives he has made clear his determination to portray Burma
impartially and fairly to the world,'' Boccardi noted, adding that
Sein Win at times objected when he felt a news report ``did not
justly describe the situation as he knew it.''
   The U.S. State Department and other sources say as many as 25
people may have been arrested in the sweep last week. Rangoon has
only mentioned 10.
   In statements released Monday and Tuesday, Amnesty International
said the detainees ``may be prisoners of conscience held for their
non-violent, political beliefs.''
   ``At last report, they were held incommunicado without charge or
trial in Insein Central Prison, near Rangoon,'' the statements
said, adding they had not been brought before a court and had been
refused visits by lawyers or family members.
   The group quoted journalists as saying that Sein Win's recent
reporting on Burma was ``independent and objective,'' and
speculating that the reporting contributed to his arrest.
   The London-based International Press Institute, a media watchdog
group, protested the AP reporter's detention in a letter to Burmese
leader Sein Lwin, according to Peter Galliner, director of the
institute.
   Rangoon radio said the new leader had met with members of the
``central organs of power'' Monday and urged them to abide by the
law, respect human rights and review the country's run-down economy
to implement needed reforms.
   ``This new government is trying to effect some economic reform
but it's quite clear that the hopes of political reform have been
pretty well bashed,'' said one Western diplomat in Bangkok.
   Diplomats in Rangoon said students and some Buddhist monks have
been staging peaceful protests daily at Shwedagon Pagoda, Burma's
holiest shrine and a traditional center for protest.
   Pamphlets also have been circulating in the Burmese capital
calling for a nationwide general strike Aug. 8.
   Western diplomats have described Sein Lwin, who took power when
Ne Win resigned last month after 26 years of authoritarian rule, as
widely unpopular in Burma. He is blamed for ruthless suppression of
student riots in Rangoon last March in which more than 100 people
are said to have died.
   ``The unanswered question is whether the students and public can
translate distaste for Sein Lwin into action, and what response the
army will have,'' one diplomat said.
</TEXT>
