<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Palestinian     08-02 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Palestinian,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Palestinian Terrorist Undergoes Identity Check</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district attorney identified a man in
custody as a Palestinian wanted by the United States for a 1982
bombing of a passenger jet that killed one person and wounded 15.
   District Attorney Ioannis Lambropoulos, after a court-ordered
identity check, said Thursday he was convinced the man was Mohammed
Rashid, 39, and not Mohammed Hamdan, as the Palestinian claimed.
   ``That's who I said he was. It's now a matter for the council to
decide,'' the district attorney told reporters after the
closed-door examination.
   Lambropoulos will submit his findings to a three-member Appeals
Council to rule on the Palestinian's identity. If the Appeals Court
also identifies him as Rashid, an extradition hearing could be held.
   The United States accuses Rashid of planting a bomb on a Pan Am
jumbo jet. It exploded in Hawaii, killing a Japanese teen-ager and
injuring 15 others.
   Rashid, who also may be linked to a terrorist attack on a Greek
cruise ship three weeks ago, was sentenced July 13 to seven months
in jail for entering Greece on a forged Syrian passport in the name
of Mohammed Hamdan.
   Police theorize the July 11 terrorist attack on the City of
Poros was a botched attempt to hijack the cruise ship and force
Rashid's release. Nine people were killed and 90 of the 471
passengers were wounded.
   Rashid was arrested at Athens airport May 29 on a U.S. Embassy
tip.
   He also is accused of planting a bomb on a TWA jet that exploded
during a flight between Rome and Athens in 1986, killing four
Americans.
   According to his lawyer, Spyros Fitrakis, Rashid told the
district attorney police had arrested the wrong man, but admitted
to membership in the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The Palestinian was identified when his fingerprints were
matched with those of Mohammed Rashid, who was jailed in Greece
from 1973-76 on narcotics smuggling charges.
   Rashid did not speak to reporters as police escorted him from
the courthouse.
</TEXT>
