<2ND_LINE>AM-Iceland-Plane Crash,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Light Plane Crashes, Three Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian light aircraft crashed
Tuesday while trying to land at Reykjavik Airport, killing all
three crewmen and narrowly missing a crowded street, authorities
said.
   The twin-propeller Casa C-212 Aviocar transport plane, on a
flight from Goose Bay, Labrador, emerged from clouds too close to
the runway and stalled as the pilot tried to bring the nose up, the
Directorate of Civil Aviation said.
   It slammed into the ground 150 feet from a road crowded with
traffic and exploded in flames at 6 p.m., the aviation authority
said.
   The plane, owned by the Ottawa company Geoterrex, was bound for
Europe with an overnight stop in the Icelandic capital, it said.
   The identities of the crew members were not immediately released.
</TEXT>
