<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlaneLands     08-02 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Lands,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane's Nose Gear Collapses During Emergency Landing, No One Hurt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDEL HUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nose gear on a twin-engine Allegheny
Commuter collapsed as it was making an emergency landing Tuesday,
but none of the seven people aboard was injured as the plane
skidded down the runway.
   The five passengers and two crewmen had left Indianapolis
International Airport an hour earlier on the Beechcraft turboprop
en route to Owensboro, Ky. After the bumpy landing, four of the
five passengers continued on to Owensboro aboard a second Allegheny
plane, said airline vice president Mickey Bowman.
   ``The fifth passenger said he had had his fill of flying for the
day,'' said Bowman.
   Damage included the nose gear, scrapes along the plane's bottom
and bent propeller tips, said Bob Spitler of the Indianapolis
Airport Authority.
   There was no fire.
   ``Apparently the passengers were calm'' throughout the ordeal,
said Bowman.
   Roger Plymate, the pilot of Flight 3876, noticed smoke when the
motor that retracts the nose gear failed to shut off just after
takeoff.
   ``He declared an emergency and was going to land in
Bloomington,'' said Spitler.
   But Bloomington airport personnel radioed Plymate that the nose
gear was not fully retracted, and he decided to return to the
longer, wider runways at Indianapolis, which also houses the
airline's maintenance base and has more emergency equipment.
   ``There was not a lot of smoke,'' said Bowman. ``Just a smell.
He pulled the circuit breakers, which is standard procedure, and
the smoke went away.''
   After a couple of flybys so control tower personnel could look
at the plane, Spitler said, Plymate put the two main gears onto the
runway, then held the nose gear off as long as possible.
   Spitler praised the crew, saying it was ``a delicate situation
but the pilot put it down very gently and smoothly and he made it a
happy ending. They did a fine job in a difficult situation.''
   Bowman said Indianapolis-based Allegheny Commuter is a feeder
airline for USAir. It has 47 departures daily to various cities in
the Midwest.
   Bowman said he did not know what caused the malfunctioning gear
motor and did not have a damage estimate for the aircraft.
</TEXT>
