<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0643 08-02 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0643,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Calls for Postponing North Trial on Some Counts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top six grafs new to UPDATE with Gesell order, picks up 7th
graf pvs bgng: ``Meantime, North''
^By JAMES ROWLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iran-Contra prosecutor on Tuesday
suggested postponing Oliver L. North's trial on major conspiracy
counts while he attempts to solve the problem of disclosing
classified documents in court.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, conceding the ``problems
of public disclosure are formidable and the outlook discouraging,''
urged the judge to consider trying North on 13 other charges before
taking up the three counts stemming from the diversion of Iranian
arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell indicated in an order
issued later in the day that he would go along with Walsh's
suggestion. The order, which et procedures for next Monday's closed
hearing on classified documents, said the proceeding would focus
only on the 13 other charges that Walsh contends are ready for
trial.
   In his pleading, Walsh said Gesell could still hold a trial _
now set for Sept. 20 _ on all 16 counts against the former White
House aide if he relaxes a July 8 order that the CIA and other
intelligence agencies turn over highly classified documents for
North's defense.
   Gesell has ruled that North needs the material to try to show he
acted with the understanding his activities were approved by higher
authorities in the Reagan administration.
   Under the proposed procedure, ``the intelligence agencies can
continue the process of collecting and analyzing their documents to
assure completion of any additional discovery ordered by the
court,'' Walsh said.
   Meantime, North could be tried on charges that he made false
statements to Congress, obstructed justice by shredding documents,
illegally accepted installation of a $13,800 security fence outside
his home and pocketed $4,300 worth of travelers' checks from the
Contras.
   The former National Security Council aide is also charged with
tax-fraud conspiracy involving private fund-raising for the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   Walsh said these charges do not involve nearly as many
classified documents. Moreover, he said, ``the criminal conduct
alleged in these counts is discrete and the allegations, far from
involving novel legal theories, are routine.''
   That statement amounted to a concession of the legal
difficulties posed by the conspiracy charge against North and three
co-defendants: former national security adviser John M. Poindexter
and arms dealers Albert Hakim and Richard V. Secord.
   The four, who are scheduled to be tried separately, all are
charged with conspiring to defraud the government, theft of
government property and wire fraud in connection with the diversion
of arms-sale proceeds to the Contras.
   Gesell has threatened to dismiss those charges if the government
does not produce the documents North says he needs to show that the
Iran-Contra operation was no different than other covert operations
authorized by President Reagan.
   In a July 25 letter to Walsh, the CIA said it was willing to let
North and his lawyers inspect most of the documents. But the agency
said that details _ or the very existence _ of many covert
activities identified in North's top-secret request cannot be
disclosed in court without jeopardizing national security.
   The CIA said it would take several months to collect many of the
documents sought by North.
   In a filing last week, prosecutor Walsh said much of the
material ``can never be disclosed publicly.''
   But in Tuesday's pleading, he said the charges should not be
dismissed before he is given an opportunity to show that North does
not need the documents for his defense.
   Walsh said he could show ``no authorized covert actions
identified in North's supplemental discovery request were
sufficiently similar to the conduct charged in the indictment to
lead North to believe that that conduct would be proper.''
   Walsh said he knew ``of no analogue for the diversion (of
arms-sale funds) charged in the indictment.''
   North, meanwhile, has asked Gesell to postpone the trial until
next year to give his lawyers more time to study the thousands of
pages of documents already turned over by Walsh. The defense also
contends that North would be unable get a fair trial during the
presidential campaign this fall.
   At last week's hearing, Gesell said he was ``not wedded'' to the
Sept. 20 trial date, adding ``we cannot go forward until we
understand what we are going to try.''
   North faces the most charges in the 23-count indictment returned
March 16.
   Poindexter is additionally charged with obstructing
congressional investigations into covert aid to the Contras. Hakim
and Secord are accused of conspiring to offer an illegal gratuity
to North by setting up a $200,000 Swiss-bank account for his
children's education.
   Secord is also charged with paying an illegal gratuity by
financing the installation of North's security fence.
</TEXT>
