<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Politics     08-02 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Politics,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Opposition Parties Reject Talks On New Election Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of the six opposition parties in
the National Assembly said Tuesday they will boycott debate on a
new election law because the proposal is ``arbitrary,
anti-democratic and anti-pluralistic.''
   A boycott by the Communist, Socialist, Liberal Independent and
Popular Social Christian parties could not block the measure. The
four hold a total of 19 seats in the 96-member legislalture and the
governing Sandinistas have 61.
   The two other opposition parties, the Conservative Democrats and
the Marxist-Leninist Popular Action Movement, hold 16 seats and are
expected to participate in the debate.
   Luis Sanchez Sancho, secretary-general of the Socialist Party,
said the proposed election law would virtually exclude opposition
parties.
   He noted the law would require a party to obtain the signatures
of 10 percent of the nation's registered voters to be considered
legal.
   Sanchez Sancho also said the proposed legislation negates
Sandinista promises of democratic reforms and defies provisions of
a regional peace accord that President Daniel Ortega and the
presidents of four other Central American countries signed on Aug.
7, 1987.
   Ortega submitted the 195-article election-law draft on July 2,
bypassing reform negotiations with the Nicaraguan rebels known as
Contras. At that time, Assembly President Carlos Nunez promised
``intense and controversial'' debate.
   National elections are scheduled for November 1990, and the new
law will replace regulations adopted by the Supreme Electoral
Council in November 1984 when Ortega won a six-year term. Most of
the opposition boycotted the 1984 balloting.
   The Sandinista National Liberation Front has controlled the
government since leading the revolutionary war that ended 42 years
of rule by the rightist Somoza family in July 1979.
</TEXT>
