<DOCNO> AP880802-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-No-NoBoys     08-02 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No-No Boys,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese-American League To Consider Apology Resolution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Congress poised to approve reparations to
Japanese-Americans interned during World War II, the country's
largest Japanese-American organization will consider apologizing to
members of its own community for labeling them as disloyal more
than 40 years ago.
   Among the roughly 120,000 U.S. citizens and resident aliens of
Japanese descent who were put in internment camps during the war,
several hundred young men were labeled ``No-No boys'' for refusing
to sign a U.S. loyalty oath, forswear allegiance to Japan or be
drafted into the military.
   The No-No boys were considered disloyal and some were beaten by
fellow Japanese-Americans. Dozens ended up in prison for refusing
to cooperate.
   Now, the Japanese American Citizens League, which had urged
Japanese-Americans to enlist in the U.S. military during the war,
will consider issuing an apology to the No-No boys at its 30th
annual convention at the University of Washington this week.
   Ben Nakagawa, who is proposing a resolution to issue an apology,
was an elementary school student when his family was shipped to the
Tule Lake camp in California during the war. He said an apology
would heal wounds within the Japanese-American community at a time
when many internment camp survivors are in their last years.
   ``The No-No boys, if they're alive now, they're in their 70s,''
he said. ``I want to have them die in peace with themselves and
with their Nikkei (Japanese-American) community.''
   ``At least within our chapter, there's a feeling people like the
No-No boys ... they, too, were real heroes and victims who have
never been redressed,'' said Roger Shimizu, president of the
league's Seattle chapter.
   ``There's never been any recognition of them. And among other
Japanese-Americans who served in the military, these No-No boys
really were traitors,'' he said.
   The league meets in a week when the Congress is expected to give
final approval to pay tax-free reparations of $20,000 to
Japanese-Americans who were interned.
   Jim Akutsu was a No-No boy. Akutsu said he revolted because he
had tried unsuccessfully to enlist before the government labeled
him an alien and shipped him to an internment camp.
   ``Citizenship is a contract between the people of the country
and the government: You protect me during peacetime and I will
protect you during war,'' said Akutsu, 68, a retired Seattle city
employee.
   ``Someplace along the line, somebody breached the line and took
away my citizenship. All of a sudden, I was 4C, an enemy alien. ...
That's why I challenged it. Am I a citizen? Am I an alien? If I was
an alien, I had no obligation to serve.''
   But Akutsu said he isn't bitter about the treatment he received,
even though he spent about three years in McNeil Island
Penitentiary with 44 other No-No boys from the Minedoka internment
camp. And he said he doesn't need an apology from the league.
   ``I don't belong'' to the league, he said. ``Whatever they did,
it's their thing. Whatever I did is my thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
