<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Campaign     08-02 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Campaign,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Accuses Government of Scare Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders accused the military
government Tuesday of using scare tactics and creating ``a climate
of violence'' in its campaign to win the October presidential
referendum.
   Genaro Arriagada, executive secretary of a 16-party opposition
coalition, said right-wing supporters of President Augusto Pinochet
attacked its campaign offices late last month. Gen. Pinochet is
expected to be the single candidate in the ``yes or no' referendum.
   Arriagada also told a news conference the Interior Ministry gave
``its full support'' to the filming of simulated anti-government
street violence Sunday near the presidential palace.
   Actors with faces masked by kerchiefs, in the style of leftist
extremists, overturned a small truck and built barricades of
burning tires. The film crew would not talk with reporters and
police barred journalists from the area.
   ``A climate of violence is being promoted'' by the Interior
Ministry, Arriagada said. ``The filming of these spots is a
violation of law ... an apology of violence.''
   He said he believed the footage would be used in pro-government
television advertisements.
   Newspapers began publishing paid advertisements Monday with the
headline ``It Happened Just 15 Years Ago'' about violence in the
final weeks of President Salvador Allende's government. Pinochet
led a coup in September 1973 that ousted Allende, an elected
Marxist who died during the military takeover.
   Gutenberg Martinez, secretary-general of the centrist Christian
Democratic Party, claimed the ads were part of a government
``campaign of terror'' and paid for with public funds.
   Carlos Cabello, leader of a pro-Pinochet organization, said the
charges were ``absurd.''
   ``We are only reminding the public that ... these same men who
now are pretending to lead us to democracy and freedom are the same
ones who 15 years ago destroyed the fatherland's roots, trying to
subject Chileans to a tyranical totalitarian dictatorship,'' he
said in an interview with the government news agency Orbe.
   The government candidate will be chosen Aug. 30 by the
commanders of the armed forces and national police, and his name
will be the only one on the ballot. Pinochet is the army commander.
   If a majority approves the candidate, he will serve an
eight-year term starting in March. If he is rejected, open
elections are to be held in 1990.
</TEXT>
