<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Irish 1stLd-Writethru a0750 08-02 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0750,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Warns Civilians; Kills Two, Injures 25</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd pvs to include reference to IRA's
botched attacks in past 8 months. PICKS up 3rd graf pvs bgng, What
apparently ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRA staged a bomb attack,
land mining and killing of a part-time trooper Tuesday and warned
civilians to avoid British soldiers. A policeman also was killed
and 25 people were wounded.
   The attacks came a day after an explosion killed a soldier and
wounded nine at an army postal sorting center in Mill Hill, a
London suburb.
   The IRA's close concentration on security targets followed a
series of botched and mistaken IRA operations since last November
that killed 17 civilians and damaged the guerrilla organization's
image.
   What apparently was a land mine blew up a military vehicle in
County Tyrone, wounding six part-time soldiers; a bomb exploded
under a car in Lisburn, killing a policeman and wounding 18 people,
and a gunman killed a part-time soldier in front of his wife and
baby daughter in Belfast, police said.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility for all four
attacks. The almost exclusively Roman Catholic guerrilla group is
fighting to drive the British from the Protestant-dominated
province and united it with the Irish Republic.
   An IRA statement issued in Dublin, capital of the predominantly
Catholic republic, told civilians to stay away from British
military installations in Britain and Europe, and to avoid bars and
discotheques patronized by off-duty servicemen.
   ``The close presence of civilians often forces us to abandon
operations,'' the statement said. ``No one should travel close to
or with clearly identified members of the British forces.''
   Tom King, Britain's top official for Northern Ireland, said the
IRA message was ``vile and offensive.''
   ``It really is a matter of the IRA trying to give the impression
to the public that they are somehow in control of the situation,''
said Ken McGuinness, security spokesman for the Protestant Ulster
Unionist Party.
   McGuinness also told Britain's Channel 4 News, however, that the
IRA had ``given an answer'' to King's assertion last week that
British security forces were on the way to defeating the IRA.
   Police said a three-pound bomb exploded about 3:40 p.m. Tuesday
under the car of an off-duty policeman in Lisburn, killing the
officer and scattering flames and debris.
   At least 18 passersby were treated for minor injuries, police
said.
   About 20 minutes later a gunman accosted part-time soldier Roy
Butler, 26, in a shoe store in Catholic west Belfast, dragged him
outside and shot him dead in front of his wife and 2-year-old
daughter, police said. A stray bullet hit a woman bystander in the
foot and the assailant escaped in a waiting car, police reported.
   Earlier Tuesday, the military vehicle was heavily damaged by the
explosion on a road near Carland in County Tyrone. IRA guerrillas
opened fire with automatic weapons as the part-time soldiers tried
to escape on foot.
   Police said other soldiers returned the fire and the gunmen fled
across open fields. Six soldiers were treated for wounds, most of
them minor, they reported.
   Forensic experts used a hydraulic platform to help sift through
rubble at the Inglis army barracks at Mill Hill, trying to
establish the cause of Monday's explosion.
   Defense Ministry officials refused comment on reports that
security was so lax at the barracks that the perimeter fence was
riddled with holes and broken traffic barriers were unrepaired
after two months.
   ``Investigations are still very much going on,'' a ministry
spokesman said. ``Naturally, after an event like that we would be
looking very closely at our security. If there are lessons to be
learned, they will be applied.''
   Officials have ordered a security review of all military bases
in Britain.
   The explosion at Inglis was the first fatal attack in mainland
Britain since IRA guerrillas bombed Mrs. Thatcher's hotel during a
political convention in October 1984. She escaped injury but five
other people were killed.
   It was the fifth IRA attack since May on British military
targets outside Northern Ireland. Three servicemen were killed and
12 people wounded in four machine gun and bombing attacks in West
Germany and the Netherlands.
   On March 6, British commandos shot and killed three unarmed IRA
guerrillas in Gibraltar.
</TEXT>
