<1ST_LINE>r w AM-S&LCrisis 1stLd-Writethru a0749 08-02 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Crisis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Urges Against Federal Bailout for S&Ls</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS last graf pvs, In an, to clarify Wall's position on
issue</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Reagan administration official
Tuesday urged Congress to reject calls by savings and loan
executives for a taxpayer bailout of their industry.
   ``From the administration's perspective, it is unnecessary to
transfer resources from the American taxpayer,'' said George D.
Gould, under secretary of the treasury for finance.
   However, others, including the chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, William Proxmire, D-Wis., said the problem has grown so
large that healthy S&Ls can't alone assume the burden of restoring
the rest of the business to solvency.
   ``We are in a big, black bottomless pit,'' said Herbert M.
Sandler, chairman of World Savings and Loan Association in Oakland,
Calif.
   ``It looks like there is virtually no way we can avoid some sort
of hit on the Treasury,'' Proxmire said.
   Gould, the No. 3 official at Treasury and the administration's
chief policymaker on banking and financial issues, urged senators
not to be spooked into hasty and drastic action by exaggerated
estimates of the problem facing the savings industry, where 500 of
3,100 institutions are considered insolvent.
   Some private analysts have said it will take as much as $100
billion to restore the industry to health, but Gould dismissed
those estimates as out of line. He suggested that $30 billion, the
estimate of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board and Congress' General
Accounting Office, ``is not a bad number.''
   However, Gould conceded that $50 billion was not out of the
question, particularly if the oil-dependent economy in Texas, where
many of the insolvent S&Ls are located, doesn't begin recovering.
   Whatever the size of the problem, Congress should turn to
taxpayer money only after ``we ... exhaust all other available
resources,'' he said.
   He suggested that, first, Congress could expand the
industry-financed recapitalization of the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., which began last summer.
   Savings institutions are charged an extra assessment to pay off
$10.8 billion in borrowing for FSLIC over three years. The
administration originally urged that the industry be tapped for $15
billion.
   Gould was backed by Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, the ranking
Republican on the committee, who said, ``I'm not going to ask the
taxpayers of this country to bail out fraud, mismanagement and
abuse of managerial powers'' by S&Ls.
   Pressed by senators to recommend action for Congress this year,
Gould advised only that they pass legislation forming a blue ribbon
commission to study the problem and report back next spring.
   The Senate Banking Committee endorsed such legislation last week
and a House Banking oversight subcommittee on Tuesday urged its
passage. However, the full House Banking Committee already voted
32-19 last week against attaching it to an unrelated banking bill.
   The committee chairman, Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
complained that the commission as proposed by Rep. Stan Parris,
R-Va., would be too heavily weighted with appointees of President
Reagan, a lame duck.
   Proxmire said he would propose bills to restrict insolvent S&Ls
from growing, a tactic critics maintain only compounds their
problems. He also advocated restricting the ability of federally
insured thrift institutions to expand into real estate and other
risky investment areas permitted by some states.
   The top federal S&L regulator, Federal Home Loan Bank Board
Chairman M. Danny Wall, said his agency already limits the growth
of insolvent S&Ls and was stepping up enforcement of the rule.
   In an interview with several reporters after the hearing, he
said he was not opposed to a move by Congress to give the S&L
insurance fund more money by expanding the existing
industry-supported borrowing program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
