<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-02 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Heat Bakes Midwest; Storms Drop Tornado in Minnesota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Midwest baked under record high temperatures Tuesday while
cooler air stretched from the Pacific Northwest to northern
Minnesota.
   Storms peppered the edges of the hot weather area and parts of
the Southeast, with a tornado reported in the Twin Cities area of
Minnesota and thunderstorms dropping up to one inch hail just west
of Akron, Ohio.
   A high pressure system over Ohio scorched the Midwest and is
expected to show little movement, keeping the eastern Midwest hot
and mostly dry. Very high humidity combined with the heat to
produce effective heat values of up to 115 degrees in places.
   Record highs for the date included 102 in La Crosse, Wis., 101
in Alpena, Mich., 98 in Detroit and Milwaukee and 97 in Cleveland
and Madison, Wis. Rockford, Ill., tied a record with 99.
   It was the 35th day this year of temperatures of 90 or higher in
La Crosse, tying a record set in 1955.
   Ahead of the hot air, thunderstorms hit northern Ohio and
northwest Pennsylvania.
   Thunderstorms also were scattered from the Carolinas across the
Gulf Coast states to Texas. A storm generated torrential rain and
40 mph gusts near Pinson, Ala., during the morning.
   In contrast to the Midwest, cooler temperatures in the 60s and
70s stretched from the Pacific Northwest to northern Minnesota.
   There were a few thunderstorms over Minnesota and the Dakotas,
between the cool northern air and the hot Midwest.
   A tornado touched down in an undeveloped area 15 miles southwest
of the Twin Cities in Minnesota and about a half-dozen funnel
clouds were sighted in the area but did not touch ground.
Accompanying storms generated winds up to 60 mph in the area.
   Thunderstorms also developed across portions of the Southwest
from western Colorado across Utah and Arizona to the desert
Southwest.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 55 degrees at Crescent
City, Calif., to 102 degrees at La Crosse, Wis. The overnight low
was 34 degrees at Ketchum, Idaho.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across
the northern border states from eastern Montana to Michigan and
from New York to Maine, with the heaviest rain in North Dakota and
northern New England. Afternoon showers and thunderstorms also were
expected over the Rockies and the southern Plateau region,
particularly the central Rockies and Arizona mountains. Scattered
showers and thunderstorms were forecast to stretch from Texas
across the lower Mississippi Vally to Tennessee, Georgia and
Florida.
   Most of the nation was forecast to have highs in the 90s. Highs
were predicted to be in the 70s along the Pacific Coast and from
the Pacific Northwest to Montana; in the 80s over parts of the
Plateau and the southern Rockies, from North Dakota to northern
Michigan, and over parts of Maine; around 100 degrees from the
central Plains and middle Mississippi valley to the upper Ohio
Valley and southern Michigan; and to between 100 and 110 degrees
across the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
