<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AstronomyMeeting     08-02 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Astronomy Meeting,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Astronomical Union Meets In Baltimore</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT category code</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five years ago, members of the International
Astronomical Union decided to hold their 1988 general assembly in
Baltimore, expecting to see exciting new data from a spaceborne,
$1.5 billion Hubble telescope.
   More than 1,500 astronomers from around the world gathered here
Tuesday for the 20th union assembly, but the Hubble, touted as the
most powerful space telescope ever built, is still sitting on Earth.
   The 1986 Challenger accident grounded the shuttle fleet,
stranding the Hubble and leaving the Space Telescope Science
Institute here with no new data for the IAU delegates.
   ``It was to be the centerpiece of the meeting,'' said Lisa
Hooker, a spokeswoman for Johns Hopkins University, which is host
for the assembly. ``They expected to have their first views ready
by now.''
   The Hubble is scheduled for launch next year.
   Even without the new space telescope views of the heavens,
astronomers attending the first IAU meeting in the United States
since 1961 expect to have lots to talk about.
   Since the last IAU assembly three years ago in India,
astronomers have conducted the first modern investigation of a
visible supernova and studied the latest sighting of Halley's comet.
   A number of papers are expected on studies of Supernova 1987A,
the first exploding star visible in 400 years. Researchers from a
number of countries are expected to report on their results of
studies of Halley's comet, still visible to powerful telescopes
following its retreat from the sun.
   A Soviet astronomer will report on a robot spacecraft launched
recently toward Phobos, a moon of Mars. There will be reports on
observations of a variety of objects, from quasars to pulsars and
cosmic dust.
   The meeting is to end on Aug. 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
