<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Disease     08-02 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Disease,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Epidemic Death Toll Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least eight people died of cholera or
gastroenteritis in New Delhi on Tuesday, raising the death toll
since the beginning of July to 223 people, a city health official
said.
   The official said the deaths were reported from hospitals, where
more than 5,000 people suffering from the diseases have sought
admission.
   At least 223 people have died in the epidemic, which broke out
last month, said the city health official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   Most of the victims have been children.
   The official said more than 19,800 cases of cholera and
gastroenteritis, contracted from contaminated drinking water, have
been reported in New Delhi, a city of 8 million.
   The diseases have broken out in slums where wells were
contaminated by rainwater flowing through sewers and uncollected
garbage.
   Garbage had not been collected in some slum areas for the past
three months because of a dispute over which municipal agencies are
responsible.
   Cases of the two diseases have also been reported in other parts
of India. At least 630 deaths have been reported in the states of
Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, Karnataka, Punjab and Gujarat.
   The diseases broke out after the annual southwest monsoon hit
India and the rains contaminated drinking water supplies.
</TEXT>
