<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Economy,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Vietnam Radio Says Foreign Companies Investing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve foreign companies have invested
in Vietnam this year, and calls are increasing for countries to end
policies of isolating that communist country, an official Voice of
Vietnam radio broadcast said.
   The broadcast said Monday that 20 foreign companies expressed
interest in a liberal investment code promulgated in January, and
that 12 companies have invested in areas including banking,
tourism, electronics and aquatic products.
   A text of the broadcast was obtained Tuesday from a Western
embassy in Bangkok.
   The radio said Vietnam also signed contracts with companies from
India, Belgium and Holland involving oil and gas surveys and
exploitation.
   ``We should recall an old proverb which goes: `It is the early
bird that catches the worm,''' the broadcast said.
   It said recent progress on resolving the Cambodian issue,
including the withdrawal of many Vietnamese troops, made it
possible for countries to end their isolation of Vietnam.
   A Thai newspaper, The Nation, has called for improving relations
and lifting a ban on rice sales to Vietnam, the broadcast said. It
quoted The Boston Globe newspaper as urging establishment of U.S.
diplomatic relations with Vietnam.
   Thailand and the United States back guerrillas fighting the
9{-year-old Vietnamese occupation of Cambodia.
</TEXT>
