<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JapaneseEducation     08-02 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japanese Education,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University To Open 1st Secondary School For Japanese Children in
U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SHARP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first fully accredited Japanese
secondary school in the United States will open next spring at an
old military academy in east Tennessee farm country, officials said
Tuesday.
   Hiroshi Jo, managing director of Meiji Gakuin University, said
the boarding school will make it possible for Japanese children to
get the education necessary for admittance to Japanese universities
without staying in Japan.
   Many Japanese who come to work in one of the 650 Japanese
companies in the United States now leave their families behind, Jo
said, so as not to disrupt the children's education.
   He said Japanese workers in America ``want to know they can send
their children to a school without anxiety, and know they have a
chance for higher education in Japan.''
   Officials said Tuesday that Meiji Gakuin agreed to pay $2.5
million to Sanford Gray, owner of TMI Academy in Sweetwater, for
the grounds where the new school will be located.
   TMI Academy opened 114 years ago as a military school for boys,
and later became a co-educational private school. It went up for
sale early this year.
   Gray said the purchase includes the 45-acre campus and its 12
buildings, as well as an adjacent 100-acre horse farm.
   Jo said the new school will be called Tennessee Meiji Gakuin
(TMG) Academy and plans call for it to open in April 1989 with
about 70 high school sophomores.
   The curriculum will be expanded to include junior high and high
school grades in coming years, he said, with an eventual goal of
about 200 students.
   Jo said the number of Japanese employees in Tennessee was part
of the reason Sweetwater was chosen, but that Japanese children
could come from anywhere in the United States.
   Jo and Meiji Gakuin Chancellor Nobumichi Hiraide both visited
the TMI Academy campus and toured the region, Jo said. They visited
with executives of the several Japanese companies with facilities
in east and middle Tennessee, and found widespread support for such
a school, Jo said.
   ``The children often become the victims'' in the increasing
Japanese investment in the United States, Jo said, adding there are
schools for Japanese children in Europe.
   ``With the support of the Japanese Ministry of Education, we
decided we must have on in America, too,'' he said.
   Gov. Ned McWherter said the school ``will help strengthen the
close ties of culture, commerce and friendship that already exist
between Japan and Tennessee.''
   The largest Japanese employer in Tennessee is the Nissan truck
plant in Smyrna, south of Nashville. Japanese companies in East
Tennessee include ACOM, which makes Panasonic electric components
in Knoxville; Sharp; Matsushita; and Komatsu. Nippondenso recently
announced it would build a $200 million manufacturing plant in
nearby Maryville.
   Meiji Gakuin University has campuses in Shirokanedai, Higashi
Murayama and Totsuka, Yokohama. It is a Christian school founded in
1859 by a Presbyterian missionary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
