<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GermanyHostage     08-02 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany Hostage,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Ransom Was Paid for German Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The news magazine Stern on Tuesday
quoted Syria's defense minister as saying a ransom of $9.7 million
was paid last year to win the release of a West German businessman
kidnapped in Lebanon.
   It reported Defense Minister Mustafa Tlass as saying, ``The
ransom for Siemens technician Alfred Schmidt amounted to 18 million
marks.''
   But the West German government and a spokesman for Schmidt's
employer, the Siemens electronics firm, repeated their denials that
either had paid a ransom.
   ``The federal government has neither paid nor offered any ransom
money in the case of German hostages held in Lebanon and also does
not intend on doing that in the future,'' said government spokesman
Norbert Schaefer.
   Schmidt was released last September and at that time Siemens
said it had not paid a ransom.
   Horst Siebert, a spokesman for the Munich-based company, told
The Associated Press Tuesday, ``We have not changed our previous
statements.''
   The report in Stern did not say who provided the money or who
received it.
   Schmidt and West German businessman Rufolf Cordes were kidnapped
separately in January 1987 by Shiite Moslem extremists. When
Schmidt was released his captors said they freed him as a
``goodwill gesture.''
   Cordes is among 18 foreigners, including nine Americans, still
held hostage in Lebanon. Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for AP, has been held the longest. He was kidnapped
in Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Stern also quoted Tlass as saying that a West German-approved
``trade'' for Cordes collapsed following ``intervention by the U.S.
government.''
   He apparently referred to a possible exchange involving Cordes
and Mohammed Hamadi and his older brother Abbas Hamadi, who are
imprisoned in West Germany.
   Schaefer said the government never considered such an exchange.
   Mohammed Hamadi is on trial in Frankfurt charged with air piracy
and murder in the June 1985 hijacking of a Trans World Airlines
jetliner to Beirut. A U.S. Navy diver was killed by the hijackers.
   Abbas Hamadi was convicted by a Duesseldorf court in April of
kidnapping Schmidt and Cordes in an effort to force West Germany to
free his brother. Abbas Hamadi was sentenced to 13 years in prison.
   West Germany refused a U.S. extradition request for Mohammed
Hamadi.
   A government official testified at Abbas Hamadi's trial that
fears for Corde's safety played was in important factor in turning
down the U.S. request.
   Schaefer said of the Stern account: ``If the Syrian defense
minister really said what Stern has quoted him as saying, then he
is relying on false information.''
   After Schmidt was freed West Germany said Syria helped gain his
release.
   Hamburg-based Stern made its report available to other news
organizations in advance of Thursday's publication.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
