<HEAD>Demonstrators Protest Shortages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police used tear gas to scatter
demonstrators who took to Khartoum's streets for a third straight
night Tuesday to protest flood-induced shortages of power, water,
bread and public transportation.
   Witnesses said the rioters burned tires on the main streets of
Khartoum, Omdurman, and Khartoum North, the three sections of this
Sudanese capital.
   Khartoum is suffering acute shortgages of electric power and
potable water resulting from the seasonal flood of the Blue Nile.
   Power turbines at Erroseiris dam and water treatment stations
were knocked out of action by huge amounts of silt carried by the
floods. Bakeries using electricity were affected.
   Torrential rains meanwhile brought public transport to a
near-halt.
   The state-owned Sudan News Agency said rains washed away
thousands of mud huts. Relief officials said canvas was being
distrubuted for use as shelter by those who lost their homes.
