<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0765,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Says Shultz Visit Shows Support for Argentine
Democracy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-13 UPDATE with comment from Shultz, anti-U.S.
protest. Picks up 8th graf pvs, On Thursday ... with minor editing
to conform</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphoto BAI-2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Dante Caputo
said Tuesday that Secretary of State George P. Shultz's visit to
Argentina underscores U.S. support for this South American nation's
return to democracy.
   Caputo told Shultz in a welcoming toast, ``We Argentines have
not forgotten the deep support received from you those times a few
tried to threaten Argentine democracy.''
   Shultz said in a return toast at the Foreign Ministry:
   ``The people of the Argentine republic have overcome great
difficulties in returning their nation to the democratic fold ...
and in establishing a social peace based on consensus and mutual
respect.
   ``For those who have followed your history, Argentina's
political achievements over the past five years are fully worthy of
the nation which gave birth to the liberator, (Jose de) San
Martin.''
   Elected President Raul Alfonsin took office in December 1983,
ending nearly eight years of military rule.
   Shultz arrived Tuesday from Guatemala, where he failed to obtain
a condemnation of Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
Instead, Shultz and the foreign ministers of Honduras, El Salvador,
Costa Rica and Guatemala issued a declaration calling for ``peace,
democracy, security, social justice and economic development'' in
Central America. The word-softening reportedly came at the
insistence of Costa Rica and Guatemala.
   Caputo's mention of threats to Argentina's democracy referred to
two challenges to Alfonsin's government during the past 15 months
by factions in the armed forces. The Reagan administration on both
occasions publicly expressed its strong support for the government,
which brought the incidents under control.
   After lunch with Caputo, Shultz met separately with Alfonsin,
Economy Minister Juan Sourrouille and Carlos Menem, presidential
candidate of the opposition Peronist Party.
   Sourrouille outlined the economic reforms his government is
putting together in an attempt to reduce the budget deficit and
curtail triple digit inflation, a spokesman for the U.S. State
Department said, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
   Shultz is scheduled to meet Wednesday with Defense Minister
Horacio Juanarena and the governing Radical Civic Union's candidate
for next year's presidential election, Eduardo Angeloz.
   About 8,000 leftists marched downtown near Government House
Tuesday evening to protest the Shultz visit. No incidents were
reported.
   On Thursday, Shultz will travel to Uruguay, the third stop on
his 10-day, nine-country Latin America tour, and meet President
Julio Sanguinetti.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said Shultz's visit to Argentina was
mainly symbolic. ``It's a way to pay attention to, and show respect
for, their (the Argentines') problems,'' he said.
   The spokesman also said Shultz did not bring any new debt
repayment proposals or offers of financial assistance.
   Argentina has a foreign debt of $53 billion and currently is
paying only the interest and nothing on the principal. Alfonsin is
under pressure from his political rivals to get the country out
from underneath the debt burden.
   Menem, chosen as the presidential candidate of the opposition
Peronists in a party election last month, has suggested that
Argentina ask its creditors for a five-year grace period during
which ``not a single dollar would leave Argentina.''
   In Managua, Nicaragua, the official Sandinista newspaper
Barricada said Shultz had failed to persuade Washington's Central
American allies to condemn Nicaragua but U.S. pressure would
continue.
   It said the one-day visit to Guatemala by Shultz ``means a new
level of North American pressure and blackmail aimed at blocking
the Central American peace process again.'' That referred to the
regional peace plan signed by the presidents of the five Central
American countries at a meeting in Guatemala Aug. 7, 1987.
   The United States, which supports Nicaraguan rebels known as
Contras in their fight to overthrow the government, claims the
Sandinistas have not complied with provisions of the plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
