<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Submarine,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Submarine In Collision Turned Later Than Admitted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese submarine that collided with a sport
fishing boat in Tokyo Bay last month, killing 30 people aboard the
boat, tried to veer out of the way much later than its captain
testified, a news report said Tuesday.
   Kyodo News Service quoted unidentified officials of the Maritime
Safety Agency as saying the submarine began turning when it was
about 650 feet from the No. 1 Fujimaru, a charter fishing boat.
   Keisuke Yamashita, captain of the Self-Defense Force submarine
Nadashio, told investigators the submarine began turning when it
was slightly less than 2,000 to about 2,230 feet from the fishing
boat, Kyodo said.
   The two vessels collided at the mouth of Tokyo Bay on July 23,
sending the No. 1 Fujimaru to the seabed in less than two minutes
with most of its 48 passengers and crew. Eighteen people survived.
The submarine reported no casualties.
   Witnesses have said the Nadashio was proceeding recklessly fast
in a busy sea lane and was distracted by a yacht approaching from
the other side, and that its crew was slow in pulling victims from
the water.
</TEXT>
