<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Bing     08-02 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Bing,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lady Bing Hospitalized in Psychiatric Ward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lady Carroll Douglass Bing, wife of former
Metropolitan Opera impresario Sir Rudolf Bing, has been
hospitalized in a psychiatric ward for the past two weeks, her
lawyer said Tuesday.
   ``She's at St. Luke's,'' said lawyer Harvey Sladkus, referring
to a private hospital in Manhattan.
   He said police took her to the hospital July 17 and she was
admitted after ``an incident involving some friends of hers. What
the incident was, I don't know.''
   ``She's an emotionally fragile lady,'' Sladkus said. He blamed
her current instability on attempts by Bing's lawyers to annul her
marriage.
   The Bings were married in January 1987 in Maclean, Va. Bing's
lawyers are trying to get the marriage annulled on the ground that
the 86-year-old former opera general manager, who has Alzheimer's
disease, did not know what he was doing.
   On May 9, state Supreme Court Justice Carmen Ciparick ordered a
psychiatric examination of Lady Bing at her lawyer's request
because of her apparent inability to follow the court's directions.
   That same day the judge ordered Lady Bing, 48, to leave her
husband's Essex House apartment for six specific hours each day so
nurses could attend to Bing.
   ``My client has lost touch with reality,'' Sladkus told the
judge.
   Sladkus said he was told of Lady Bing's hospitalization by her
sister, Dianne, who called from her home in Washington, D.C. He
said he has no idea how long she will stay at St. Luke's. ``That's
a medical determination,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Sladkus said, he has asked that the judge stay all
annulment proceedings until doctors say Lady Bing is able to defend
herself. He said the judge scheduled further proceedings in the
case for Aug. 10.
</TEXT>
