<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimariesRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0825 08-02 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0825,0860</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Dunn ahead in Michigan GOP Senate race, Kansas results,
CORRECTS wording of Detroit measure below the dash, to explain it
is not advisory.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri Democrats nominated Betty Hearnes, wife of a former
governor, for the state's top job Tuesday, and endorsed Rep.
Richard Gephardt's last-minute bid for a seventh term in Congress.
   Detroit voters appeared to be endorsing a ban on casino
gambling, while former congressman Jim Dunn jumped ahead of a
fellow Michigan millionaire in a Republican primary for the right
to challenge Democratic Sen. Donald Riegle.
   Gambling was on the ballot also in Missouri, where voters were
favoring a measure to raise the limit on the lottery jackpot.
   With 7 percent of the Missouri vote counted, Mrs. Hearnes, who
would be the state's first woman governor, had 25,410 votes or 85
percent and Lavoy ``Zaki'' Reed, a St. Louis area teacher, had
4,574 votes or 15 percent.
   ``It's a big step. You've got to cross this hurdle and then go
for the next one,'' Mrs. Hearnes said early in the day. Republican
Gov. John Ashcroft, seeking a second term, did not face a primary.
   Gephardt, who abandoned his bid for the presidential nomination
just in time to file for re-election, piled up 82 percent of the
vote against three little-known Democrats.
   In another Missouri congressional race, farm activist Wayne
Cryts also swamped three opponents for the Democratic nomination,
setting up a rematch with Republican Rep. Bill Emerson.
   Detroit voters were declaring for the third time in 12 years how
they felt about Mayor Coleman Young's plan to improve the economy
with hotel-casinos, and before the first votes were tallied exit
polls conducted for WXYZ-TV and the Detroit Free Press said voters
favored a ban by 60 percent to 40 percent.
   The Missouri amendment to let lottery officials use a higher
percentage of sales for prize money and advertising was ahead 3,832
votes or 55 percent to 3,097 or 45 percent with 1 percent of
precincts counted.
   In Michigan, Dunn and Robert Huber _ also a former one-term
congressman _ competed for a chance to face Riegle, who had no
primary opposition in his bid for a third term. With 4 percent of
the precincts reporting, Dunn had 9,227 votes or 62 percent to
Huber's 5,581 votes or 38 percent.
   Kansas also had primaries. The only congressional incumbent
facing a challenge, GOP Rep. Jan Meyers, tallied 85 percent of the
vote in the 3rd District to overwhelm Charles B. ``Bat'' Masterson,
73, a retired school adminstrator.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Detroit's referendum on casino gambling generated the most heat
of any issue in Michigan. Young, who is expected to seek
re-election next year, said casinos could bring desperately needed
money into the city and help lower its 9.6 percent unemployment
rate. His position pitted him against the ministers and church
members who in the past have formed the core of his constituency.
   Voters previously rejected the idea of casinos in 1976 and 1982.
   The current measure was designed to put a law on the books that
would ban casinos from Detroit even should the Legislature someday
legalize gambling in the state.
   Huber, who was in Congress in 1973-74, and Dunn, who served from
1981-82, had little success in winning financial support, and each
spent more than $200,000 of his own money. By contrast, Riegle, who
has not lost an election in 22 years, has a $4 million warchest for
the fall.
   Dunn, 44, who ran unsuccessfully for a Senate nomination 1984,
had the support of most party officials this time.
   Huber, 65, the more conservative of the two, emphasized his
opposition to abortion and sought support from the partisans
brought into the party by Pat Robertson's presidential campaign.
   Dunn said in a radio interview last week that his opponent
regarded AIDS as God's punishment of homosexuals and drug users.
Huber, asked about Dunn's remarks, said ``I don't know whether it's
the wrath of God, but if it isn't it should be.''
   Supporters of the Missouri lottery amendment called it crucial
to the future of the 2{-year-old games. Currently the lottery is
required to give 45 percent in prizes, 45 percent to the state and
spend 10 percent on administrative costs. The change would require
only that a minimum of 45 percent go for prizes, and officials say
they want give about 50 percent in prizes.
   ``The issue is not to give the Missouri Lottery more than any
other state, but rather to put it on the same playing field as
neighboring lotteries,'' said Mike Morris, executive director of
the lottery.
   Mrs. Hearnes, 61, is a state representative whose husband,
Warren, was governor from 1965-73.
   Cryts, who nearly beat Emerson in the 8th District race in 1986,
was catapulted to fame in 1981 when he took his family's soybeans
from a padlocked grain elevator.
   Missouri will have a Senate race on the ballot in November, but
neither Democratic state Sen. Jay Nixon nor Republican Sen. John
Danforth had any primary opposition.
</TEXT>
