<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Newspaper     08-02 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Newspaper,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Censor Closes Paper, Then Cancels Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military censor on Tuesday ordered the
Israeli afternoon tabloid Hadashot closed for a week for violating
censorship, but canceled the order hours later when newspaper
officials apologized.
   Hadashot violated censorship regulations intentionally after
receiving recent warnings about previous offenses, the army said in
a statement.
   At issue was an article outlining new appointments expected to
be made by army Chief of Staff Brig. Gen. Dan Shomron. Hadashot did
not submit it to the censor before publishing it Tuesday.
   Under censorship regulations, all stories relating to security
matters must be submitted to the military censor.
   Hadashot's news editor, Danny Dor, complained before the closure
order was canceled that Hadashot was being singled out.
   ``The rules are not applied equally,'' Dor said. ``When other
newsapers publish articles without going to the censor, nothing
happens to them.''
   Hadashot, with a circulation of 50,000, was founded in March
1984. A month later, it was closed for four days for violating
censorship.
   The military censor has rarely closed down Israeli newspapers,
but repeatedly applied such measures against Palestinian
publications in Arab east Jerusalem.
</TEXT>
