<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-INSSubpoenas     08-02 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-INS Subpoenas,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Bars Blanket Order for Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officers cannot order housing
or labor camps to turn over their records of tenants to see if any
are in the United States illegally, a federal appeals court ruled
Tuesday.
   In a case from southeast Washington, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals said federal law does not authorize the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to issue ``John Doe'' subpoenas _ those that
do not name a specific individual _ for records of suspected
undocumented aliens.
   Lawyers for managers and residents of the Walla Walla Labor
Camp, which resisted a subpoena for records of about 150 families
in 1984, said the tactic was a departure from INS practices of over
30 years.
   ``We felt it was a dangerous precedent as well as being a
tremendous invasion of privacy,'' said Dan Clark, a lawyer for the
residents' tenant council. ``It's a way of getting into personal
records and doing an investigation of a whole class or group of
people without any individualized suspicion or cause to justify
it.''
   ``They were basically going on a fishing expedition,'' said
Rebecca Smith, a lawyer for the tenants. ``Several times in the
past, the INS has contended its authority is broader than a number
of police agencies. This ruling shows that it's not, and that farm
workers have the same rights as other citizens.''
   Justice Department lawyer Ellen Shapiro, who represented the
INS, did not immediately return a phone call late Tuesday.
   The federally funded labor camp, operated by the Walla Walla
Housing Authority, houses mostly Hispanics. The head of each
household must document legal residence, and lawyers for the
tenants said an inspection by the U.S. Farmers Home Administration
shortly before the case arose had found no violations.
   The INS subpoena was issued by an agent who said he had arrested
about 300 illegal aliens at the camp in 11 years, 19 in 1984, and
was continuing to receive complaints about undocumented aliens who
were receiving housing benefits illegally.
   The records, sought for an unspecified ``criminal
investigation,'' covered U.S. residency, income, welfare status,
vehicles and prior tenancy of all residents of the camp.
   After the camp manager refused to turn over the records on
privacy grounds, U.S. District Judge Robert McNichols ruled in
March 1986 that the subpoena was legal. He noted that the Internal
Revenue Setvice can issue subpoenas for unnamed persons if it has a
reasonable basis to believe they are violating the tax laws, and
said the INS had equal authority.
   But the appeals court ruled 3-0 that the IRS authority was based
on express provisions of federal law that do not exist for the
immigration agency.
   ``Despite the INS's concededly broad subpoena and investigatory
authority, we are reluctant to assume the existence of the power to
issue third-party subpoenas directed at unspecified targets where
Congress has not provided for them specifically, nor provided
procedural safeguards,'' said the opinion by Judge Robert Beezer.
   Because the court concluded that the subpoena was unauthorized
by law, Beezer said, it was not necessary to decide whether it also
violated the constitutional right to privacy, as argued by lawyers
for the tenants and the American Civil Liberties Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CullenDavis     08-02 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cullen Davis,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group, Former Juror Call For Reindictment of Davis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE COCHRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juror in the wrongful death civil
trial of Cullen Davis and a victims' rights group Tuesday demanded
that the bankrupt oil heir be retried for a 1976 shooting spree at
his remote Fort Worth mansion that left two dead and one crippled.
   Condemning Davis as a ``cold blooded killer,'' a group called
the Alliance for Justice urged Tarrant County District Attorney Tim
Curry to reopen the 12-year-old criminal case against Davis. He has
been acquitted in two criminal trials.
   ``The evidence proved beyond a reasonable doubt that it was
Cullen Davis who killed those people,'' said Kenneth Pool, 29, the
jury foreman in a 1987 wrongful death civil trial that ended with a
hung jury.
   ``Cullen Davis got away with murder ...,'' Pool said. ``With
God's help, justice can be done.''
   District Attorney Curry said Davis cannot be prosecuted again
because the ``double jeopardy provision of the U.S. Constitution
prohibits us from any further prosecution of these cases.''
   But Alliance for Justice members noted that Davis was tried and
acquitted for murder of only one of the two victims of the 1976
shooting. They want him tried for the other murder.
   Davis, a born-again Christian, could not be reached for comment
but his attorney, Steve Sumner of Dallas, accused the group of
``tasteless, grandstand tactics'' designed to gain leverage in
civil suits still pending against his client.
   The accusations against Davis, 55, stem from an Aug. 2, 1976,
episode in which a man dressed in black and wearing a wig invaded
the $6 million Davis mansion and shot four persons, including
Davis' ex-wife Priscilla.
   Mrs. Davis, now 47, survived a gunshot wound in the chest but
her boyfriend, Stan Farr, 30, and her daughter, Andrea Wilborn, 12,
were killed.
   A mansion visitor, Gus ``Bubba'' Gavrel, then 22, was crippled
by a bullet that lodged near his spine.
   An Amarillo jury in 1977 acquitted Davis of killing his
stepdaughter, despite the testimony of three survivors who blamed
him for the murder.
   Less than a year later, Davis was arrested and accused of
masterminding a separate murder-for-hire scheme in which he
allegedly targeted for death a divorce judge, his ex-wife and
several Amarillo witnesses.
   A Houston jury deadlocked 8-4 in favor of conviction in the
murder solicitation case, and a Fort Worth jury acquitted him in a
retrial.
   After that acquittal, the district attorney's office dismissed
charges against Davis for the murder of Farr and the attempted
murder of Mrs. Davis and Gavrel.
   In 1986, Davis settled Gus Gavrel's $13 million civil lawsuit
out of court. The settlement wasn't disclosed but has been reported
to be worth about $1 million. A year later, a jury deadlocked 8-4
against Davis in a wrongful death and personal injury suit filed by
Mrs. Davis and her second husband, Jack Wilborn, the father of
Andrea.
   Mrs. Davis said she hasn't decided whether to continue the civil
action.
   Davis later filed for bankuptcy in federal court, leaving in
limbo his ex-wife's civil suit and suits filed by the Farr estate
and his heirs.
   ``I think jurors have been in awe of his money,'' Mrs. Davis
said. ``Maybe now that he's supposed to be broke they won't be as
interested in his wealth and might listen to the truth.''
</TEXT>
