<DOCNO> AP880802-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Vietnamese-Church     08-02 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnamese-Church,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Over Church with Diocese Resolved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Vietnamese-Americans
occupying a Roman Catholic church settled their lawsuit against the
local diocese, agreeing to purchase the building and turn it into a
cultural center.
   The dissidents took over the San Jose property in 1986, when the
Rev. Paul Luu Dinh Duong was appointed pastor of a temporary
mission for Vietnamese-Americans that was housed in the church.
   The protesters refused to accept Duong's authority, and said
they wanted the temporary mission upgraded to a permanent parish
where they can worship in their own language.
   Bishop Pierre DuMaine, who appointed Duong, has refused to back
down from his mission plan and has encouraged the Vietnamese to
attend services throughout the diocese.
   The dissidents sued the San Jose diocese in 1986, claiming that
the building belonged to them. The diocese bought the property for
an undisclosed sum in 1982.
   Under terms of the out-of-court settlement reached late Friday,
the dissidents agreed to pay $400,000 for Our Lady Queen of Martyrs
church. They also promised to remove all signs identifying the
building as a Catholic church or affiliated facility.
   Diocese spokesman Terrence Sullivan said the dissidents planned
to turn the building into a cultural center.
   The protesters plan to continue prayer services, religion and
language classes for children and occasional masses, said Bai An
Tran, leader of the dissidents.
   Bishop DuMaine said the settlement ``removes a major obstacle to
re-opening discussions for a reconciliation in the Catholic
Vietnamese community.''
   There are about 8,000 Catholic Vietnamese-Americans in the San
Jose area, and they appeared about evenly split over the church
dispute.
   If the group cannot raise at least $175,000 over the next 105
days for a down payment on the building, the settlement requires
the dissidents to vacate the property.
</TEXT>
