<DOCNO> AP880802-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ConsentDecree     08-02 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consent Decree,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Find Louisiana Maintains Unlawful University Segregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of three federal judges ruled Tuesday
that Louisiana has allowed ``unlawful'' segregation to persist in
state colleges and universities despite a 1981 agreement to end
racial bias.
   ``Despite the slight increase in black enrollment statewide, the
racial polarization has increased as a whole during the term of the
consent decree,'' said the unanimous opinion by U.S. District Judge
Charles Schwartz Jr.
   The judges acknowledged, however, that part of the problem was
with the consent decree itself, an agreement with the U.S. Justice
Department that called for the state to encourage integration by
spending money to improve black colleges and universities.
   ``If money was the sole problem, then there should still be
improvement, though perhaps an insufficient improvement for
constitutional purposes, in desegregation of Louisiana's public
universities,'' said Schwartz.
   Of Louisiana's 20 institutions of higher education, Schwartz
said, those originally established as ``black'' schools _ Southern
University-Baton Rouge, Southern-New Orleans, Southern-Shreveport,
and Grambling _ remain predominately black.
   ``The court finds, except for Bossier Parish Community College
and the St. Bernard Parish Community College, that Louisiana is
continuing to operate an unlawful, dual system of public higher
education,'' said Schwartz.
   The court said drastic changes may be needed to remedy remaining
vestiges of the former segregated system.
   ``A possible remedy that suggests itself to the court would be
one that reduces the number of senior colleges and many of their
duplicative programs, in particular, the duplication in
institutions in the same vicinity, institutes a system of junior
colleges with open admissions to all high school graduates,
institutes a higher minimum entrance requirements to the remaining
senior colleges, and vests the state supervision over the
institutions to a single board,'' the opinion said.
   John Kennedy, Gov. Buddy Roemer's lawyer in the case, said the
court could order all of those changes, require additional spending
and more.
   ``We need to settle this and do it on an innovative basis.
That's what they're telling us,'' said Mack Barham, an attorney
representing the Board of Regents, which oversees all four of the
state's higher education panels.
   Lawyers for the mostly black Southern University and Grambling
University systems could not be reached for comment immediately.
   Both the U.S. Department of Justice and the state, without
admitting liability, agreed in the consent decree to dismantle the
system of higher education divided by race under state law prior to
1954, when a landmark U.S. Supreme Court outlawed segregation.
   The decree was intended to resolve a 1974 lawsuit filed by the
Justice Department against the state. The agreement was to have
expired Dec. 31, 1987, but the Justice Department extended it
indefinitely at the insistence of lawyers for the Southern and
Grambling systems.
   The court acknowledged that Louisiana has spent more than $200
million on black colleges since 1981. But the judges agreed with
the Justice Department's position that Louisiana's failure to keep
all the promises it made in the consent decree is the chief reason
segregation still exists.
   And, in a concession to an idea that was rejected by the 1988
Legislature, the court said supervision of the state's colleges and
universities perhaps should be the work of a single board, rather
than four separate ones.
   A trial is scheduled for Sept. 22 if negotiations between the
Justice Department and the state don't yield a remedy to the
consent decree. Tuesday's ruling by Schwartz and his colleagues was
part of a move to dispose of all pending motions before the trial
begins.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
