<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ghost Highways,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Miles Of Highways Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missing: 730 miles of Philippine
highways. If found, contact the Philippine Department of Public
Works.
   Public Works Secretary Juanito Ferrer told a House of
Representatives committee on Tuesday that a recent survey found the
government had been paying about $400,000 a year for maintenance of
roads that don't exist.
   Ferrer said corrupt officials were apparently pocketing the
money.
   He said most of the ``ghost highways'' were in the northern
Luzon island stronghold of ousted President Ferdinand Marcos.
Others were in central Luzon, the central Visayas islands and
Mindanao.
   It was the latest in a growing series of charges of corruption
within President Corazon Aquino's government.
   Mrs. Aquino, who took office in February 1986, has pledged to
curb corruption, which was rampant in the Marcos administration.
   But Filipino political commentators and others claim corruption
remains widespread in the government.
</TEXT>
