<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Flood     08-02 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Flood,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Search for More Than 400 Missing in Flood Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods caused by sudden heavy rains left 225
people dead and 449 missing and affected nearly 100,000 residents
of coastal Zhejiang province, China's official Xinhua News Agency
reported Tuesday.
   Downpours from Friday evening through Saturday poured up to 19.6
inches of rain in 12 hours on parts of five hard-hit counties
around Ningbo, a prosperous commercial city on the East China Sea.
   Xinhua said water resources in flood-hit areas were polluted and
drinking water supplies were inadequate.
   An official of the Zhejiang provincial Foreign Affairs Office,
identifying himself only as Huang, said helicopters rescued some
people stranded by floods. He said floodwaters had covered 154,400
acres of farmland. About half the waters now have receded, he said.
   The official China Daily newspaper quoted an unidentified
official of the provincial Flooding and Drought Combating
Department as saying Tuesday that those missing were ``not likely
to survive.''
   He said it was the worst flooding disaster to hit Zhejiang in 40
years, destroying 16,949 homes, 100 reservoirs and 305 bridges. He
put the economic loss at $167 million.
   It was the second storm this summer to pound Zhejiang, one of
China's richest provinces. Torrential rains in late June killed 45.
   At least 750 people have been reported killed in floods ravaging
coastal, southern and northern China this year, while wide areas of
central China are suffering from one of the worst droughts in
memory.
   Searing temperatures in Shanghai, Nanjing and other cities along
the Yangtze River have been linked to more than 500 deaths.
   Rain-swollen rivers led to two boat accidents in Sichuan
province late last month which left 103 dead and at least 100
missing.
</TEXT>
