<1ST_LINE>u p AM-MissouriPrimary 3rdLd-Writethru a0828 08-02 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missouri Primary, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0828,0432</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Lottery wins</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri Democrats on Tuesday gave Betty
Hearnes a chance to return to the governor's mansion _ this time as
chief executive rather than first lady. Voters also approved a
measure to raise the limit on their lottery jackpot.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt easily won the Democratic nomination for a
seventh term in Congress, while farm activist Wayne Cryts earned a
chance for a rematch against Republican Rep. Bill Emerson.
   In the Democratic primary for governor, with 48 percent of the
vote counted, Mrs. Hearnes, who would be the state's first woman
governor, had 201,089 votes or 82 percent and Lavoy ``Zaki'' Reed,
a St. Louis area teacher, had 45,338 votes or 18 percent.
   Republican Gov. John Ashcroft had no primary opposition in his
bid for a second term.
   The lottery measure was ahead by 260,801 votes or 58 percent to
191,294 or 42 percent, with 51 percent of precincts counted.
   Supporters of the amendment called it crucial to the future of
the state's 2{-year-old games. The amendment would remove current
restrictions that now limit how much can be spent on prizes and
adminstrative costs.
   In the 3rd District, Gephardt was piling up 81 percent of the
vote against three lesser-known Democrats who had jumped in during
his run for the presidency. Gephardt filed for re-election after
folding his presidential bid.
   Cryts also swamped three opponents in the 8th District
Democratic primary.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Under current law, the lottery gives 45 percent of proceeds to
prizes, 45 percent to the state and spends 10 percent on
administrative costs. The change would require only that a minimum
of 45 percent go for prizes.
   Ideally, lottery officials want to give about 50 percent in
prizes to make the games more competitive with neighboring states.
Lottery officials say without the changes, the games could fold
next spring when a special reserve fund the lottery has been using
runs dry.
   Most Democratic primaries for statewide posts were lopsided
affairs with one clear favorite, such as the gubernatorial primary
where Mrs. Hearnes, a 61-year-old state House member, was expected
all along to win the right to a November showdown with Ashcroft.
Her husband, Warren, was governor from 1965-73.
   Cryts, who nearly beat Emerson in 1986, gained national
attention in 1981 when he took his family's soybeans from a
padlocked grain elevator.
   Democratic state Sen. Jay Nixon was unopposed in his bid to take
on Republican Sen. John Danforth in November.
</TEXT>
