<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Place, The People, The Parades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some facts and figures on New Orleans, home
of the 1988 Republican National Convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE PLACE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Location: Southeastern Louisiana, surrounded by Mississippi
River, Lake Pontchartrain, Lake Borgne.
   Area: 199 squuare miles.
   Elevation: Ranges from 5 feet below sea level to 15 feet above.
   Flood protection: Levees, pumps, drainage canals.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE PEOPLE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   City population: 555,641.
   Percent black: 55.1 peercent.
   Metro population: 1,257,049.
   Percent black: 32 percent.
   Percent Hispanic: .4 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE CLIMATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Average high temperature, August: 90.3 degrees.
   Average low temperature, August: 75.3 degrees.
   Average rainfall, August: 6.67 inches.
   Average relative humidity: 77 percent.
   Common afternoon heat index: 98-100 degrees.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ECONOMY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment, metro area: 9.4 percent.
   Unemployment, state: 10.5 percent.
   Major industries: petroleum, maritime and aerospace equipment,
food processing, the port, tourism.
   Average per capita income, 1986: $21,988.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FOOD, DRINK AND FUN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Restaurants: 1,314.
   Bars: 666.
   Number of tourists annually: 7.5 million.
   Biggest party: Mardi Gras _ the day before Lent _ attended by 1
million.
   Parades in the city, 1987: 281.
   Parades, 1988 to date: 170.
   Favorite local delicacy: Crawfish (sorry, out of season in
August).
   Favorite local sandwich: Po' boy.
   Best known drink: Pat O'Brien's Hurricane.
   Bottles of Tabasco purchased annually in metro area: 1.2 million.
</TEXT>
