<1ST_LINE>s p BC-ConventionWeather Adv07   08-02 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Convention Weather, Adv 07,0253</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hot, Humid Weather Will Greet The Republicans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to the weather in New Orleans,
city officials have one bit of advice for the thousands attending
the Republican National Convention.
   ``You'd be crazy not to carry an umbrella, for the sun as well
as the rain,'' says Yvonne Gelpi, a member of the city's GOP Host
Committee.
   New Orleans in August means high temperatures about 90.3 degrees
and relative humidity that rarely dives below 50 percent.
   The heat index _ a formula used by the National Weather Service
that combines both heat and humidity _ hovers close to 100.
   Perspiration doesn't evaporate in the damp air and the only
respite from the sticky heat comes in the form of brief
thundershowers that hit almost every day.
   Convention officials plan to use awnings, covered walkways and
air conditioned convention vehicles in an attempt to help those
unaccustomed to such unkind conditions.
   Hurricanes are another summer weather worry, although the storms
are more likely to threaten later in the year.
   Convention manager Bill Philips said the city would have several
days notice should a hurricane or tropical storm form in the Gulf
and head toward the city. He said plans and schedules would have to
be adjusted on a day-to-day basis to ensure convention-goers'
safety.
   But he added, ``I'm more concerned about the humidity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
