<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   08-02 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0475</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency wants the
government to capture the expected windfall corporate profits that
could reach $7 billion during future cuts in production of
chemicals that destroy the Earth's protective ozone layer.
   The EPA disclosed Monday it was considering regulations that
could require manufacturers to pay fees to the government equal to
their extra profits; could require recycling or other controls on
manufacturing processes; or could require companies to buy
manufacturing rights from the government at auctions open to anyone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AGB Television Research is suspending its U.S.
television ratings operation, saying it underestimated the costs of
competing with audience measurement leader A.C. Nielsen.
   The disclosure disappointed some advertising and television
industry executives, who said Monday that AGB had provided some
competition in the national TV ratings arena that has been
dominated for 30 years by Nielsen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NV Philips, the Dutch electronics giant, has
named a new chief executive at North American Philips Corp. and
split off $1 billion worth of peripheral operations into an
independent subsidiary.
   Philips said Monday that the changes, effective Sept. 1, were
intended to ``further integrate the Philips organization in the
U.S.A. into the global activities of the company.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government's Export-Import Bank has
agreed to resume lending to Brazil to encourage sales of U.S. goods
there.
   The action by the bank's board of directors, announced Monday,
follows an agreement reached in Paris over the weekend between
Brazil and 13 creditor governments, including the United States.
This accord will delay repayments on $5 billion worth of debt
falling due between Jan. 1, 1987 and March 31, 1990.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AGOURA HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda's luxury Acura cars ranked
highest in customer satisfaction for the second consecutive year in
a consumer survey that found only two American nameplates in the
top 10.
   The rankings released Monday by J.D. Power and Associates, an
auto industry research group, were based on questionnaires
completed by 25,200 motorists one year after they bought their cars.
   Ranked in order, the top 10 models were Acura, Mercedes-Benz,
Honda, Cadillac, Toyota, Lincoln, BMW, Volvo, and, tied for ninth,
Mazda and Audi.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished mixed Monday. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials inched up 1.78 to close at 2,130.51.
   The dollar fell against most major currencies in U.S. trading
after a mixed performance overseas.
   Bond prices edged up in light dealings.
   Soybean, corn and oat futures prices shot up their permitted
daily limits and wheat futures surged on the Chicago Board of
Trade. On other exchanges, coffee futures plummeted, cattle futures
climbed and pork futures fell sharply.
</TEXT>
