<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-02 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Prices Slightly Lower In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices of crude oil futures contracts have
dipped slightly in advance of Wednesday's scheduled meeting of
OPEC's price monitoring committee.
   The contract for September delivery of West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 23 cents to $16.08 a
barrel Monday on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Prices of some refined products rose slightly because of
short-term supply and demand imbalances, analysts said.
   The September contract for No. 2 heating oil rose .02 cent a
gallon to 45.12 cents and the September contract for unleaded
gasoline rose .32 cent to 48.45 cents a gallon.
   William Byers, an analyst for Bear, Stearns & Co., said the
absence of news about the likelihood of a price accord by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries left traders cautious.
   ``If there's an incentive to do anything, it's to limit
exposure,'' Byers said.
</TEXT>
