<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Gillette-Coniston     08-02 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette-Coniston,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette Settles Coniston Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. has fended off another possible
takeover attempt by settling lawsuits with Coniston Partners
stemming from their bitter proxy fight earlier this year.
   As part of the settlement outlined Monday, Gillette will buy
back an estimated 16 million shares at $45 each, or a total of $720
million.
   The deal also contains a standstill agreement under which
Coniston is barred from buying significant numbers of Gillette
shares, participating in any proxy contest or otherwise seeking
control of the company for three years.
   The settlement ends Coniston's suit over the April 21 proxy vote
it lost to Gillette. As a result, the personal care products giant
does not face a rerun of the election.
   A federal judge said last month he was inclined to order a new
vote _ which many observers thought would favor Coniston _ because
Gillette misled stockholders in an advertisement about Coniston
before the election.
   Under terms of the settlement, all Gillette stockholders may
sell one share back to the company at $45 for each seven they own.
   Gillette officials estimated that 16 million of the company's
112 million outstanding shares likely would be purchased under the
settlement.
   Gillette has relied on standstill agreements and stock buybacks
in the past to fend off unwanted suitors.
   After Revlon Group's failed bid for Gillette in 1986, Gillette
paid $558 million to buy back 9.2 million shares of stock and got
Revlon chairman Ronald O. Perelman to make a similar standstill
agreement.
   In addition, Gillette has reached a series of other standstill
agreements with potential suitors since then. The company's failure
to disclose the agreements during its proxy fight with Coniston was
another issue in its legal dispute with the partnership.
   Edward Froelich, an analyst with Pershing & Co., said Monday
that the latest settlement means Gillette management ``wants to
keep the status quo. But they're shrinking the capital and diluting
earnings a bit.''
   Froelich said the company would be able to continue fighting off
such overtures ``as long as they keep the earnings rising, and they
have. I don't think the stockholders will be too badly off.''
   Gillette stock fell $2.62{ a share to $37.50 in composite
trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Coniston, which owns nearly 6 percent of Gillette's outstanding
shares, waged the proxy battle earlier this year in an effort to
win four directors seats and pressure the 12-member Gillette board
to sell the company. Coniston believes a sale would boost the value
of Gillette stock.
   Gillette filed suit April 14 to block Coniston's proxy bid on
the grounds that Coniston falsified Securities and Exchange
Commission filings and did not fully disclose all its investors.
   Coniston countersued, alleging Gillette misrepresented the
partnership in advertisements and mailings to the company's 27,000
shareholders and failed to publicly disclose all companies that had
expressed interest in buying Gillette.
   U.S. District Court Judge Mark L. Wolf ruled in early April that
Gillette inaccurately portrayed Coniston in newspaper
advertisements leading up to the proxy vote in which shareholders
rejected Coniston's slate of four director candidates.
   Paul Tierney Jr., a Coniston general partner, issued a statement
Monday saying: ``We believe this settlement at this time is in the
best interests of all concerned.''
   Joan Fitzgerald, a spokeswoman for Gillette, maintained that
``all shareholders will benefit'' from the repurchase agreement and
said it was similar to the stock buy-back plan the company began in
1986, prior to Coniston's action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Butcher-Singer     08-02 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Butcher-Singer,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Butcher & Singer Being Sold to Wheat, First Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Butcher & Singer's merger with Wheat, First
Securities of Richmond, Va., will create a financial services
company with brokers in 92 locations from Massachusetts to South
Carolina, officials of the regional brokerage firms say.
   ``I think that everyone is enthusiastic about it because it
makes you much more of a contender when you're this size,'' McBee
Butcher, chairman and chief executive of Butcher & Singer, said of
Monday's merger announcement.
   Complete financial terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   The two firms plan to form WBF Securities Inc., a financial
services and investment banking holding company with two separate
divisions and capital of $56 million, about $15 million of which
will be contributed by Butcher & Singer.
   WBF Securities will be owned by WFS Financial, the
Richmond-based parent of Wheat, First Securities.
   WBF Securities will have about 2,000 employees, including 750
investment brokers. Butcher & Singer has 38 offices from
Massachusetts to Maryland. Wheat, First Securities, established in
1934, has 54 offices from South Carolina to Pennsylvania.
   Butcher, whose privately-held firm has roots dating to the
American Revolution, said the merger will help cut costs and raise
efficiency at Butcher & Singer. He said about 100 of the company's
500 jobs in Philadelphia will be eliminated by the merger.
   Both companies will maintain separate brokerage offices, and all
will remain open, the two parties said. The WBF Securities
headquarters will be in Richmond.
   John L. McElroy Jr., chairman and chief executive of Wheat,
First Securities, will hold the same titles with WBF Securities.
Butcher and other executives from Butcher & Singer will become
officers of WFS Financial.
   Wheat interests will own a majority in the combined companies.
Butcher said Johannes Fuerst von Thurn und Taxis, a West German
prince who last December bought one-third interest in Butcher &
Singer, will be a minority owner in WFS.
   Both parties would like to complete the merger by the end of
September, Butcher said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FirstRepublicBank-Reorganization     08-02 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First RepublicBank-Reorganization,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First RepublicBank Files For Protection From Creditors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Corp., whose subsidiary banks
have been declared insolvent by federal regulators, has filed for
protection from creditors under U.S. bankruptcy laws.
   Federal banking authorities closed the holding company's 40
Texas banks after the close of business Friday and turned them over
to Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB Corp.
   Following that action, First RepublicBank Corp. and IFRB Corp.
its wholly owned subsidiary and intermediate holding company formed
in last year's merger with InterFirst Corp., on Saturday each filed
a voluntary petition for Chapter 11 court protection from creditors.
   First RepublicBank Corp. was left with a single bank in Delaware
and certain subsidiaries engaged in non-banking activities,
according to a prepared release issued Monday.
   ``The bankruptcy filings by the holding companies do not affect
their former banking operations in Texas,'' the statement said.
``First Republic understands that such banking locations will open
for business today as banking offices of a newly chartered bank
named NCNB Texas National Bank.''
   Formerly Texas' largest bank holding company, First RepublicBank
Corp. was declared insolvent by the U.S. comptroller of the
currency. Furthermore, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which
loaned First Republic $1 billion in March, called for repayment of
its note.
   When the flagship bank could not meet the obligation,
authorities took over the bank and its subsidiaries across the
state and the FDIC awarded them to NCNB.
   The petitions, filed in a U.S. bankruptcy court for the Northern
District of Texas, listed estimated assets of $535.7 million and
liabilities of $788.2 million for First RepublicBank.
   IFRB Corp. had estimated assets of $279.2 million and
liabilities of $638.9 million, papers filed with the court said.
   FirstRepublic Bank officials said estimated assets reflected in
the petitions ``may ultimately prove worthless, including certain
intercompany accounts and sums receivable from former subsidiary
banks.''
   Liabilities of the holding companies exclude liability to the
FDIC for repayment of its $1 billion loan to some subsidiary banks
before closure.
   Other First RepublicBank subsidiaries _ First RepublicBank
Delaware, Republic Money Orders Inc. and First RepublicBank
Services Corp. _ will continue in business and serve customers
without interruption, the statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
