<DOCNO> AP880802-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-02 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steadies, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied at lower levels against most
major foreign currencies in thin late-morning trading in Europe
today.
   Traders said the dollar was showing little movement ahead of the
release of U.S. leading indicators for June.
   Gold prices fell.
   Traders said some dollar buying emerged in the mid-morning after
the dollar slid to a European low of 1.8575 West German marks.
   ``The dollar's fall this morning wasn't really justified, but
then again its recent rise has also been exaggerated,'' said one
trader in Milan.
   She said the markets were waiting for the release of the U.S.
leading indicators. The markets were expecting the June index to
rise between 1.1 percent and 1.5 percent, following a 0.1 percent
fall in May.
   However, she said the market probably already discounted a
better figure for June so that there would be little substantial
improvement in the dollar even if a good figure emerged.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7190, stronger
than $1.7130 Monday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8665 West German marks, down from 1.8758; 1.5555
Swiss francs, down from 1.5615; 6.2963 French francs, down from
6.3255; 2.1061 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1145; 1,377.25 Italian
lire, down from 1,381.50; 1.2095 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2075.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.85 yen to a closing 132.40 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 132.65 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $435.25 a troy ounce, up
from late Monday's $433.75. But at mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of
$432.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $434.25, down from $436.50 late
Friday. Zurich was closed Monday for a Swiss national holiday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.56 to close at a bid $436.37.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.80 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $6.81.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
