<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury-Trump,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Acquires 0.4 Percent Stake in Pillsbury, Seeks Bigger
Holding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate developer Donald Trump has acquired
400,000 shares of Pillsbury Co. as an investment and is seeking
federal approval to buy nearly 25 percent of the ailing food giant,
according to news reports.
   Trump's new holding represents 0.4 percent of Pillsbury's
outstanding shares, according to today's editions of the New York
Times. The newspaper quoted the New York-based developer as saying
he paid $15 million for the stake, which he acquired over the last
week.
   The 0.4 percent stake is the maximum Trump was able to buy under
government antitrust regulations.
   Pillsbury has been the subject of lively takeover speculation
recently. Last week, the Minneapolis-based company named Philip L.
Smith, the head of rival General Foods Corp., as its new chairman.
But some analysts were skeptical that Smith would be able to turn
around Pillsbury, especially its Burger King fast-food chain.
   Trump often has acquired large blocks of stock in companies that
later became targets of hostile takeovers, including Gillette Co.
and Federated Department Stores Inc. He is estimated to have netted
$100 million on his investment in Federated, which he made two
weeks before Canadian retailer Campeau Corp. launched a hostile,
and ultimately successful, bid for the company.
   The Times said Trump declined to discuss his plans for the
Pillsbury stock but is not expected to try to take over the
company. ``I think it's got potential,'' he told the paper.
   Trump told the Times he had sent a letter to Pillsbury
management Monday informing the company of his acquisition and
plans to buy more.
   Pillsbury's brands include Green Giant vegetables, Haagen-Dazs
ice cream and Van de Kamp's frozen fish.
</TEXT>
