<DOCNO> AP880802-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Rustproofing     08-02 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rustproofing,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Rustproofing Company Stops Its Warranty Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rusty Jones Inc. says it is scrapping warranties
on the company's car rustproofing products because of competition
from automakers _ a move its rivals predicted could put the firm
out of business.
   Mark Drinan, a vice president of Chicago-based Rusty Jones, said
Monday the company would not issue warranties on cars sold or
treated with rustproofing Aug. 1 or later. The company also
announced it was completely suspending sales in New York because
that state requires warranties on all rustproofing products.
   Drinan acknowledged that ending warranties might force Rusty
Jones out of business altogether because consumers may be unwilling
to buy the product without a warranty.
   Drinan said the company was withdrawing its warranties because
of increased competition since the nation's major automakers
introduced in early 1987 limited, six- or seven-year warranties
against holes caused by rust.
   ``I'm not really excited about the prospects for Rusty Jones
now,'' said William Pochiluk, president of AutoFacts Inc., of
Paoli, Pa., an automotive research and consulting firm.
   ``If I were a dealer, I think I'd have a hard time giving Rusty
Jones away without a warranty, much less trying to sell it,''
Pochiluk said. ``There's going to have to be massive price slashing
to sell the product. The extended rustproof warranties from Detroit
certainly had an effect on Rusty Jones' decision.''
   Officials of Rusty Jones and Beatrice Co., which acquired the
rustproofer in 1984, would make no predictions on the future.
   Asked if the decision to drop the warranties meant Rusty Jones
would go out of business, Michael Mater, president of the Beatrice
subsidiary, said, ``Reviews are taking place, things are being
looked at. I hope it's not the end.''
   Drinan refused to say how much Rusty Jones' sales have decreased
since the automakers started their warranty program.
   He refused to provide the company's 1987 earnings or revenues.
Drinan also would not say how many outlets Rusty Jones has across
the country, although he said its operations were concentrated east
of the Mississippi River and north of the Mason-Dixon line.
   Rusty Jones' warranties covered holes in the auto's body caused
by rust. The length of the warranties varied from several years to
the life of the vehicle, depending on conditions, Drinan said.
   Under a warranty, a customer had the option of receiving the
cost of the repairs or a full refund for Rusty Jones treatment,
Drinan said.
   The automakers also now offer repairs if rust develops, Drinan
said.
   Warranties for treatments done before August 1 will still be
valid, Drinan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 0951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GCC-OPEC     08-02 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GCC-OPEC,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GCC Oil Ministers May Hold Conference in September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil ministers of the six-nation Gulf Cooperation
Council may meet in September to discuss the glut on the world oil
market and the stability of oil prices, the Kuwait news agency
reported.
   Citing unidentified sources, KUNA said Tuesday that the GCC
secretariat is consulting with the oil ministers of the six nations
to finalize an exact date for the meeting at the organization's
headquarters in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.
   The GCC is comprised of four members of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries _ Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates _ along with Bahrain and
Oman.
   The sources said the ministers were keen to find a way to drive
oil prices up to the OPEC benchmark of $18 a barrel. A barrel is
equivalent to 42 gallons.
   KUNA's sources said the GCC ministers were expected to appeal to
the OPEC member states to adhere until the end of the year to the
individual production quotas to absorb the surplus on the world
market and thereby bolster oil prices.
   Oil prices have been running about $3 a barrel below the OPEC
benchmark.
   The sources expect the GCC ministers to warn OPEC that further
increases in oil production ``could push oil prices to further
deterioration if the member states do not adhere to the official
decisions agreed upon.''
   The GCC meeting will await the outcome of the meeting of OPEC's
five-member price-monitoring committee this week, KUNA said. The
committee, comprised of the oil ministers of Saudi Arabia,
Venezuela, Algeria, Indonesia and Nigeria, is scheduled to begin
talks Wednesday in Lausanne, Switzerland.
   The price-monitoring committee is meeting against the background
of a possible end to the 8-year-old war between Iraq and Iran, both
members of OPEC.
   The conflict had been casting shadows on the cartel, with Iraq
currently producing almost double its assigned oil quota and
insisting on having the same quota as Iran. The Iranians have been
widely accused of discounting oil because of the costs of the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
