<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     08-02 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0357</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced early today, mirroring
a rally in the credit market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.83 to 2,138.34 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 9 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 620 issues up, 342
down and 445 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 35.48 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said equities were supported by bond prices, which rose
in reaction to the Commerce Department's monthly report on the
Index of Leading Indicators.
   While the government's chief forecasting gauge of future
economic activity shot up 1.4 percent in June, the biggest increase
in 18 months, investors were more interested in a downward revision
in the May index.
   The May decrease, originally estimated at 0.1 percent, was
revised to a 0.8 percent decrease, which worked to depress fears
that the economy is overheating and that interest rates inevitably
must rise.
   Analysts said the June figure mostly was in line with
expectations.
   The market's early advanced marks the fourth consecutive session
of gains in the Dow average. Still, analysts note that the gains
were posted in thin volume and were restricted to certain issues,
and they therefore remain reluctant to proclaim the stock market's
summer rally back on track.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, IBM was up \ at 126{,
Boeing was up ] at 62}, Gillette was off | at 36~, and Tenneco was
off [ at 48].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.50 to 154.02. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index stood at 306.52, up 0.19.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 1.78 to 2,130.51.
   Gaining issues outnumbered declines by about 11 to 9 on the
NYSE, with 830 up, 672 down and 481 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 138.17 million shares, against 192.34 million shares in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
