<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Argentina-Economy     08-02 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Economy,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility Rates Hiked 30 Percent; More Economic Changes On The Way</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has increased
utility rates by 30 percent as part of its efforts to narrow the
budget deficit and bring triple-digit inflation under control.
   Presidential spokesman Jose Lopez, who announced the increase
late Monday night, said wage and price controls, which were
introduced in 1985 and abandoned last year, were not being
considered.
   More elements of the government's plan, which may include
devaluation, were expected to be disclosed later today.
   Banks and exchange houses remained closed for a second day. Vice
President Victor Martinez, dismissing speculation to the contrary,
said they will reopen as scheduled on Wednesday.
   Financial institutions have been jittery for weeks about the
impending changes. They were ordered closed by the government on
Sunday. Last week, they refused to sell certificates of deposit for
longer than seven days. The interest rate was 19 percent.
   The opposition Peronist Party and the 3-million member General
Labor Confederation complained Monday that they were not consulted
about the changes.
   The agriculture sector, which produces the soy and wheat and
cattle that generate most of Argentina's foreign exchange, bitterly
opposed exchange restrictions that would limit their profits.
   The government reportedly is considering requiring farmers and
ranchers to turn in their dollars at commercial rates that are
lower than the financial exchange rates.
   President Raul Alfonsin spent most of Monday closeted at his
official residence in the suburb Olivos with top advisers.
   Central Bank President Jose Machinea and Treasury Secretary
Mario Brodersohn returned Sunday from Washington, where they
reportedly negotiated a $1.2 billion stand-by loan from the
International Monetary Fund.
   Alfonsin, who took office in December 1983, has been plagued by
economic problems, principally a foreign debt of $53 billion, and
an inflation rate that has risen by 121.2 percent during the past
six months, and by 321.7 percent over the past year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
