<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BraniffCutback     08-02 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Braniff Cutback,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Braniff Cuts Service, Jobs in Orlando</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc.'s short-lived expansion in
Orlando has come to a halt with plans to cut service by 30 percent
and eliminate 154 jobs.
   Braniff, announcing the cutbacks Monday, called them seasonal
and temporary. The airline has opened a new hub in Kansas City,
Mo., and is concentrating much of its attention there in the wake
of Eastern Airlines' recent pullout from Kansas City.
   Dallas-based Braniff returned to Orlando in January and expanded
rapidly when it acquired Florida Express Inc., a regional carrier.
Braniff had pulled out of Orlando in 1982.
   Braniff, recently acquired by investment group BIA-COR Holdings
Inc. for $100 million, employs about 600 people in Orlando. The
cutbacks take effect next month.
   ``We're trying to build some hubs that will have good sustaining
power,'' Braniff spokesman Don McGuire said. ``September is not the
time to build a hub in Orlando.''
</TEXT>
