<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Russell Adv05   08-02 1041</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Russell, Adv 05,1070</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday Aug. 5 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>George Russell: Tacoma's Close Enough To Wall Street, Thanks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A half century ago, the Russell clan left
Wall Street for the much quieter avenues of Tacoma. Today, even
though he keeps a minute-by-minute watch on New York markets,
George Russell has no desire to trade his view of Puget Sound for
Manhattan.
   Russell runs the Frank Russell Group of Companies _ named for
his grandfather _ which advises pension funds and other large pools
of capital on how to make the most money with the least risk.
   Clients include 40 of the largest U.S. corporations _ among
them, International Business Machines Corp., General Motors Corp.,
Boeing Co., Hearst Corp. and Xerox Corp. _ plus a growing number of
foreign companies, foundations, profit-sharing plans and a few very
rich individuals.
   In all, Russell clients have holdings totaling about $240
billion.
   The 56-year-old Russell pioneered the idea of tracking
performance of money managers so pension funds can rely on more
than just intuition in deciding where to entrust their assets.
   The privately held company now employs about 700 people, and has
annual revenues ``in the neighborhood of $100 million,'' Russell
says.
   He's proud of a new home office due to open in downtown Tacoma
this fall: A telescope in his current headquarters lets visitors
monitor the new building's progress. Moreover, he's proud the
company's been able to make it in Tacoma, a city that suits his
style.
   ``I had a chance to go to Wall Street, and didn't choose to get
into that herd-type thought-process,'' he said.
   ``If you're on Wall Street, what you've got is a beeper on your
belt, and if you don't answer that beeper 24 hours a day, you're
not going to get your bonus at the end of the year.
   ``We look at it quite differently, and maybe it's because we're
in Tacoma. I don't know, but it seems to me that we ought to have
the family beeper on the belt and if the family yells for help then
the person ought to go solve that problem and then come do the
business work.''
   In his line of work, things ``will never improve unless the
people that are in charge hire people that are smarter than they
are,'' Russell said.
   ``If you get the priorities in the right place to begin with as
you run a business and you put the people ahead of the business,
then they'll eventually realize they can have fun in life, too, and
the business will be fun, too.''
   Russell's office reflects his work-hard-but-have-fun beliefs.
Folding doors screen off a narrow, wall-length work area from the
rest of the room, which is filled with comfy furniture and
photographs of his family, the Northwest and his 60-foot yacht.
   The boat, he says, has entertained a lot of clients. ``If you
come to New York, you go out to a fine restauraunt. In Tacoma, your
options are different.''
   Russell defines his outfit as ``asset management consultants,''
three words that take him about 30 minutes to explain. ``This is
not an easy organization to understand,'' he conceded.
   Besides advising the 40 corporate pension accounts, the company
gathers and sells statistics on money managers, runs mutual funds
for bank trust departments, operates a brokerage house, and offers
investment funds and advice for smaller clients, including
endowments, foundations and individuals.
   It also has developed indexes for measuring stock and real
estate performance, including the Russell 2000 and Russell 3000
indexes traded on the New York Futures Exchange.
   ``If you think of a compass, we pretty much on the consulting
side are covering 360 degrees,'' Russell said.
   Doing so has brought his privately held company 25 percent
growth in each of the past 15 years, he says.
   ``The staff he's put together has been helpful to us in deciding
what we want to do in making investment decisions,'' said Al
Wolfarth, assistant treasurer for pensions at Monsanto Corp., which
has used Russell since 1974. In a field with many good companies,
Wolfarth said, ``I would refer to the Russell firm as the Cadillac
of the industry.''
   Russell's grandfather, Frank, started the company in 1936 when
he retired as a Merrill Lynch broker to come to Tacoma where his
son was a newspaper executive. He kept busy as an investment
counselor and by running a small mutual fund.
   ``All his friends were in it _ there were about 176 stockholders
and $300,000 in assets,'' George Russell said.
   Russell joined his grandfather when he graduated from Harvard
University in 1958. He took over the firm two months later when his
grandfather died.
   It prospered, with about 300 salesmen by 1965, selling mutual
funds, life insurance and real estate syndication. But, ``the fact
was that I didn't feel that we were adding any particular value,''
Russell said. ``There were a lot of people doing what we were
doing.''
   About 1968, he says, he began looking at pension accounts, which
then were usually in conservative investments and managed by one
person, ``generally selected for some political reason.'' A few
years earlier, researcher Peter Dietz, later hired by Russell, had
come up with a set of formulas for tracking pension fund
performance.
   In 1969, Russell made a cold telephone call to J.C. Penney Co.,
and sold the treasurer on a service to provide information on where
to put Penney's pension money. Penney was the first client in
Russell's core consulting company, which he limits to 40 clients.
   More cold calls and word-of-mouth advertising helped the company
grow. In 1979, Russell opened a London office and later added
offices in Sydney, Tokyo and Toronto. Each foreign office also
limits its list of clients, which include Rolls Royce and the
largest banks in Australia and Japan.
   By limiting clients, Russell says, they get better service and
he gets a stable business. In the last 19 years, there have been
only 10 changes in the list , he says.
   ``After this long time, we're quite happy,'' said client
Wolfarth. ``Don't tell George that because we try to keep them on
edge once in a while.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday Aug. 5</NOTE>
