<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-02 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean, Corn Futures Open Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most corn and soybean futures opened sharply
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade as crops continued to
bake in the heat wave gripping the drought-stricken Farm Belt.
Wheat opened slightly lower.
   Demand for soybean futures was especially strong following the
Agriculture Department's weekly crop progress survey, which found
soybean plants blooming on 76 percent of the soybean acreage in the
top 19 producing states.
   ``You're looking at most of the beans in the most critical stage
of yield determination, the pod-setting and pod-filling stage,''
said Cathy Leow, a grain market analyst in New York with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc. ``Given that, and given the adverse
weather, the bean market is showing strength.''
   But she said fears of severe yield reductions were tempered by
the National Weather Service's latest 6-to-10-day outlook, which
predicted normal rainfall and above-average temperatures in the
Midwest and the Northern Plains during the first five days of next
week.
   Wheat opened slightly lower, partly in reaction to the USDA's
rejection of China's bid for 600,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S.
wheat, analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was 3\ cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.77 a bushel; corn was 5{
cents lower to 13 cents higher with September at $3.03 a bushel;
oats were 1 cent to 9{ cents higher with September at $2.92 a
bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 31{ cents higher with August at
$8.46 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .60 cent lower to .30 cent higher with August
at 65.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .55 cent
lower with August at 78 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to
.93 cent higher with August at 45.30 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent lower to .38 cent higher with August at 32.75
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled sharply lower on Monday while pork
futures were sharply higher.
</TEXT>
