<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     08-02 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0413</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed lower today after an
early advance as fresh economic data gave traders reasons to fear
the economy may be overheating.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 7.11 to 2,123.40 at
midday.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 544 issues up, 732
down and 529 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 92.70 million shares as of noon
on Wall Street.
   The market advanced sharply on the opening and then gradually
gave back the gains in listless dealings.
   Analysts said equities initially were supported by bond prices,
which rose in reaction to the Commerce Department's monthly report
on the Index of Leading Indicators.
   While the government's chief forecasting gauge of future
economic activity shot up 1.4 percent in June, the biggest increase
in 18 months but in line with expectations, it was partially offset
by a downward revision in the May index.
   The May decrease, originally estimated at 0.1 percent, was
revised to a 0.8 percent decrease.
   Separately, the government said factory orders rose 5.5 percent
in June, far above market expecations of a 3.5 percent increase.
   ``Stocks are responding to the fact that the economy is in the
late stages of the business cycle, which will precipitate action by
the Federal Reserve'' to raise interest rates, said Alfred Goldman,
vice president at A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
   Goldman noted that volume is light, when trading in takeover
stocks and strategies to capture quarterly dividends are subtracted.
   ``This shows a lack of conviction,'' he said. ``Market
participants are hanging on every bit of economic news, but there's
no long-term investment buying coming in.''
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Texaco was up ] at 47\.
The oil giant said it would sell its 78-percent stake in Texaco
Canada. Pillsbury was up 1] at 38[; developer Donald Trump revealed
he owns 0.4 percent of the food company and is seeking to boost
that stake to 25 percent.
   Elsewhere, IBM was down | at 125|; Boeing was down [ at 62\, and
Gillette was off } at 36}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.43 to 153.09. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index stood at 305.74, down 0.97.
