<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drought-Train     08-02 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Train,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Central Anticipated Barge Problems, Was Ready for Extra
Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Central Railroad saw the drought coming
and geared up to handle the mountains of grain and coal diverted to
the rails when Mississippi River levels dropped too low for barge
traffic, railroad officails say.
   While barges were stranded in shallow water, the IC _ whose
tracks have paralleled the river for 137 years _ was chugging
along, bringing grain and coal from Illinois to the South.
   In the first 26 days of July, the IC moved 9,201 carloads of
corn and soybeans from Illinois to elevators between Baton Rouge,
La. and New Orleans _ 4,815 more carloads than in the same period
last year, the Chicago Tribune reported in today's editions.
   In the same period, coal shipments totaled 12,972 cars, an
increase of 4,361 loads, and chemical carloads were up 8,500 from a
year earlier, the Tribune reported.
   The report quoted railroad officials as saying that last spring,
before the impact of the drought was felt in the Midwest, Illinois
Central hired consultants to study water levels in the Mississippi.
   When the consultants concluded 1988 would be an extremely
difficult year for barge operators who depend on deep water to move
their towboats, the railroad began stockpiling rail cars and other
equipment, officials said.
   The preparations paid off.
   ``We've never made a profit in July since 1851,'' said Harry J.
Bruce, chairman and chief executive officer of the railroad.
   This year the carrier went beyond the ``break-even'' point,
Bruce said, though he would not indicate the exact profit.
   The railroad's consultants have said the low river levels will
last into the winter, causing ice jams to form earlier than usual,
Bruce said.
   This also will mean more business for the railroad, he said.
   ``The new business isn't the result of an aberration that just
happened since Easter,'' Bruce said.
   ``The situation has been coming on for about 10 years with the
declining water levels.''
   He said he hopes the recent traffic surge provides an
opportunity for the railroad to demonstrate to shippers that it can
handle their commodities regularly, not just when barges are
stranded.
   ``I don't want to be their fire department,'' Bruce said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
