<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Price-Lewis     08-02 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Price-Lewis,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riverside Grocery Wholesaler to be Bought by Price Club Owner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfred M. Lewis Inc., an 83-year-old
grocery wholesaler, has agreed to a $52 million buyout offer from
the parent of the Price Club retail warehouse chain.
   Lewis management has agreed to a $40-a-share tender offer for
the company's stock from the Price Co. of San Diego, Lewis
announced Monday.
   Price is interested in the Riverside company primarily for its
real estate, which includes a warehouse in Northridge suitable for
a new Price Club, said Giles Bateman, Price's chief financial
officer. Bateman said Price officials would study what to do with
the grocery distribution business.
   The deal is set to close in about six weeks.
   Lewis has warehouses in Riverside, Los Angeles, San Diego and
Phoenix, Ariz.
   The unsolicited offer from Price was made two weeks ago, said
Lewis Chairman Carl Peterson.
   Price Co. has 38 retail warehouse stores which sell food and a
variety of merchandise in no-frills settings at a discount to
members.
</TEXT>
