<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Close Mostly Higher On Hot Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade while drought-stunted crops
baked in a sizzling Midwestern heat wave.
   But forecasts for scattered showers in the Corn Belt later this
week limited gains in the potentially explosive corn and soybean
markets, and wheat closed lower on disappointing export news,
analysts said.
   ``We're quite surprised that with this heat out there, the
markets aren't doing better than they did,'' said John Frazier, a
grain market specialist in Chicago with Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   The closely watched soybean crop in the central Farm Belt is in
the midst of a critical pod-development and pod-filling stage that
will last about three more weeks, Frazier said. The soybeans need
cooler weather and moisture during that period to avoid severe
yield losses, he said.
   ``Our (soybean production) forecasts are dropping daily,''
Frazier said.
   Wheat prices fell partly in reaction to the USDA's rejection of
China's bid for 600,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat,
analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 6 cents lower with September
at $3.75{ a bushel; corn was 10{ cents lower to 11 cents higher
with September at $3.01 a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to 8{
cents higher with September at $2.90 a bushel; and soybeans were 15
cents lower to 18{ cents higher with August at $8.28 a bushel.
