<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Heck'sPlan     08-02 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heck's Plan,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholder Group Opposes Heck's Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Heck's Inc. stockholders
said Tuesday it opposed a recently filed company reorganization
plan because it dilutes its shares.
   The plan, filed late Monday, has what was described as crucial
support of the discount retail chain's creditors' committees, said
Maarten Hemsley, Heck's chief financial officer.
   ``We're excited by having accomplished this,'' Hemsley said.
``It's has been a major hurdle.''
   But Robert Miller, an attorney for the shareholders' committee,
said his group opposes the plan and called it illegal and
unfeasible.
   ``Among other things, the plan illegally denigrates the
shareholders' rights in favor of a sweetheart deal for
management,'' Miller said Tuesday.
   Heck's filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11
of federal bankruptcy laws a year ago.
   Under the 60-page plan, Heck's would issue new stock to replace
current shares. Stockholders would receive up to 10 percent of the
new stock, while about 85 percent of the shares in the reorganized
company would go to Heck's major bank and other uninsured
creditors. The remaining 5 percent would be issued to key Heck's
employees.
   The plan also calls for major creditors to gain four seats on
the reorganized, nine-member board of directors.
   The reorganization plan must be approved by U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Ronald Pearson.
   Heck's operates about 85 retail stores in West Virginia and
several surrounding states.
</TEXT>
