<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 1805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   08-02 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Persists But Jittery Grain Markets Close Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures closed mixed Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade
despite a third day of scorching heat in the Corn Belt.
   On other markets, coffee futures plunged again; cotton was
sharply lower; livestock and meat futures were mostly lower;
precious metals slipped; energy futures declined and stock-index
futures advanced.
   Corn and soybean futures settled mostly higher while wheat
finished lower in Chicago.
   But with temperatures in the Midwest again peaking near 100
degrees on Tuesday, ``we're quite surprised that with this heat out
there, the markets aren't doing better than they did,'' said John
Frazier, a grain market specialist in Chicago with Balfour Maclaine
Corp.
   Frazier said buying was limited by traders' memories of steep
losses in the soybean market during the previous two weeks and by
at least one private forecaster's prediction of widely scattered
showers in the Corn Belt during the rest of the week.
   Experts said the closely watched central Midwestern soybean crop
was in the midst of a critical pod-development and pod-filling
stage that will last about three more weeks.
   But the soybeans need cooler temperatures and more moisture to
avoid severe damage and Frazier said his company's soybean
production estimates were falling daily.
   ``As we do our crop tours, we're finding a tremendous number of
bean stalks that have very few pods if any pods at all,'' he said.
   The National Weather Service has predicted normal precipitation
and above-average temperatures for the Corn Belt during the first
five days of next week, but the market disregarded the forecast.
   ``It's difficult to make a forecast any more than four or five
days out,'' said Cathy Leow, assistant vice president in charge of
grain futures trading with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York.
   Corn and oat futures followed the soybean market while wheat
prices fell partly in reaction to news that the Agriculture
Department had rejected China's bid for 600,000 metric tons of
subsidized U.S. wheat, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 5{ cents lower with September at
$3.75{ a bushel; corn was 10} cents lower to 11 cents higher with
September at $3.01 a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 7\ cents
higher with September at $2.88} a bushel; soybeans were 15 cents
lower to 18 cents higher with August at $8.29 a bushel.
   Coffee futures plummeted for the fifth time in the last six
sessions on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange on fears that
producer and consumer nation-members of the International Coffee
Organization will be unable to come to an agreement on quotas,
analysts said.
   The September coffee contract settled 7.84 cents lower at
$1.0883 a pound, compared with $1.3295 cents a pound just one week
ago.
   Cotton futures fell to new life-of-contract lows for all
delivery months except October on the New York Cotton Exchange
after a USDA report showed the cotton crop improving, analysts said.
   October cotton settled 1.13 cents lower at 55.02 cents a pound.
   Sagging demand for beef weighed on the cattle futures market at
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, and the bearish sentiment spilled
over into the neighboring pork pits, said Dale Durchholz, livestock
analyst with AgriVisor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   Live cattle settled .28 cent to 1.33 cents lower with August at
65.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .78 cent lower
with August at 77.85 cents a pound; hogs were .57 cent lower to .35
cent higher with August at 45.32 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .37 cent to 1.90 cents lower with August at 32.15
cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices fell moderately late in the day on the New
York Mercantile Exchange on fears that Saudi Arabia will not
cooperate with other OPEC members when the cartel's pricing
committee meets Wednesday to consider measures aimed at raising
prices, said Peter Beutel, an analyst in New York with Elders
Futures Inc.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 40 cents to 55 cents
lower with September at $15.61 a barrel; heating oil was .62 cent
to .88 cent lower with September at 44.29 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .43 cent to .73 cent lower with September at 47.86
cents a gallon.
   The drop in crude oil prices weighed on the inflation-sensitive
precious metals market, pushing gold and silver futures lower on
New York's Commodity Exchange, analysts said.
   Gold settled $2.90 to $3.60 lower with August at $431.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 7.5 cents to 7.9 cents lower with September at
$6.84 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled .40 point higher at 273.05.
</TEXT>
