<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SEC-DefenseContractors     08-02 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SEC-Defense Contractors,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Reminds Contractors to Report Involvement in Pentagon Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Monday correct in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is
reminding defense contractors that federal securities laws require
them to reveal any involvement in the Pentagon procurement
investigation.
   The SEC, in a statement Monday, said, ``Companies are reminded
to consider their disclosure obligations in connection with issues
arising from the government's defense contract procurement
inquiry.''
   Securities laws requires companies to reveal to potential
investors any known factors that may hurt profits, including
investigations by government agencies.
   The reminder could flush out names of companies previously not
known to be part of the scandal.
   The SEC's statement said, ``The commission recognizes the exact
subjects and scope of the government's inquiry are still unknown.
... However, companies engaged in the defense business should
review on an ongoing basis the need for appropriate disclosure.''
   Companies file their financial statements with the SEC every
three months. Statements for the April-June quarter are due by the
middle of this month.
   Justice Department investigators are looking into allegations
that defense contractors and consultants, many of them former
military men, bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details
that could be vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   The SEC said its warning applies not only to companies that are
targets of the probe, but also to companies that would be adversely
affected by resulting changes in Defense Department procedures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
