<DOCNO> AP880802-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TradeBill 1stLd-Writethru f0238 08-02 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0238,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Continues Work On Trade Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Plant Closing Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 7-8 pvs: Byrd said, with 4 new grafs with Senate
wrapping up for night, senators upset by ethanol; pickup 9th graf
pvs: Besides giving</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders pushed Tuesday for speedy floor
action on a major trade bill only hours after President Reagan
reluctantly agreed not to veto legislation requiring companies to
provide advance notice of plant closings and mass layoffs.
   ``The president wanted a trade bill _ that's why he swallowed
the plant closings,'' said Minority Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., as
the Senate began debate on the 1,000-page bill that is intended to
curb U.S. trade deficits.
   The Senate had been waiting to act on the trade bill, which the
House passed, 376-45, on July 13. There had been an implied threat
that the trade bill might die if Reagan balked at signing the
plant-closings bill.
   Reagan vetoed an earlier version of the trade bill, largely
because it included the plant-closing provision he opposed. That
section was removed and passed separately by veto-proof margins in
the House and Senate.
   The latest version of the trade bill would give the
administration urgently sought authority to make agreements in the
current ``Uruguay Round'' of international trade talks, and would
assure accelerated congressional approval of any such deals.
   Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., expressed hope the
Senate would approve the House-passed trade bill without amendments
and send it quickly to the president for signing.
   Before recessing for the night, Byrd announced tentative plans
to vote on the bill Wednesday. But leaders failed to dissuade
senators from offering amendments. They had sought to do so as a
way of hastening the bill directly to Reagan's desk and avoiding
the potential quagmire of negotiations to resolve differences with
the House.
   There was still a chance of sending the bill directly to Reagan
but only if all amendments offered were defeated.
   Farm Belt senators attempting to strip from the bill or at least
weaken a provision that would increase duty-free imports of
Caribbean ethanol _ ethyl alcohol that is mixed with gasoline to
form the fuel gasahol. Ethanol is made from farm products and U.S.
corn growers are anxious to block further imports.
   Besides giving the administration authority to reach agreements
on modifying the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the major
pact that regulates world commerce, the bill would streamline
mechanisms for imposing import curbs to protect U.S. industries and
retaliate against trade violations by other countries.
   Other provisions range from a potential $2 billion in
agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil
industry earnings.
   The bill was largely stripped of protectionist provisions that
drew fierce opposition from the administration and a broad
coalition of ``free trade'' advocates in Congress.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Finance Committee
and the Democratic vice presidential nominee, told reporters he
would ``pursue a no-amendments strategy'' to keep the bill out of a
House-Senate conference.
   Asked about Reagan's about-face on the plant-closing notices,
Bentsen replied, ``I think he saw the polls, and I think he also
knew what was going to happen in the Senate.''
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., said he was glad to see the
plant-closings controversy resolved.
   ``I think that this issue has been a tar baby as far as
Republicans are concerned,'' Danforth said. ``That was a political
mistake. Most people in the country did not agree with the
president's position on plant closings and he finally reached the
conclusion that this was not a winner and the time had come to get
rid of the tar baby.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880802-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-88 2141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NLIndustries-Merger     08-02 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NL Industries-Merger,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NL Industries Drops Proposed Merger With Valhi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NL Industries Inc. has dropped consideration of a
proposed merger with its majority shareholder Valhi Inc., the
holding company for investor Harold Simmons, after failing to reach
a merger agreement, NL said Tuesday.
   NL Industries' board of directors plans meet Aug. 12 to review
alternatives with respect to the separation of its chemicals and
petroleum services operations and the redemption of its Series C
preferred stock, the company said.
   ``Exactly what the alternatives are, we really can't say,'' said
NL spokesman Patrick M. Murray. ``We've had some very preliminary
discussions and we'll be working through that process in next two
weeks.''
   Valhi gained control of Houston-based NL, a petroleum services
and chemical company, in a hostile takeover in 1986. It owns about
52 percent of NL's outstanding common shares and 67 percent of the
Class C shares.
   Valhi has offered to acquire NL's Series C preferred stock,
which represents the chemicals unit and was issued as a takeover
defense in June 1986, while giving common shareholders cash and
stock in a new company that would own the oilfield business.
   NL's three independent directors, who retained the right to veto
merger and acquisition plans following the hostile takeover, have
blocked Valhi's attempts to acquire the chemicals business.
   ``The issue all along has been an issue of valuation and how the
stock was valued,'' said Murray. ``It was really an issue of our
independent directors approving the proposal from Valhi, and they
did not do that. It was not whether we valued it higher or lower
than Valhi.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
